<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0728 07-08 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0728,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaigns in West With Veep Choice Uppermost</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new grafs 4-5, bgng ``Dukakis then,'' as sub for
4th graf pvs, on Dukakis in Los Angeles for baseball game, picks up
5th graf pvs, ``I think''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEXARKANA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis campaigned
Friday with Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, saying ``I'm pondering'' him
as a potential vice presidential candidate, as aides sought a new
meeting with Jesse Jackson on the same subject.
   Dukakis said as he began a Western trip into GOP territory that
he aimed to show ``this son of Massachusetts ... will not concede
one single state to the Republicans in this presidential election.''
   A senior aide traveling with Dukakis, Kirk O'Donnell,
acknowledged, however, that Dukakis' message on economic
opportunity was being obscured by attention focused on the question
of whom he would choose as his running mate. The Texas appearance
with Bentsen was similar to Dukakis campaign appearances recently
with other prospective running mates, including Sen. John Glenn in
Ohio and Rep. Lee Hamilton in Indiana.
   Dukakis then flew to Los Angeles where he went to Dodger Stadium
for Friday night's Dodger-Pirates baseball game, visited the locker
room and joined Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., in box seats along
the first-base side near home plate.
   While in Texas, Dukakis indicated at a news conference that he
favors some form of payments to the families of victims of the
Iranian airliner shot down by a U.S. warship in the Persian Gulf
last Sunday.
   ``I think some form of humanitarian assistance would probably be
appropriate,'' he said.
   He also responded to Friday's report that the national
unemployment rate had fallen to a 14-year low _ good economic news
for Bush and the Republican administration _ by saying those
figures masked economic suffering.
   ``National unemployment rates don't tell you a great deal about
what is happening in communities and neighborhoods and regions
across this country,'' he said. ``For one thing, a great many of
these jobs are low-wage jobs, many of them paying no more than
$7,000, $7,500 a year. They don't have health insurance.''
   The same report also showed Massachusetts' unemployment rate
rose, from 2.8 percent to 3.5 percent in June, dropping the state
to second place after more than four years of having the lowest
rate among the nation's most populous states. Dukakis did not
mention that change, if he knew of it, and cited the lower figure
in his remarks in Texarkana.
   Both Dukakis and Bentsen, the Senate Finance Committee chairman,
gave little detail in response to questions about vice presidential
discussions, but Dukakis acknowledged the two ``have talked from
time to time on that.''
   At the same time, Dukakis senior adviser Paul Brountas, who is
leading the Massachusetts governor's search for a running mate, was
trying to arrange a meeting with Jackson, who this week has renewed
his contention that he is the most qualified prospect. Dukakis
repeated that Jackson remains under consideration.
   With less than two weeks to go before claiming the presidential
nomination at the Democratic National Convention, when he must
settle on a running mate, Dukakis faced more questions about that
choice as he began a campaign swing aimed at challenging George
Bush in Republican areas of the Southwest, the West and Rocky
Mountain regions.
   Bentsen, who is among eight Democrats interviewed previously by
Dukakis for the job, appeared with him at a rally in front of the
Texarkana post office straddling the Texas-Arkansas border, along
with Arkansas Sen. Dale Bumpers and Gov. Bill Clinton, who will
nominate Dukakis at the Atlanta convention.
   Dukakis praised Bentsen as Finance Committee chairman and, when
asked if Bentsen would be more valuable remaining in the Senate,
replied: ``I'm pondering. He could make a great contribution in
this county in many, many ways. He already has.''
   Bentsen declined to answer most questions, but replied when
asked if he wanted the job, ``I don't think we have to worry about
that.''
   Dukakis renewed his criticism of Bush for opposing legislation
requiring 60 days notice to workers before plants are closed,
saying it is ``probably the single most dramatic example of the
difference between our parties.''
   Back in Boston, the Legislature sent to Dukakis' desk an $11.75
billion budget for fiscal 1989. Lawmakers finished a 13{-hour
debate on the budget early Friday, sending the spending plan to
Dukakis seven days after the new budget year technically began July
1.
   GOP legislators had a heydey debating the compromise budget,
which was hastily revised amid falling revenue predictions. ``This
could be the greatest gift that George Bush could receive between
now and November _ it is so absurdly out of balance,'' said
Republican Sen. David Locke, a Bush campaign official.
</TEXT>
