<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--FatalStings     07-08 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Fatal Stings,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockbroker Dies From Bee Stings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stockbroker who quit his job to open a
beekeeping business died from an allergic reaction to two bee
stings, his family said.
   Richard Nauditt, who quit his office job with Merrill Lynch in
late December, was found on June 19, Father's Day, said his wife,
Lauri Nauditt.
   ``He always wanted to own his own business, and this was
something that excited him,'' Mrs. Nauditt said recently.
   ``He had never been stung until April,'' she said. ``The week
before he died he was stung once and his finger swelled up,'' but
he didn't think anything about it.
   Nationally, 41 people died from insect stings in 1985, the last
year for which national figures are known, according to the
Washington Department of Vital Statistics.
</TEXT>
