<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Toddlers-AutoDeaths     07-08 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toddlers-Auto Deaths,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toddlers At Risk Of Being Run Over In Driveways Or Parking Lots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older children are most likely to be hit by cars
when crossing the street, but children under 5 are especially at
risk of being hit and killed in parking lots or in their own
driveways, researchers report.
   ``The `typical' pattern of injury involved a situation in which
a 1-to-2-year old child was backed over in his home driveway by a
light truck or van driven by a family member,'' the researchers
write.
   The researchers studied 71 cases in Washington state in which
children under five were hit and killed by motor vehicles, said the
study's principal author, Dr. Robert J. Brison of Queen's
University in Kingston, Ontario, Canada.
   Thirty of the 71 deaths occurred in driveways and 11 in parking
lots. The remaining 30 occurred in traffic, Brison said.
   In cases in which the kind of vehicle had been reported, 76
percent involved a light truck or van.
   ``Older children are injured and die from darting out into
traffic,'' said Brison. ``Younger children seem not to have that
pattern of injury. They seem to be injured most commonly in a home
driveway or in a store parking lot.''
   Brison, who practices emergency medicine at Kingston General
Hospital, said in a telephone interview Thursday that parents of
young children ``need to be aware of this pattern of injury, so
that they can put the children in a safe area, such as a playpen,
or pick them up'' before backing out of the driveway.
   The study by Brison, Kristine Wicklund of the Washington state
health department and Beth Mueller of the University of Washington
appears in the current issue of the American Journal of Public
Health.
   ``It's a very good article,'' said Richard Waxweiler, chief of
injury epidemiology at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta. ``And what it brings up to me as one important point is
that we mainly think of motor vehicle safety as being under the
purview of the Department of Transportation, and yet they only deal
with traffic injuries. And so they're missing these.
   ``And yet they have the jurisdiction over automobile design, for
instance, and Brison and co-authors clearly brought up that
automobile design is a potential risk factor that deserves further
investigation.''
   Brison and his collaborators suggested it might be possible to
design vehicles, especially light trucks and vans, to offer more
visibility in the rear.
   The National Center for Health Statistics says that in 1985, the
latest year for which statistics are available, 7,157 pedestrians
were killed in traffic accidents, including 401 children under 5
years old.
   Waxweiler said there were 430 pedestrians of all ages reported
killed in non-traffic situations in 1985.
</TEXT>
