<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RobinsonLawsuit     07-08 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robinson Lawsuit,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Stepbrother Sues NBC, US News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's half-brother has filed a $20
million lawsuit against NBC and a reporter at a local network-owned
television station, contending he was libeled by a report that he
had ordered a killing.
   The libel action by businessman Noah R. Robinson seeks $10
million each in damages from the network and reporter Peter Karl at
WMAQ-TV, citing reports about a December 1987 attack on a South
Carolina woman.
   WMAQ News Director Dick Reingold declined to comment on the
lawsuit Thursday, saying he had not seen it. There was no one
available to comment for NBC at the network's New York media
relations office after business hours Thursday.
   Robinson of Chicago, half-brother of the Democratic presidential
candidate, also filed a $1 million lawsuit against U.S. News and
World Report Inc. in Cook County Circuit Court on Wednesday.
   He said while the magazine reported he had been arrested by the
FBI, the federal agency did not take part in his arrest and he was
not charged with a federal crime.
   C. Thomas Dienes, general counsel for U.S. News in Washington,
D.C., said he had not seen the lawsuit and could not comment on it.
   Robinson, 45, is free on bond after his arrest June 4 in
Greenville, S.C., where he and Jackson were born, on charges of
conspiracy, intimidation of a witness, obstruction of justice and
being an accessory to a felony.
   The charges stem from the stabbing of Janice Denise Rosemond,
who survived an attack in her Greenville apartment in December 1987.
   Robinson was charged with hiring the person who attacked her,
Greenville police have said.
   Authorities have said Ms. Rosemond was a witness to the murder
of Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber, a former employee of Robinson's who
was shot in 1986 outside a building owned by Robinson.
   They said she identified the man who shot Barber, but recanted
her testimony afer she was stabbed.
   In his lawsuit against NBC-owned WMAQ-TV in Chicago, Robinson
says a June 7 report aired by the station ``falsely, wrongfully and
maliciously accused (Robinson) of having participated in the murder
of Leroy `Hambone' Barber.''
   The suit labeled the newscast ``false and untruthful in that
Janice Rosemond never told a federal grand jury or anyone else that
plaintiff (Robinson) had ordered the murder of Leroy ``Hambone''
Barber.''
   Robinson has said that the charges against him are politically
motivated, noting Jackson's presidential bid.
   Jackson and Robinson have the same father, but their
relationship has been rocky. In 1987, Jackson was quoted as saying
``I have no connection with him,'' following reports of an
investigation to determine whether Robinson had broken federal
bankruptcy laws.
</TEXT>
