<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Police-AIDSFiles     07-08 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police-AIDS Files,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Denies Keeping List Of AIDS Carriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Phoenix police chief denied Thursday
that his department maintained a computer list of suspected AIDS
carriers, although he acknowledged there were a few such notations
in the files.
   ``We do not have and we have never had a list,'' Chief Ruben
Ortega said in response to an article in The Arizona Republic
Thursday that said Phoenix police and Maricopa County sheriff's
officials both have maintained files on suspected AIDS carriers for
at least a year.
   Ortega said the department had launched an investigation to
determine how AIDS information was placed in some files. He said
the practice is unauthorized and speculated that officers who
requested AIDS information be entered into files do so because they
feel a need to warn other officers.
   Ortega denied the Republic's report that the police files were
purged of the AIDS information after inquiries were received from
the newspaper. The purge already had begun at that point, he said.
   Maricopa County sheriff's officials confirmed that they include
information on AIDS and any other contagious disease in individual
files when a person goes to jail. The information is based on what
officers are told by the inmates or on examinations, Capt. Frank
Waelde said.
   Jane Aiken, an Arizona State University law professor who
specializes in legal issues involving AIDS, said that maintaining
such files raises concerns about abuses of medical confidentiality
and the discrimination that could result.
   Bill MacDonald, chairman of the Phoenix-based Arizona AIDS
Project, a private organization, expressed similar concerns.
   ``It is outrageous that the Police Department has been carrying
that type of information in a person's records,'' MacDonald said.
``I thought there were laws that protect the rights of
individuals.''
   Mike Petchel, president of the Phoenix Law Enforcement
Association, said officers need such information for their own
safety.
   ``Personally, I think it's an area that needs to be examined for
a policy, because officers feel they may be subjected to contact
with someone carrying an infectious disease,'' Petchel said.
   The number of names in the files was not known, nor was it clear
where police obtained the names.
   Chad Butt, a 45-year-old Phoenix man, told the Republic that he
learned in May that police computer files had the phrase ``High
risk: AIDS'' next to his name.
   Butts said he was told by police that the information came
``from the health department.''
   However, officials of the Maricopa County health department and
the Arizona Department of Health Services denied releasing names of
any of the more than 2,000 AIDS carriers on file in Arizona.
</TEXT>
