<DOCNO> AP880708-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Summits Bjt   07-08 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summits, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Summits Frequently Fail To Use Leaders' Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quick. Think back to the Moscow summit. It was
only a few weeks ago.
   What did it produce?
   An end to the nuclear arms race? A Middle East agreement?
Superpower cooperation to end the Iran-Iraq war?
   None of the above.
   President Reagan, who now leads all U.S. chief executives in
superpower summits with four of them, gave his enthusiastic support
to Mikhail Gorbachev's campaign to restructure the Soviet economy.
   That was significant, and very dramatic.
   Here was the American president, a pronounced critic of
communism, in Moscow endorsing Gorbachev's perestroika program _
and blaming the bureaucracy, not the Kremlin, for violations of
human rights.
   But the agreements reached in Moscow were on the level of
fishing and maritime pacts _ not the sort of accords that require
the immense political power of the U.S. president and the Soviet
general secretary.
   Charles M. Fairbanks Jr., a scholar at the Johns Hopkins School
of Advanced International Studies, has concluded that summits
frequently fail to make effective use of the considerable authority
of national leaders.
   In a recent study, and an interview, Fairbanks said summits
frequently become occasions of drama rather than instruments of
coordinated diplomacy.
   The Moscow summit, he said, ``produced essentially nothing in
diplomatic terms. The most important thing, I think, that took
place was Reagan speaking to a Soviet audience. That probably
served a useful function. But it's certainly not the function a
summit is held out to serve.''
   Summits have come to be understood as occasions for personal
negotiations between immensely powerful political leaders. At
Reykjavik, in 1986, for instance, Gorbachev presented Reagan with a
series of historic arms control proposals.
   These included the abolition of ballistic missiles and,
possibly, all nuclear weapons.
   Normally, diplomats at lower levels work for years to reach the
point where such cosmic decisions can be made at the summit.
   ``The advantages of traditional diplomacy are that it is calm,
quiet and usually secret,'' Fairbanks writes. ``Summit conferences,
however, are very dramatic.''
   Gorbachev used the Reykjavik summit to symbolize his dedication
to arms control. It also produced pressure for concessions from
Reagan, but they were later withdrawn. The idea of banning
ballistic missiles was quickly and quietly buried only a few months
later.
   In the end, Reykjavik did not produce anything substantial.
   Because summits are so dramatic, they create a desperate need
for success. And this, Fairbanks said, gives birth to a tremendous
temptation to proclaim fictitious results.
   Reporters get sucked in. Trivia is exalted. But sometimes all
that really happened is that the two most powerful leaders in the
world met.
   Time magazine seemed to realize this in its account of the 1967
summit meeting between President Lyndon Johnson and Soviet Premier
Alexei Kosygin in Glasboro, N.J., in 1967.
   ``In the aftermath of history's first hot-line diplomacy,'' Time
reported, ``the most significant aspect of the Smalltown summit was
that it happened.''
   Then there are the summits which really produce results.
   President Jimmy Carter invited Prime Minister Menachem Begin of
Israel and President Anwar Sadat of Egypt to Camp David in 1978 and
overcame differences between the two Middle East leaders since
their own summit meeting a year earlier.
   The result was the 1979 peace treaty between Egypt and Israel.
   Reaching back into history, Fairbanks recalls the long-forgotten
summit held between Wilhelm II of Germany and Nikolai II of Russia
at B'yorkyo in July 1905.
   In terms of immediate results, he writes, ``this was perhaps the
most successful summit in history.''
   Germany signed an alliance with Russia that might have changed
the course of history.
   But even that treaty was quickly canceled.
   Nikolai's foreign minister explained to the czar that it
undercut Russia's longstanding alliance with France and had to be
discarded.
   Nine years later, Russia went to war with Germany as an ally of
France. The war devastated Russia and paved the way for the
Bolshevik revolution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid reports on diplomacy for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hastings     07-08 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Votes To Impeach Federal Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings says his
fight to remain on the federal bench is ``far from being over''
even though a House subcommittee unanimously recommended that he be
impeached.
   Hastings, Florida's first black federal judge, said from Miami
he is ``legally, morally and spiritually correct'' and the
subcommittee's 7-0 decision Thursday shows members ``do not respect
the jury system.''
   A federal jury acquitted Hastings five years ago of the bribery
charges that account for part of the criminal justice subcommittee
resolution containing 17 articles of impeachment.
   The resolution charged that Hastings conspired with a Washington
lawyer to seek a bribe from two convicted racketeers, lied during
his trial about his action and leaked information from an FBI
wiretap over which he had jurisdiction.
   The subcommittee found that Hastings committed ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' and should be impeached. The House Judiciary
Committee will decide next Thursday whether to send the resolution
to the House floor.
   If the full House impeaches Hastings, the Senate would conduct a
trial to determine whether he should be removed from office.
   Hastings' attorney, Terence J. Anderson, said he was surprised
by the unanimous vote. ``I thought there might be only five votes
against him,'' he said. ``I take it in good faith that they believe
it was an impeachable offense.''
   ``It's now time to prepare for a trial in the Senate,'' said
Anderson, echoing the thoughts of others that the unanimous vote
almost assures that the resolution will be approved by the full
committee and the House.
   Hastings said he would not step down from the bench voluntarily.
   ``It ain't over,'' Hastings said. ``It's far from being over.''
   Anderson said Hastings ``hasn't fought this battle for seven
years for a $90,000-a-year job.''
   ``It's the principle of it,'' he said.
   Anderson said, however, that Hastings may recuse himself from
cases if there is a trial in the Senate.
   ``You can't be trying cases and be running back and forth
between Washington and Miami to hear them,'' he said
   Hastings, who calls the charges politically motivated and has
insisted that he is innocent of any wrongdoing, refused to testify
on his own behalf during the subcommittee's hearings, an action
more than one member commented on. Rep. George W. Gekas, R-Pa., the
ranking Republican member, said his refusal to testify hurt him and
made for a weak defense.
   ``He didn't testify on principle,'' said Anderson. ``He
testified before a jury of his peers, under oath, and those
transcripts were available if they wanted to read them. He didn't
have to testify here.''
   In February 1983, Hastings was acquitted of charges he conspired
with Washington lawyer William Borders to receive a bribe in
exchange for modifying the sentences of two convicted racketeers.
Borders was convicted in a separate trial, was sent to prison and
has now been released.
   A month after Hastings' acquittal, U.S. District Judges W.
Terrell Hodges of Florida and Anthony A. Alaimo of Georgia filed a
complaint under the 1980 discipline law asking the 11th U.S.
Circuit of Appeals, which includes Florida, to investigate
Hastings. After a lengthy inquiry, made longer by Hastings'
challenge to the law's constitutionality, a five-member panel of
the 11th Circuit recommended that the House begin the impeachment
inquiry.
   Two years ago, U.S. District Judge Harry E. Claiborne of Nevada
became the first federal judge in 50 years to be impeached. Unlike
Hastings, Claiborne was convicted of a crime, tax evasion, and was
brought to the Senate for his trial from a federal penitentiary.
   Another House judiciary subcommittee is holding hearings on an
impeachment resolution against U.S. District Judge Walter L. Nixon
Jr., of Mississippi, who was convicted of perjury and is serving a
prison sentence. Impeachment charges were brought against Claiborne
and Nixon when they refused to resign from the bench after their
convictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Aegis Bjt   07-08 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aegis, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Powerful Aegis, `If It Flies, It Dies'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So fierce is the Navy's Aegis system, the 6
million-part, $1 billion weaponry used to down an Iranian jetliner,
that crewmen on the first Aegis ship coined the motto, ``If it
flies, it dies.''
   But some looking at Sunday's tragedy in the Persian Gulf say
unleashing the Aegis cruiser Vincennes in the tiny, crowded waters
was the equivalent of letting a pit bull protect a playpen.
   Analysts speculating on the attack conclude the cruiser's
defense system did exactly what it was supposed to: track and
destroy an apparent threat, suspected at the time to be an Iranian
F-14 fighter.
   But questions remain, like why Aegis' super-sophisticated
technology could not separate civilian from military air traffic,
or distinguish a 63-foot-long fighter from a 176-foot airliner.
   The Navy and the key Aegis contractor _ RCA Corp. of Moorestown,
N.J. _ have given only limited answers. But experts and extensive
defense literature offer some suggestions.
   The Vincennes, only the third ship to carry the technology,
relied on Aegis to discover and track an unidentified aircraft
approaching during hostilities between U.S. and Iranian forces.
   Aegis experts note that while radar consoles likely showed the
plane as hostile, it was Vincennes Capt. Will Rogers III _ not the
emotionless Aegis computers _ who gave the order to fire.
   One of two Aegis-guided SM-2 Standard missiles found its mark,
later determined to be an unarmed Airbus with 290 people aboard.
   Dr. Thomas Amlie, a former director of the Naval Weapons Center
in China Lake, Calif., said the system appears to have done
``exactly what it was supposed to do.''
   ``It worked perfectly ... unfortunately,'' said Amlie, now
employed by the Air Force.
   Aegis ships carry a complex mixture of radar, computers and
weapons to cast a protective net over a Navy task force. When the
net is penetrated, Aegis evaluates the intruder, and declares it
friend or foe.
   The system, first deployed in 1983, is said to be able to sort
out more than 200 targets from as far out as 250 miles.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, on Thursday questioned whether such a powerful system
should be deployed in the narrow gulf.
   ``The Aegis cruiser is essentially a blue-water ship that was
operating in a brown-water lake,'' said Nunn.
   But a Capitol Hill expert insisted Aegis is the world's best
naval system for fighting in close quarters. ``It gives the
commander more time to make a ponderous decision,'' said the
researcher, who asked to stay anonymous.
   The Vincennes' crew ``had about four minutes from the time they
picked up this target until it was declared hostile,'' Adm. William
J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said Sunday.
   Pentagon officials say Rogers concluded the Airbus was an enemy
based on its flight path, its failure to identify itself, and its
confusing broadcast of both civilian and military frequencies.
   The information was processed electronically into the Vincennes'
Combat Information Center, its nerve center. The windowless chamber
glows with the light of four, 42-inch-square ``battle picture''
screens and other consoles.
   They depict aircraft not as traditional radar blips, but as
graphic symbols _ white on a blue background, roughly like a
complex video game.
   While Navy officials have declined this week to let reporters
view such a display, one expert says Aegis designates planes by
showing circles around friends, diamonds around foes and squares
around unknowns.
   Like all Navy anti-aircraft systems, Aegis cannot definitively
distinguish one type of plane from another, especially when flying
head on.
   The system relies on friendly aircraft to emit, or ``squawk,''
their identities. Aegis sees all unidentified airplanes as
potential foes.
   Humans, using the system as a tool, must make the ultimate
decision.
   ``It's not designed to classify targets,'' the congressional
staffer said. ``It's just designed to detect and track them.''
   Ironically, he said, an experienced radar operator using a less
sophisticated system might have been able to tell an Airbus from a
fighter by comparing the size of blips.
   In theory, the Vincennes' control-room screens could show
civilian routes and even expected flights, experts say.
   The USS Ticonderoga, the first Aegis cruiser, acted as a ``de
facto'' control tower off Lebanon in 1983, according to its
combat-systems officer.
   The Ticonderoga's systems ``routinely'' sorted out traffic in
the potentially hostile skies, Cmdr. James McClure wrote in a
glowing 1985 review of Aegis for ``Proceedings.''
   However, during that mission, the Ticonderoga's computers
reportedly failed to see a small, incoming plane visible to the
naked eye. In 1986 hostilities off Libya, the Aegis cruiser
Yorktown targeted and shot what some analysts say was a dense cloud
on the water's surface.
   Even Crowe acknowledges Aegis has limitations. ``It has not
solved all of our problems and it does not defy the laws of
physics,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FedNominee Bjt   07-08 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fed Nominee, Bjt,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Nominee Under Fire for Alleged Tax Dodge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boston banker nominated to the Federal
Reserve Board is denying accusations that he attempted to dodge
taxes in a $2.5-million ``golden parachute'' compensation package
with the bank he heads.
   ``The tax is being paid, regardless,'' and the federal
government is losing no money, John P. LaWare told the Senate
Banking Committee. ``I'm not sure it's a dodge.''
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., chairman of the committee, saw it
differently. He noted that the $500,000-a-year deal requires the
bank _ not LaWare _ to pay a 20 percent penalty that Congress
imposed on portions of such arrangements that are considered
excessive.
   ``How do you justify such an attempt to dodge the tax code?''
Proxmire asked. He noted that Congress enacted the special penalty
in 1984 ``to discourage excessive payments which officers and
directors vote themselves'' when corporations change ownership or
control.
   LaWare repeated, ``I'm not sure a tax dodge is involved.''
   LaWare was given the special compensation package earlier this
year, just after turning 60, as part of a merger agreement that
created Shawmut National Corp. of Boston and Hartford, a bank
holding company. A banker for 35 years, he has been chairman and
chief executive officer of another Shawmut holding company since
1980.
   Under the agreement, the corporation will continue LaWare's
annual salary of about $500,000 until he is 65, even if he leaves
the bank. In addition, the bank will give him enough extra to cover
the 20 percent penalty. LaWare must pay income tax on the full
package.
   Proxmire estimated that having the bank pay the penalty was
worth $200,000 to LaWare.
   LaWare has agreed to sever all financial connections with the
bank before taking the Federal Reserve seat.
   Despite Proxmire's concerns about the financial deal, the
chairman and most other members who attended the hearing praised
LaWare. ``The president has made an excellent choice,'' said Sen.
Jake Garn, R-Utah.
   Nevertheless, there is no assurance LaWare, a Democrat, will
take a seat on the board, which controls the nation's money supply
and, thus, interest rates. That is because his confirmation would
mean that President Reagan would have filled all seven seats on the
board.
   Committee aides say some Democrats have expressed a reluctance
to seat another Reagan nominee this year, preferring to leave a
vacancy for the next president, who they hope will be Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
   Proxmire told reporters he will confer with committee members
before deciding whether the panel should vote on the LaWare
nomination this year. Should the committee recommend the
nomination, it would be up to Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd to
determine whether the Senate considers the nomination this year.
   LaWare's term would expire Jan. 31, 2002.
   The issue of monetary policy was barely mentioned at the
hearing. Most questions were about the federal budget and trade
deficits, the increasing share of U.S. debt held by foreign
investors and Third World debt.
   LaWare said he is little concerned about the fact that only one
of the world's 10 biggest banks is American.
   ``I don't think that makes much difference,'' he said. ``It's
how well-managed and profitable they are. ... I am more concerned
with the profit-and-loss statement'' than with size.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosings     07-08 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Ducks Decision on Closing Military Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has sidestepped a final decision on
one of the touchiest parochial issues faced by the 535 legislators
_ closing military installations the Pentagon says are no longer
needed.
   The House debated the issue for four hours Thursday and could
agree only that it should put off any final decision.
   ``This is not something people around here like to deal with
very much,'' admitted Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House
Armed Services Committee.
   While the House inconclusively debated, House and Senate
negotiators agreed on a Pentagon budget bill that dropped any
mention of closing bases, an issue on which the negotiators had
been trying to reach agreement. The final decision was to drop any
mention of base closings from the bill.
   Bases mean jobs, something legislators fight hard to protect,
several House members noted during Thursday's debate.
   ``It has been historically unthinkable and unworkable for the
Department of Defense to close bases because of congressional
opposition,'' said Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., ranking
Republican on the Armed Services Committee.
   In fact, congressional opposition has prevented any base
closings since 1977. But in the 16 years before then, the Pentagon
shut down 3,600 installations.
   There are about 3,800 military installations around the nation
and another 1,900 overseas, according to Aspin, who said the figure
covers facilities ranging from recruiting stations to the largest
bases.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has appointed a nine-member
commission to review which of the military installations can be
shut down. That panel is meeting now, and Pentagon officials have
said that between $2 billion and $5 billion annually could
eventually be saved.
   The commission is scheduled to make its recommendations by Dec.
31 and President Reagan would then have two weeks, or shortly
before he leaves office, to either accept or reject the entire list.
   The House is considering two separate bills that would implement
the commission's decisions.
   One, sponsored by Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, provides that the
commission's recommendations would take effect unless both the
House and Senate vote to reject them.
   The second, backed by a trio of House committees, provided that
the recommendations only take effect if both chambers vote in favor
of them. But the House voted 250-138 approval Thursday of an
amendment to the committee-backed bill, a change that provides the
closures will go ahead unless both chambers vote to block them.
   That modified the bill to make it similar to the Armey plan and
provided a test of sentiment, according to Aspin.
   Then the chamber adjourned, following its normal pattern of not
doing business after Thursday afternoon, which allows west coast
members to return home for a weekend of re-election campaigning.
   Rep. Dave McCurdy, D-Okla, said closing bases ``is certainly one
of the toughest political issues we face.''
   Until 1975, Congress had placed few obstacles in the way of
Pentagon base closure plans. But when the Air Force proposed
shutting down Loring Air Force Base in northern Maine that year,
Congress blocked the procedure. One requirement ordered lengthy _
and costly _ environmental impact studies for the Loring closing
and all future closings.
   House approval of the base-closing bill would send it directly
to a conference committee with the Senate, which approved its own
plan two months ago. The package was dropped out of the Pentagon
budget bill in order to give the House time to decide what it
wanted to do, according to Senate leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Airliner-Explanations     07-08 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Explanations,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>As Facts Emerge, Pentagon's Explanations Shift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Pentagon pieces together more
information about what happened in the haze over the Persian Gulf
on Sunday, it has been revising its explanations of the shooting
down of an Iranian airliner by a U.S. warship.
   Starting with what type of plane was shot down _ the Pentagon
originally said it was an F-14 jet fighter, not a commercial
airliner _ the Pentagon has gone on to revise its account of
whether it was in the commercial air corridor, at what altitude it
was flying and what sort of signals it was transmitting.
   ``We all of us probably know a lot more about that situation now
than the captain of the ship did,'' Defense Department spokesman
Dan Howard told reporters Thursday at an 80-minute briefing devoted
almost entirely to the shooting.
   Still, he said, much remains unknown and the full, official U.S.
explanation will have to await the report of a Navy investigating
team, now in the gulf area, that is expected to complete its report
in two or three weeks.
   From the beginning, the affair has been marked by confusion as
officials and reporters groped for information in the highly
technical world of air-and-sea battle in the 1980s.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WHAT TYPE OF PLANE WAS IT?</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's first announcement, issued within hours after the
2:51 a.m. EDT incident Sunday, said the plane shot down by the
cruiser Vincennes was an Iranian F-14 ``approaching in a hostile
manner.''
   At 1:30 p.m. EDT Sunday, however, Adm. William Crowe, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, appeared at a hastily called news
briefing and confirmed Iranian reports that the plane was in fact a
civilian airliner.
   Pentagon sources said U.S. military leaders changed their mind
after an analysis of intelligence data showed an A300 Airbus had
been found in the waters of the gulf and no Iranians warplanes were
flying in the area at the time.
   One source said the intelligence collected after the incident
included radio signals from airplanes and ground stations as well
as a limited and not always reliable network of informers on the
ground.
   In his Sunday briefing, Crowe stressed that the information he
was giving was ``based on the information currently available'' and
was subject to correction later.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WAS IT IN THE COMMERCIAL CORRIDOR?</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The suspect aircraft was outside the prescribed commercial air
corridor,'' Crowe said, in a statement that became a subject of
dispute in the ensuing days.
   On Wednesday, according to congressional sources, Navy briefers
told House and Senate members that the airliner was inside the
20-mile wide corridor assigned to commercial airliners flying
between the Bandar Abbas airfield and Dubai.
   Howard said Thursday the aircraft was about 4{ miles ``outside
the normal flight path,'' which he said veteran air traffic
controllers had told him was the center line of the corridor.
   The width of such commercial air corridors varies. Although they
are 20 miles wide in Iran, they are eight miles wide in the United
States and there have been suggestions to make them narrower,
Howard said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>WAS THE PLANE DESCENDING?</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In another statement that has been called into question, Crowe
said Sunday that the airplane was ``decreasing in altitude as it
neared the ship.'' He said that it was at 7,800 to 9,000 feet when
it was hit.
   Data from the frigate USS John H. Sides, which was in the same
area, indicated that the plane was at 12,600 feet and either steady
or ascending.
   Howard said Thursday that the altitude reported for the plane by
air traffic controllers at Dubai, United Arab Emirates, was similar
to that given by Crowe and that if the altitude were as different
as reported by the Sides, the missile would not have hit the
airplane.
   He conceded, however, that authorities do not know whether the
missile scored a direct hit or merely exploded somewhere within
lethal range of the aircraft.
   Crowe also said Sunday that the aircraft ``neither answered nor
changed its course'' after being given warnings by the Vincennes on
both military and civilian frequencies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DID IT TRANSMIT MILITARY SIGNALS?</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At his briefings Tuesday and Thursday, Howard said the Vincennes
received signals from the airplane in modes common to civilian,
commercial and military aircraft and could not tell from the signal
whether the plane was civilian or military.
   Both times, Howard said this was not inconsistent with the
version given by Crowe, who said there were ``electronic
indications on (the) Vincennes that led it to believe the aircraft
was an F-14.''
   After the congressional briefing Wednesday, Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, said
signals received by the Vincennes were identical to those emitted
earlier by Iranian F-14s from Bandar Abbas, leading to speculation
that they did not come from the airliner.
   Howard, however, said that such speculation was based on a
discussion of remote possibilities and that almost certainly
``there is no phantom aircraft there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
