<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Energy-Water     07-08 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Energy-Water,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Expected To OK Energy, Water Development Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is expected to sign a $17.8
billion package for energy and water development programs _ a bill
whose timely passage made it something of a legislative oddity.
   The measure, sent to the White House on Thursday following 91-3
approval by the Senate, is the first regular appropriations bill
for the coming fiscal year to clear Congress.
   For the past two years, lawmakers have rolled the 13 regular
bills into huge omnibus packages called continuing resolutions.
   If the energy and water legislation is signed by Reagan, it
would be the first regular spending bill to get a presidential
signature since December 1985.
   The bill is expected to get his approval. It is one of the few
fiscal 1989 appropriations bills wending their way through Congress
that has not drawn a veto threat.
   The legislation is a hold-the-line plan containing few new
initiatives and, lawmakers say, not one dime to allow the Army
Corps of Engineers and Bureau of Reclamation to begin building any
new dams, harbor and irrigation projects next year.
   Another casualty is the superconducting super collider, which
was refused the $350 million the administration sought to begin its
construction. Instead, Congress voted $100 million for more
preliminary planning for the high-energy physics research project.
   Leaders of the House and Senate appropriations committees said
the next president should make the decision on whether to commit
the nation to building the multibillion-dollar project.
   The legislation would give the corps $11 million less in fiscal
1989, which begins next Oct. 1, than it is now getting. The bureau
would get $40 million more. Both agencies would have money to
continue work on more than 200 existing construction projects, but
at a slower pace in a number of cases.
   The Energy Department would get about two-thirds of the $17.83
billion, with $8.1 billion earmarked for the nuclear activities it
conducts on behalf of the Department of Defense.
   There is $3 million in the bill to bolster federal research into
the ``greenhouse effect,'' which some scientists say is a dangerous
global warming trend caused by mankind's overloading the atmosphere
with gases like carbon and fluorocarbons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
