<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FugitiveCaptured     07-08 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Captured,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escaped Murder Suspect, Stopped By Trooper, Flees, Is Recaptured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Carolina prison escapee wanted in
a Florida murder spree was captured late Thursday after eluding
more than 50 searchers through woods, car lots and a lake bank for
two hours.
   Officers said they captured Thomas Anthony Wyatt, 24, of North
Wilkesboro, N.C., about 10:15 p.m. at a car lot on S.C. 200, the
same road on which he was pulled over in a traffic stop two hours
earlier.
   He escaped May 13 in his green prison work garb from the Wilkes
County Prison Unit, where he was being held for questioning in
connection with the Florida murders of three Domino's Pizza workers
and a Tampa woman May 17.
   Wyatt's partner in the escape, Michael Gene Lovette, 29, of
Statesville may still be at large, The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer
reported. Charlotte is the major city between Lancaster County, in
north-central South Carolina, and Wilkes County, several hours'
drive north in the western North Carolina mountains.
   An unidentified man who was with Wyatt in the pickup truck
pulled over by Highway Patrol Trooper E.S. Robinson Thursday
evening was being held in the Lancaster County Jail after he gave a
false name, officers said.
   Robinson held the unidentified man after Wyatt fled while the
trooper checked the truck's tag number, verifying it was stolen.
   More than 50 Lancaster sheriff's officers, FBI and state agents
and their bloodhounds traced Wyatt's steps through woods, around
homes and a series of car lots.
   Intermittently, residents reported a man in gray sweat pants in
the area, asking for a ride and roaming in a used-car lot. When
officers captured Wyatt, he was wearing gray jogging pants.
</TEXT>
