<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Election-Tacos     07-08 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Election-Tacos,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Tacos' Stuffed With Fraudulent Ballots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Taco'' took on a new meaning on
election day in Mexico, when fraudulent voters folded a ballot in
half like a tortilla, filled it with other votes and stuffed it
into ballot boxes.
   As opposition parties in this northern industrial center
denounced widespread fraud in presidential elections, local
newspapers reported Thursday that the ``taco'' tactic of vote
rigging was well planned and favored the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party.
   The party, known as the PRI, claimed victory in Wednesday's
presidential election with candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   About 50 ballots make a fine ``taco.'' Discovering ``tacos'' and
revealing the ``taqueros,'' people who stuff ballot boxes, became
an election day frenzy for the media and opposition political
parties.
   The daily newspapers El Porvenir and El Norte reported Thursday
that their reporters passed themselves off as laborers or labor
union supporters to gain access to ``taco'' operations.
   The papers named the Mexican Labor Federation and the
Revolutionary Federation of Workers and Peasants, two of the
largest unions in the country and important arms of the PRI, as
prime ``taqueros.''
   ``El Porvenir reporters who passed themselves off as workers
from both unions formed part of the brigades of voters, verifiying
the introduction of so-called tacos,'' El Porvenir reported.
   ``Tacos Tarnish Elections,'' read a headline in El Norte.
   A teachers' union sponsored classes on how to use ``tacos,'' El
Norte reported.
   El Norte's Francisco Betancourt reported that he convinced the
Revolutionary Federation he wanted to help stuff ballot boxes.
   He said he went to the union's headquarters on election day and
was among those given ``packets of ballots already marked in favor
of the PRI.''
   Betancourt said he was driven along with other ``taqueros'' to a
precinct, but fled before doing anything illegal. He turned his
``taco'' in at El Norte.
   El Porvenir said one of its reporters, Jose Juan Olvera, was
discovered trying to pass himself off as a Revolutionary Federation
``taquero'' and ``received a punch in the face.''
   But union spokesman Isaias Vazquez said in a telephone interview
that the union ``at no time attacked any reporter and neither did
it promote the violation of electoral laws. Yes, we had tacos, but
they were of the corn and flour kind.''
   Olga Roman, a secretary at Mexican Labor Federation
headquarters, said union spokesmen were out of the office and
unavailable for comment.
   The newspapers and opposition parties alleged many other types
of voter fraud, including people voting more than once, refusals to
allow opposition poll watchers into polling places and ballot boxes
already filled before voting began.
   In Chihuahua, meanwhile, the main opposition party, National
Action, complained of widespread irregularities, including the
elimination from voter rolls of thousands of its sympathizers.
   The party's strength is in the northern state's two large
cities, the city of Chihuahua and Ciudad Juarez across the border
from El Paso, Texas.
   In many of the precincts checked by journalists late Wednesday
as the votes were being tallied, the difference in favor of
National Action was as little as 20 to 40 votes.
   Hundreds of sympathizers carrying their voting cards showed up
at party headquarters to complain their names did not appear on the
voter rolls. There were no similar reports by PRI sympathizers.
   ``This is a dictatorship,'' said Leopoldo Corral, who complained
he had waited for hours only to be told he could not vote.
   Electoral Commission president Miguel Etzal Maldonado blamed the
elimination of names from the voter rolls on ``technical
failures.'' Gov. Fernando Baeza said they were ``natural human
errors.''
   PRI officials declined to release any election figures in the
state and said the Electoral Commission would have official results
on Sunday.
</TEXT>
