<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Government     07-08 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Government,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Accepts Resignation of New Health Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's health minister, who has come under fire
for controversial statements on AIDS testing and drug addiction,
has resigned after nine days in office, Premier Michel Rocard's
office announced.
   Rocard had asked for Leon Schwarzenberg's resignation, saying
the respected cancer specialist infringed on a ``code of ethics''
by making controversial statements despite the premier's request
that new ministers refrain from making broad policy announcements.
Schwarzenberg resigned Thursday.
   In a news conference Tuesday, Schwarzenberg proposed systematic
testing of pregnant women for AIDS. He declined to say whether the
tests should be mandatory.
   Health policy under former conservative Minister of Health
Michele Barzach specifically opposed mandatory AIDS testing, a
position that received broad public support.
   Pregnant women in France are routinely tested for AIDS, but only
at the discretion of individual physicians.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   Schwarzenberg also advocated the distribution of drugs, under
certain conditions, to drug addicts through French hospitals. The
plan provoked a heated response from many French doctors and
politicians.
   The new health minister was one of several ``civil''
appointments to a Socialist Cabinet that Rocard has tried to
broaden by including centrists and non-politicians.
   Integrating the new personalities into the government has proven
difficult. On Wednesday, Rocard was forced to reverse a policy
statement made a day earlier by Justice Minister Pierre
Arpaillange, who recommended changes in the policy governing
solitary confinement of some prisoners convicted of murder,
including terrorists. Arpaillange did not provide details on his
plan.
   Following an outcry in the National Assembly and in the press,
Rocard announced that after consulting with Arpaillange, a
respected jurist, present solitary confinement practices would
remain in effect.
</TEXT>
