<HEAD>British Tourist Gets Three Months For Tearing Up Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British tourist was sentenced to three
months in jail for tearing up $11 worth of Kenyan banknotes at a
Nairobi airport, a newspaper reported.
   Edward James Lewin admitted mutilating six notes, worth $11, at
the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport departure lounge on Tuesday
night, The Standard newspaper reported Thursday.
   Lewin was about to catch a flight home to London when security
police found the money on him and advised him to change it into
foreign currency, the paper said.
   But Lewin angrily tore up the notes, bearing the portrait of
President Daniel arap Moi, it said.
   ``Tourists need to respect this country,'' Chief Magistrate
Joseph Mango said Wednesday when he sentenced Lewin.
   Lewin said he was drunk and did not realize what he was doing.
   The airport had posted notices warning travelers that it is an
offense to mutilate Kenyan banknotes.
