<DOCNO> AP880708-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     07-08 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Needs To Reveal More About His Personality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush says he has to do a
better job of telling Americans ``what makes me tick inside'' while
voters need to learn where Democratic rival Michael Dukakis really
stands on the issues.
   The vice president complained Thursday that one recent poll
found that two-thirds of the people believed Dukakis was more
conservative than Bush. ``There's something wrong with that,'' Bush
said. ``The issues are not in focus. ... I honestly believe that
the country doesn't yet fully appreciate where the governor stands
... on a lot of key issues.''
   Bush, certain to be the Republican presidential nominee, made
his observations during a foray into Dukakis' home turf of Boston,
where he spoke before a Greek-American audience whose political
sympathies could be expected to rest with Dukakis.
   However, the audience of several thousand people gave Bush a
surprisingly warm reception.
   The vice president said it had been a smart idea to have him and
Dukakis speak on separate days. ``Too much charisma can be
dangerous to your health,'' Bush joked.
   Today, the vice president flies to Atlanta for a pep talk to a
Republican unity dinner in the same city where Dukakis will claim
the Democratic presidential nomination this month.
   At a news conference Thursday, Bush said he has not done a
sufficient job telling the nation what kind of person he is.
   He said: ``I've not felt too comfortable talking about the
private side of the Bush family and all of that _ what it means to
me, the loss of a child, whatever it might be.
   ``I now have concluded that I have to make clear what makes me
tick inside.''
   Referring to a speech Wednesday before a Hispanic audience in
which he talked at length about his life, Bush said, ``I was trying
to say, look, I understand this, here's what motiviates me, here's
the inner side.''
   He jokingly said he ``wasn't trying to draw a contrast that
we've got 12 grandchildren and he's (Dukakis) working for one.''
However, Bush's wife, Barbara, quickly corrected him on the number
of grandchildren, and the vice president said, ``Make that 10.''
   Talking about the campaign, Bush said he would ``be positive,''
outlining his views, while surrogates focus on Dukakis' record and
what they feel are its shortcomings, ``factually, without venom,
without vendetta.''
   Nevertheless, Bush said he had ``an enormous difference on
taxes'' with Dukakis. The vice president said he opposed new taxes
while Dukakis recently oversaw an increase in cigarette taxes in
Massachusetts.
   Bush also suggested he would do a better job than Dukakis in the
area of foreign affairs.
   The vice president said he would talk about ``who has the most
experience, who best (is qualified) to sit down with Mr. (Mikhail)
Gorbachev, (the leader of the Soviet Union), what administration
has achieved the only arms control agreement in the nuclear age to
eliminate an entire category of weapons when some were sitting up
here saying `Freeze, freeze,' lock in Soviet superiority with a
thousand warheads and zero for the United States.''
   Bush flew to Boston after a political strategy session with
President Reagan at the White House.
   In a break with tradition, Bush likely will campaign for votes
and try to divert attention from Dukakis during the Democratic
National Convention, which runs July 18-21.
   Sheila Tate, the vice president's press secretary, said
schedulers were looking at events on Monday and Tuesday of
convention week, followed by appearances Friday and Saturday after
the convention closes.
   Usually, the presidential candidates allow each other to have
all the limelight during their conventions, and expect the same
courtesy in return.
   Yet Bush, who has trailed in many polls until just recently,
said he probably would do some political travel during Dukakis'
convention.
   On the one hand, Bush said, ``we'd just get a little bit of
ink'' by being on the road.
   On the other hand, he said, ``you don't want to look like you're
trying to frantically elbow your way into the news cycle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
