<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Death     07-08 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Death,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Death Penalty For Drugs, Trafficking In Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament has approved the death
penalty for people convicted of drug offenses or trafficking in
women, the government announced today.
   The action was taken late Thursday by the 300-seat Parliament,
in which President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's ruling Jatiya Party
has a four-fifths majority.
   Ershad was expected to sign the new laws quickly.
   The legislation sets a minimum penalty of seven years in jail
and a maximum penalty of death for drug-related crimes. Earlier,
the maximum sentence was 10 years in jail.
   There had been no law against trafficking in women, which has
been an increasing problem in Bangladesh.
   Police and border guards say that more than 4,000 women have
been rescued from being taken illegally across the border into
India this year.
   The security forces say the women are lured with promises of
jobs outside Bangladesh, but often end up sold into prostitution.
   The new women's protection law sets a minimum penalty of seven
years in jail for traffickers and a maximum of death.
   Prime Minister Moudud Ahmed told the Parliament that the new
laws would act as a deterrent to crimes involving drugs and against
women.
   ``Let us hope we are not required to apply the laws,'' he said.
</TEXT>
