<HEAD>Atlanta Labor Dispute Settled, Won't Disrupt Delegate Lodging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party officials are breathing a sigh
of relief that a labor dispute which had threatened to leave about
1,000 delegates to the party's national convention without their
hotel rooms has been settled.
   ``We're out of the pup-tent business,'' said Peter Kelly,
chairman of the California delegation, which had 700 rooms reserved
at the Atlanta Hilton & Towers, site of the dispute.
   The delegation, along with those from Louisiana, Tennessee and
Wyoming, had decided they would not cross picket lines, which
members of the International Brotherhood of Firemen and Oilers had
said they would form if their contract dispute could not be
resolved.
   Hilton General Manager Andre Shaefer said a one-year agreement
had been reached, but declined to give details.
   ``We came to an agreement, and that means no picketing,''
Shaefer said. ``It's something we didn't want.''
