<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Flooding,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Called Out To Rescue Flood Victims, Toll Rises To 91</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army was called out today to help
rescue an estimated 4 million people stranded by flooding as the
death toll in five days of monsoon rains reached 91, officials and
newspapers said.
   At least 27 people were killed Thursday as floodwaters spread
from the country's northeast into the southeast district of
Chittigong, the Bengali-language newspapers Ittihad and Sangbad
reported today.
   Two of the victims Thursday were reported drowned in Chittigong.
All the earlier victims were in the northeast, along the Indian
border.
   Army units began moving into flooded areas today after the
cabinet decided the night before to call out the force, said
officials at the Flood Control Ministry who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The Bengali-language newspapers said 4 million people were
marooned, many trapped atop their homes or even in trees. Thousands
of mud-and-thatch houses have been washed away by the surging
waters, the papers said.
   About 50,000 people have been moved to 20 relief centers in
schools and other public buildings, the papers reported.
   Iqbal Hossain Chowdhury, a government official supervising
rescue work in the town of Sunamganj, said by telephone that 90
percent of the northeastern town was under water.
   ``This seems to be an unprecedented flood in recent memory,'' he
said.
   Bangladesh, a largely lowland nation of 105 million people, is
regularly inundated as its many rivers overflow during the monsoon.
Last year, 1,200 people were killed in flooding.
</TEXT>
