<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   07-08 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0831,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Stock Prices Gain In Early Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices, comment from
analysts; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against the Japanese yen at the
close of the trading week Friday, while stocks advanced.
   After opening at 131.95 yen, the dollar closed trading only
slightly higher at 131.97 yen, down 0.33 yen from Thursday's close
of 132.40. It traded mainly between 131.90 yen and 132.60 yen
during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 38.47-point loser Thursday, advanced 188.95
points, or 0.68 percent, to close the week at 27,917.08.
   The dollar overcame an early, speculative sell-off to recover in
morning dealings. On Monday the currency hit 134.85 yen, its
highest closing rate since Nov. 24.
   ``It recovered after opening lower on the tail of a weaker
currency in New York and is coming up little by little,'' said a
currency dealer with a major Tokyo commercial bank.
   ``But dollar-buying was countered by speculative selling and
that affected the currency's rise,'' said the dealer, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Others said the dollar came under pressure as investors reacted
to a comment late Thursday by Japan's Trade Minister Hajime Tamura.
   Tamura, speaking to a group of foreign reporters in Tokyo,
denied reports of a clandestine U.S.-Japan agreement to prop up the
dollar for political reasons.
   Tokyo currency dealers have said that Japanese and U.S. monetary
authorities are favoring a higher dollar for mainly political
reasons.
   According to currency analysts, a stronger dollar would pave the
way for more latitude in managing monetary policy, reducing fears
of inflation, circumventing higher interest rates and ensuring the
health of U.S. financial markets.
   Such developments would likely increase the chances of a
Republican Party victory in the November presidential polls, they
said.
   In stock market dealings, security houses were traded along with
pharmaceuticals and retailers, while steelmakers and heavy
industries were generally down.
</TEXT>
