<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Art     07-08 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Art,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Soviet Style: Foreigners Flock To Nation's First Art
Auction</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1974, Vladimir Nemukhin and Bela Levikova
helped organize an outdoor art show that drew cool reviews from KGB
agents, who bulldozed the artwork.
   On Thursday, the two Soviet artists displayed their work at the
country's first international art auction, an unlikely event that
raked in $3.6 million from a flock of art-loving foreigners.
   About 2,000 people crowded into a hall at the International
Trade Center for the auction organized by Sotheby's of London. In
two hectic hours, 120 works of art were put up for bids.
   The event drew more than a little curiosity in a country where
prices usually are regulated by bureacrats.
   ``Maybe money is a bad standard for merit, but it's a worldwide
standard,'' said Nikolai Filatov, a Ukranian-born artist who had
two works sold.
   Art that deviated from the principles of Socialist Realism once
met with the Kremlin's disdain. KGB agents used dump trucks and
bulldozers to literally crush the exhibition that Nemukhin and
Levikova helped organize in a Moscow park 14 years ago.
   Bids at the auction were taken from the 1,000 people in the
audience, as well as by telephone and through written offers
submitted in advance.
   Because payment in British pounds was required, Soviets in
theory were excluded from taking part in the auction, since it is
illegal for them to hold foreign currency.
   But they made their feelings known, applauding when a
contemporary work fetched more than $400,000, and when paintings by
Ilya Glazunov, an artist with high-level official support, failed
to sell for their minimum estimated value.
   The total bids was $3.6 million, which Sotheby auctioneer Simon
de Pury said ``exceeded our wildest expectations.''
   London art dealer David Juda won a fierce bidding war with a
$567,000 offer for Alexander Rodchenko's ``Line,'' a 1920 oil
painting that depicts a white line zigzagging across a matte black
canvas.
   ``That was my very last bid,'' Juda said. ``I don't think I paid
too much _ but maybe I did.''
   In all, 18 works by artists from before World War II were
auctioned off. But the bulk of the works on sale was by
contemporary artists.
   One 1986 work, ``Fundamental Lexicon'' by Moscow-born Grisha
Bruskin, sold for $416,000, which de Pury said was a record for a
modern Soviet artist.
   Gowrie said rockstar Elton John had bid $75,000 for a blue-hued
landscape by modern Soviet painter Svetlana Kopystianskaya, and the
same sum for a portrait by her husband, Igor Kopystiansky.
   Juda, a veteran of art auctions, said he though Western interest
in Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev reforms had caused a new
curiosity in Russian art, but that the price level at the auction
had been ``extremely high.''
   The artists get 60 percent of the sale price, the Soviet
Ministry of Culture receives 30 percent and Sotheby's gets 10
percent.
</TEXT>
