<2ND_LINE>PM-Starr's Son,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Son of Ex-NFL Star Bart Starr Found Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 24-year-old son of former Green Bay
Packers quarterback Bart Starr had been dead up to four days before
his body was found by authorities summoned to the locked home by
his father, police said.
   The remains of Bret Michael Starr were unrecognizable, said
Hillsborough County sheriff's spokesman Jack Espinosa, adding that
it took authorities more than four hours Thursday to make a
positive identification.
   There were no signs of a struggle in the house or trauma to the
body, no bullet or stab wounds and no indication of foul play,
police said.
   The county medical examiner planned to conduct tests today to
determine how he died, said Jack Hall, forensic investigator. He
was unsure how soon results would be available.
   ``The place was locked up tight. The body was lying on the floor
in a dining area that opened into a back yard. It had been there an
estimated two to four days and the air conditioning was off,''
Espinosa said.
   Authorities gave no indication that drugs were involved, but the
elder Starr wrote about his son's drug problems in his
autobiography, ``My Life in Football: Starr.''
   ``Unbeknownst to us, by the time Bret graduated from high
school, he was well on his way to a cocaine addiction,'' the book
says, noting that the younger Starr had trouble dealing with his
father's fame.
   Starr went to see his son at his house in Carrollwood Thursday
morning but couldn't get in. Struck by a foul smell, he went for
help.
   Starr and a deputy who returned with him obtained a key from the
landlord but had difficulty entering the house because of two
Rottweiler dogs inside. They were removed by animal control
officers.
   Bret Starr moved to Tampa in late 1984 and was part owner of a
wholesale exotic fish and reptile importing company called Gulf
Coast Fisheries.
</TEXT>
