<HEAD>Jackson Keeps Pushing For Veep Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says it would provide
balance to the Democratic presidential ticket if he were offered a
spot as Michael Dukakis' running mate.
   ``His ancestors came over on an immigrant ship. Mine came over
on a slave ship. That's balance,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson, who will go to the Democratic National Convention on
July 18 with more than 1,100 delegates, said he deserves to be
considered for the vice presidential nomination.
   ``There are several people under consideration, which is
appropriate, but then some one must be chosen based upon some known
standards. I want to know what those standards are and if I have
the best qualifications, obviously I should be selected. And if I
do not, I should not,'' he said.
   Jackson spoke at the Monumental Baptist Church in Memphis to
about 100 supporters, including two dozen of his convention
delegates.
   Jamillah Muhammad, southern regional co-ordinator for the
Jackson campaign, said the meeting was set up for state campaign
leaders from Tennessee, Mississippi, Alabama and Georgia who were
unable to attend an earlier gathering of their colleagues in
Washington, D.C.
   ``Most of the delegates wanted a chance to see him in a smaller
more intimate setting before the convention,'' she said.
   Jackson was leaving Memphis today and traveling to Dallas for a
meeting with Dukakis aides, his campaign said.
   Jackson described himself as a proven leader who has played a
major role in setting the party's agenda on social issues.
   ``The issue is not what do I want but what have I built,'' he
said. ``I've built a coalition of serious people throughout America
who want to make America better and keep America strong.''
   Noting that the Democratic party has never placed a black
candidate on the presidential ballot, Jackson told the delegates,
``We must break with tradition.''
