<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Enforcement     07-08 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Enforcement,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Water Cops & Tattle-Tale Neighbors Enforce Water Conservation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Farmer, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Water wasters in Grand Rapids, Mich., now can go to jail for 90
days, Oak Brook, Ill., residents have had their water cut off for
oversprinkling their lawns, and a switchboard in Columbus, Ohio, is
being bombarded with calls from people snitching on neighbors for
using too much water.
   Water police are on patrol in growing numbers as communities hit
by drought are resorting to desperate measures to conserve water.
Record heat in many areas is increasing the demand for water just
when supplies are running low.
   On Thursday, angry residents of Columbus flooded the city's
Water Division switchboard with calls accusing their neighbors of
violating the city's new ban on lawn sprinkling and filling
swimming pools. Officials hope the crackdown will reduce
consumption by about 50 million gallons a day, down from the
current average of 170 million.
   A Water Division spokeswoman said repeat violators of the ban
which took effect Thursday faced fines up to $100 and shutoff of
their water service.
   ``The biggest response we're seeing is people calling in
violators,'' said Jackie England, public information manager for
the Water Division. ``We're getting inundated by calls. We are
taking addresses and we are going to follow up.''
   She said 50 addresses were reported just half an hour after the
switchboard opened. ``The first call at 8:01 was a woman who had 20
addresses,'' she said.
   A Columbus radio station said its traffic reporter saw three
high schools sprinkling football fields and reported it to school
officials. The sprinkling quickly stopped.
   In Georgia, it's not the people but whole counties in trouble
over water.
   Gwinnett and Cobb counties, both suburbs of Atlanta, were each
fined $75,000 this week by the state Department of Natural
Resources for exceeding their June water allotments and told they
have to cut back.
   The counties protested that the limits were unreasonable because
their populations have grown, to a combined total of around
600,000, since the limits were set. State resources Commissioner J.
Leonard Ledbetter offered to take the counties to court if they
don't comply.
   Oak Brook, Ill., also has patrols on the lookout for people
sprinkling lawns when they shouldn't.
   Tom Lane, acting superintendent of public works in the Chicago
suburb of Oak Brook, said Thursday that 30 violators of the
community's restrictions on lawn sprinkling have had their water
shut off since limits were enacted by law June 18.
   ``We have public works and water department men on the street 24
hours a day, along with police'' to catch violators, said Lane. A
second violation prompts a water shutoff, and the price of getting
water turned back on is $200, he said.
   ``We have had several people (call) outraged'' about the
restrictions, Lane said. ``But we've got people calling on each
other now. They figure if they've been cited and cut off, why
shouldn't someone else?''
   Police Capt. Howard E. Rupard has traveled a beat in Lexington,
Ky., for 28 years watching for burglars, vandals and rowdies. Now,
he faces a new kind of criminal _ the water ordinance violator.
   ``I've had many, many other experiences,'' Rupard said, ``but
never with water.''
   It's been neighbor against neighbor in Lexington since the city
went on a water alert Friday. A judge can impose fines up to $250.
   Rupard and another officer recently found a fast food restaurant
still under construction that had a dozen sprinklers firing away.
   Representatives of the store said they hadn't heard of the
ordinance but wanted to comply. One problem was that the sprinklers
were automatically programmed. ``It took me 20 minutes to figure
out how to turn it off,'' said store manager Paul Marcinek.
   Grand Rapids, Mich., put extra-sharp teeth in its water
conservation law. Residents were put under a lawn sprinkling
restriction Thursday that could result in a 90-day jail term and a
$500 fine for violators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
