<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Handicapped,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200 Handicapped People Stage Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 handicapped people in
wheelchairs and on crutches demonstrated in downtown Seoul,
demanding the cancellation of the ``Paralympics,'' the special
Olympics for disabled athletes to be held in Seoul this year.
   ``Cancel the Paralympics,'' the disabled protesters shouted
Thursday as they tried to march into the streets. Hundreds of
helmeted riot police blocked the way.
   The protesters, many in wheelchairs and on crutches, punched at
police as they tried to break through the cordon. Police did not
react and just blocked the march by interlocking shields.
   The demonstrators said it is ``shameful'' for South Korea to
hold the special Olympics while failing to provide sufficient
welfare facilities for tens of thousands of the disabled in the
country.
   The ``Paralympics'' in Seoul are scheduled for Oct. 15-24. About
5,500 handicapped athletes from 60 countries, including the Soviet
Union and China, are expected to take part.
   Since their inception in 1960, the special Olympics have been
held every four years in the same country and during the same year
as the Summer Olympics except in the cases of the Mexico Olympics
in 1968 and the Moscow Olympics in 1980.
</TEXT>
