<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     07-08 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number of Teacher Strikes Unchanged at 87, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group opposed to strikes by public employee
unions says there were just as many strikes staged by public school
teachers this year as last.
   The Public Service Research Foundation said Thursday while there
were the same 87 strikes in 14 states in 1987-88 as the year before
the situation had actually worsened because more teachers were
involved and almost three times as many students missed classes.
   It said 66,043 teachers went out on strike at some point during
the school year that just ended, and 945,793 students missed
classes.
   It said in 1986-87, there were 87 strikes in a dozen states,
affecting 49,546 teachers and 326,431 students.
   The foundation, part of an organization that opposes collective
bargaining for public employees, published the figures in its
fortnightly newsletter, The Government Union Critique.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trial Begins for Navy Man Charged With Murder in Shipboard Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a Navy petty
officer charged with murdering a disbursement officer during the
robbery of a $94,000 payroll says his client had plenty of money
and has been wrongly accused.
   Petty Officer 1st Class Ruben Colon, 34, had saved more than
$100,000 and was preparing to leave the service after 15 years, the
attorney, Lt. Matthew Michels, told a court-martial panel on
Thursday.
   However, prosecutors argued that Colon was followed by Navy
investigators to the bank where $87,000 in cash and 2,575 U.S.
Treasury checks were found in a safe deposit box rented in Colon's
name.
   Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad, disbursing officer of the destroyer John
Hancock, was killed March 15 in a robbery of the warship's payroll.
   Colon, of Vega Baja, Puerto Rico, faces the death penalty if he
is convicted of the murder charge. The Navy has not executed anyone
since an 1849 mutiny.
