<DOCNO> AP880708-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-Elections Bjt   07-08 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Elections, Bjt,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Toasts Victory But Braces For End To Exclusive
Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's governing party was toasting victory
in the presidential elections even before the votes were counted,
but it also was bracing for an end to the exclusive power it has
wielded for six decades.
   ``It is the new political reality of the nation, and with which
we will have to coexist in a harmonious and respectful fashion,''
governing party candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari said Thursday.
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, went into
Wednesday's election squeezed between popular opposition candidates
on both its left and its right and persistent suspicions it would
cheat to stay in power.
   In the hours after the polls closed, the PRI-dominated Federal
Election Commission said its vote-counting computer was broken.
Opposition leaders said that meant the PRI had not done as well as
it had hoped.
   ``We have achieved this victory in one of the most contested
elections in our history and one of the most peaceful,'' Salinas de
Gortari told thousands of cheering supporters at party headquarters
Thursday.
   But Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, candidate of the leftist coaltion, said
it was too soon to call any of the races. He and other opposition
leaders accused the PRI of vote-rigging, and he warned the election
commission not to tailor the results to PRI's victory claim.
   More than 38 million people were registered to vote.
   Interior Minister Manuel Bartlett, head of the election
commission, said Thursday that official results will be released on
Sunday. In the long wait, the parties were trying to assess their
showings.
   It was clear that at least some segments of the governing party
were bracing for a bigger bow to democracy than they had bargained
for with all the talk of clean elections and democratization.
   ``Information allows us to see that the opposition groups show a
majority force in several districts of the country,'' Salinas said,
in an apparent concession that PRI had lost some congressional
seats.
   He said the ``legal victories'' of the opposition would be
respected.
   Salinas seemed to be preparing the party faithful for what could
be a pivotal moment in PRI history _ less than overwhelming victory
at all levels.
   No PRI presidential candidate has ever won with less than 70
percent of the vote and it has never given up a governor's race. It
lost only one Senate seat since 1929 _ and that was to a candidate
whose coalition included PRI.
   Sources inside the PRI and in opposition camps were saying
Cardenas might even win the federal district, a sprawling area
including Mexico City that is home to a quarter of the nation's 80
million people.
   Six decades of uninterrupted power has given PRI the reputation
of a party that stoops to voter manipulation, election fraud and
intimidation. The opposition made honest elections the main
campaign issue.
   The slaying of a top strategist for the leftist opposition only
days before the election and reports of fraud on election day did
little to dampen the allegations.
   The Democratic Assembly for Effective Suffrage, a citizens'
watchdog group, reported 1,100 cases of balloting irregularities,
including 500 in the Mexican capital alone.
   Opposition spokesmen said Thursday that some complaints had been
filed with local and federal election officials and documentation
was still being gathered on many cases.
   The erosion of PRI's influence in a time of economic crisis and
growing demands for democratization was evident in the strong
campaigns waged by Cardenas and Manuel J. Clouthier of the rightist
National Action Party.
   Privately, Salinas' inner circle was admitting its doomsday
scenario included giving up one or two spots in the 64-seat Senate
and taking the presidency with a smaller margin than any president
in party history.
   ``We are viewing it with serenity,'' one aide said, agreeing to
meet with foreign reporters only on condition of anonymity.
   Although the president dominates the political system in Mexico
and PRI's majority in the 500-seat Chamber of Deputies is not at
risk, anything more than a figurehead role for the opposition would
be a dramatic change.
   Aides said that Salinas' constant campaign talk about holding a
clean election laid the groundwork for such an eventuality.
   Cardenas, Clouthier and Rosario Ibarra de Piedra of the small,
radical Revolutionary Workers Party met with federal officials
Wednesday night and issued a statement accusing the government of
rigging the election.
   The statement accused the government of stuffing ballot boxes,
eliminating citizens from voting rolls, paying people to vote and
multiple voting.
   ``The Mexican political system is corrupt and lacks
credibility,'' Clouthier told a news conference Thursday.
   PRI representatives called the fraud allegations a publicity
move and challenged the opposition to prove its allegations.
   President Miguel de la Madrid, whose six-year term expires Dec.
1, was quoted in the government newspaper El Nacional Thursday as
saying the voting showed the world that Mexico is capable of
holding a clean election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
