<2ND_LINE>PM-Tangled Sub,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Sub Becomes Tangled With Fishing Buoy In Hawaiian Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese submarine participating in naval
maneuvers lost a confrontation with a fishing buoy off Pearl Harbor
and had to be freed by U.S. Navy divers, a Navy spokesman said.
   No one was injured Thursday when the submarine Takeshio's left
stern diving plane became tangled in a cable holding a fish
aggregating buoy 10 miles south of Pearl Harbor, according to U.S.
Navy spokesman Petty Officer Brent Johnston.
   The 236-foot Takeshio, which was submerged at the time, suffered
no damage, Johnston said. The sub was able to surface, but remained
stuck until divers freed it about six hours later, he said.
   The Takeshio carries a crew of 80, according to ``Jane's
Fighting Ships.''
   A U.S. Navy diving team cut the sub loose from the buoy cable,
and the Takeshio returned to Pearl Harbor under its own power,
Johnston said.
   The diesel-powered Takeshio wass in Hawaiian waters
participating in RIMPAC 88. The United States, Australia and Canada
are also taking part in RIMPAC, short for ``Rim of the Pacific.''
