<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soweto-Blackouts     07-08 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soweto-Blackouts,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Plan Blackouts To Enforce Rent Collections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Soweto said they
plan electrical blackouts to counter a two-year boycott of rent and
service payments by residents of the country's largest black
township.
   Local officials switched off power for several hours Wednesday
evening to three sections of Soweto. The action forced postponement
of a professional soccer game, put out street lights and prompted
some police and fire stations to operate on emergency generators.
   On Thursday officials said they planned more blackouts.
   ``Unless residents pay their bills we will continue with the
blackouts,'' said R.E. du Toit, chief electrical officer for
Soweto, the main township outside Johannesburg.
   The blackouts effect all residents in the targeted areas, not
just those participating in the boycott.
   ``It is unfortunate that those who pay their rent, water and
electricity will suffer as much as those who do not,'' du Toit said.
   The Soweto City Council has threatened to cut off electricity to
the entire township in two months unless residents resume paying
rent and service fees.
   An estimated 80 percent of the township's 2.5 million residents
are participating in the boycott that begain in 1986. The Soweto
City Council is $40 million in debt and no longer can afford to
purchase electricity, du Toit said.
   The boycotts were launched to protest poor services,
dissatisfaction with township officials and a host of political
grievances. The black township officials were elected in polls that
drew only 10-20 percent of voters, and they are widely viewed by
blacks as collaborators with the white-dominated national
government.
   The level of black political violence has fallen from the
turbulent period of 1984-6, but widespread civil disobedience
remains in townships such as Soweto.
   In addition to the rent boycott, most high school students in
Soweto are staying away from classes this week to protest the
detention of student activists. The boycott was called by the
Soweto Students Congress and coincided with a return to school
after the mid-year holidays.
   Local officials appear helpless to end the rent boycott, despite
repeated pleas. There have been some evictions but most residents
immediately move back into their homes.
   Du Toit said that one section of the township had its
electricity shut off in May, but there has been no increase in
payments.
   Some township residents say local activists have intimidated
them into not paying rent, adding that they fear retribution from
members of the community more than they fear eviction or the loss
of services.
   Most houses in Soweto have electric lights, although many
township residents use coal for cooking and heating.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
