<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrash-Settlement     07-08 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash-Settlement,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Offer To Settle For $1 and Recall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a 10-year-old girl killed
in a fiery church bus crash say they have offered to give up a
settlement from Ford Motor Co. if the automaker agrees to recall
and modify its older school buses.
   ``If someone was ever injured or killed in a similar accident,
and we hadn't done everything we could to prevent it from happening
again, we couldn't live with ourselves,'' said James Nunnallee,
whose daughter, Patricia, died May 14 with 26 others on the
Radcliff Assembly of God church bus.
   ``People might think we're crazy, but it doesn't bother us.''
   Nunnallee, an Air Force major, and his wife, Karolyn, said
recently they would accept a $1 settlement if Ford agreed to the
recall and to revamp the gas tanks on thousands of its older buses.
   When the church's bus was struck by an allegedly drunken driver
heading the wrong way on Interstate 71, the gas tank was punctured,
and smoke from the ensuing fire that spread rapidly through the bus
was blamed for all 27 deaths.
   Sixty-four of the 67 families whose relatives were killed or
injured in the accident have accepted the out-of-court settlements
jointly offered by Ford, which manufactured the bus' chassis, and
Sheller Globe Corp., which made the bus' body.
   Ford representatives have agreed to meet with the Nunnallees to
discuss the recall proposal, the couple's lawyer said.
   Robert Waite, a spokesman for the company, said Thursday Ford
has been considering the possibility of a recall since the crash
occurred. ``There may be an action taken _ it's under active
consideration here,'' he said.
   The bus was one of the last made in the United States before a
1977 federal rule took effect, requiring manufacturers to start
protecting their fuel tanks from the impact of crashes.
   Michael Hance, the Nunnallees' lawyer, said his clients have
asked Ford to replace the tank on each old bus, install a cage
around the existing tank or remount each tank inside the chassis,
where it would be shielded by the frame.
   But the company, which has disclaimed responsibility for the
accident, is concerned that performing the repairs might give
owners ``a false sense of security,'' Waite said.
   ``We don't want people to think you can magically make a
20-year-old bus brand new,'' he said.
   Lawyers familiar with the case have told The Courier-Journal
that the settlements by Ford include payments of $63,000 apiece to
families of children who suffered minor injuries and $700,000 to
the estates of each of the 24 children who died.
</TEXT>
