<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ThenDaisyGrowled     07-08 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Then Daisy Growled,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobody Here But Us Bobcats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Ferrara tried passing off his live bobcat
as a dead ocelot to throw authorities off the scent. But when Daisy
growled, the jig was up.
   Ferrara had tried his best, a spokesman for the American Society
for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals said Thursday. First, he
flatly denied that a bobcat shared his three-room New York City
apartment.
   Then he tried to dodge ASPCA officers by allowing how he once
had an ocelot that died. He displayed a cremation certificate and a
sympathy card from the Long Island Ocelot Club.
   But the cat-and-mouse game came to an end when Daisy started
growling.
   ``They look under the dining room table, and under the dining
room table, under a piece of cloth, is the bobcat,'' recounted the
spokesman, Jeffrey Hon. ``The bobcat weighs 30 pounds and is
seemingly very vicious.''
   The officers, alerted Wednesday by a neighbor's complaint of a
wild animal in the Queens building, had found their prey. Their
next step was obvious, Hon said.
   ``They take refuge in the bedroom.''
   The encounter was not all that unusual for the ASPCA, which
enforces animal cruelty laws in the city. ``At least once a year we
get a really weird case,'' said Hon. ``We had a lion out in Staten
Island once. Somebody had it living in their garage.''
   This time it was Daisy, a healthy 5-year-old female bobcat,
declawed but ``very, very fast,'' said Hon. ``It could jump you if
it wanted to.'' Its lair was Ferrara's Long Island City apartment,
decorated with porcelain cat heads and stocked with cat-related
videos.
   ``The guy's really into cats,'' said Hon.
   Ferrara said Daisy was a gift from friends and he didn't know it
was illegal to keep a wild animal as a pet in New York. He said
Daisy stayed at home, was paper trained, ate cat food and chicken
gizzards and occasionally even paid attention to him.
   ``She's a feline. She will do some things that I tell her. Other
commands she will acknowledge but will only react to them if she
feels like it,'' he said. ``She had the run of the place.''
   Friendly? ``To me, yes.''
   To ASPCA officers, apparently not. They summoned police, who
arrived an hour later and shot Daisy with two tranquilizer darts.
Freed from their bedroom retreat, the ASPCA officers confiscated
the cat and gave Ferrara a ticket for keeping a wild animal as a
pet. They're holding Daisy while they seek an appropriate home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
