<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Taiwan 1stLd-Writethru   07-08 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0465,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalist Party Picks President Lee As Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf, `New faces ...,' to UPDATE
with China party chief's congratulations; picks up 11th graf, `Lee
became ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui today was elected
chairman of the ruling Nationalist Party, a move that strengthens
his mandate to lead this prosperous island after four decades of
Chiang Kai-shek family rule.
   Lee, 65, is the first native Taiwanese to lead the party, which
was formed 94 years ago on the Chinese mainland and still claims to
be the legitimate ruler of all China.
   The Chiang family matriarch, Madame Chiang Kai-shek, made a rare
public appearance at the 13th party congress that chose Lee. She
urged delegates not to forget the contribution of old-guard members
facing retirement as a reform-minded younger generation seeks power.
   Madame Chiang, at least 86 years old, walked slowly as
bodyguards and a nurse followed.She received warm applause from the
delegates and shook hands with Lee.
   All but eight of the 1,184 delegates attending the congress of
the Nationalist Party, also known as the Kuomintang, stood up to
support Lee's nomination.
   Jaw Shau-kong, a young Nationalist lawmaker, remained seated to
protest the decision not to elect the chairman by ballot.
   The congress is the first in which delegates were not handpicked
by top party officials and in which a Central Committee election
was not restricted to candidates proposed by the party leader.
   The session comes at a time of increasing political
liberalization in Taiwan, a nation slowly emerging from its
authoritarian past.
   The selection of Lee, acting party chief since January, is the
first of several crucial personnel moves to be made during and
immediately after the weeklong congress that began Thursday.
   New faces are expected in the party's policy-making Central
Standing Committee and the Cabinet as old guard party
conservatives, who fled the Chinese mainland to Taiwan in 1949 with
Nationalist strongman Chiang Kai-shek, step down.
   Meanwhile, China's Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang sent
congratulations to Lee today, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   It quoted a message as saying: ``I sincerely hope that our two
parties will, together with the people of the whole country, make
joint efforts to strive for an early realization of the great cause
of the reunification of China.''
   Lee became president and acting party chairman after the Jan. 13
death of Chiang Ching-kuo, the son of Chiang Kai-shek, ended four
decades of family rule on Taiwan.
   Under the Kuomintang's authoritarian rule, Taiwan developed into
an export-fueled economic powerhouse. Chiang Ching-kuo in his final
years also introduced democratic change by lifting martial law and
allowing opposition political parties.
   Lee has vowed to continue the democratic trend and also supports
reforming the state-dominated financial system.
   Polls have shown Lee to be immensely popular. Native Taiwanese,
ethnic Chinese whose families settled in Taiwan before 1949,
account for about 85 percent of the island's nearly 20 million
people.
   Lee's popularity and his efforts to avoid alienating
conservatives have helped increase his influence.
   Lee was born Jan. 15, 1923, in Japanese-occupied Taiwan. His
ancestral home in Sanchih village is a spacious red-brick
Chinese-style building in the middle of a rice field.
   The local media have given Lee favorable coverage, portraying
him as a model youth and diligent student. At age 42, Lee left his
teaching post at a Taiwan university to study in the United States,
where he earned a doctorate from Cornell University.
   He has published several works on agriculture and economics,
including one with the weighty title, ``Intersectoral Capital Flows
in the Economic Development of Taiwan.''
   Lee is a pious Christian who is married with two daughters. The
local media say he is an excellent golfer who also plays the violin
and enjoys Beethoven. He also is a keen student of Japanese
fencing, known as Kendo.
   ``It was a miracle,'' prominent writer Po Yang recently said of
Lee's rise to power. He described Lee as ``the first leader with a
happy family and a healthy mind in China's 5,000-year history.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
