<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PamplonaDeath     07-08 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pamplona Death,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton Falls From Building At Bull Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-year-old Englishman fell from a
building to his death today as the week-long San Fermin Festival of
drink, dance and bulls entered its third day in this northern city,
police said.
   In an incident unrelated to the daily morning bull run, Roy S.
Sofer of London died after falling from the fourth floor of a
central Pamplona building, which he had reached by climbing up a
water pipe on its facade, police said.
   Police said friends of Sofer told them he had been trying to win
a bet over who could climb highest. Sofer was dead on arrival at a
local hospital, a hospital spokeswoman.
   The festival attracts an estimated 200,000 tourists from around
the world and across the country, doubling the city's normal
population, according to city officials.
   The second running of the bulls today resulted in slight
injuries to 13 people who tested their mettle running ahead of
them, police said.
   Most of the injured in the bull run received on-the-spot
treatment for bruises and scratches, but two required brief
treatment at the city's Navarre Hospital, police said.
   The bulls ran the half-mile stretch from the corrals to the bull
ring in 3 minutes and 20 seconds, with more than a thousand people
running ahead of them. Professional matadors kill the bulls each
afternoon in bullfights.
   The festival in honor of San Fermin, Pamplona's patron saint,
has been held continously since 1591. Ernest Hemingway described it
in his 1926 novel ``The Sun Also Rises.''
   Since 1591, bulls have gored 52 people to death, 12 since 1924,
according to official records.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
