<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Australia-Rabbits     07-08 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Australia-Rabbits,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australian Rabbits Multiplying Like Rabbits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia's wild rabbit population now
exceeds 200 million, or about 13 rabbits per citizen, the
government-funded Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
said today.
   Noel Flavell, an economist with the bureau, said the rabbit
population was booming because the myxomatosis virus, which had cut
down the rabbit population since it was introduced 30 years ago,
has become less effective.
   The rabbit costs Australia around $55 million in lost
agricultural production, according to a bureau report.
   Flavel said the mortality rate of myxomatosis infected rabbits
had dropped from 99 percent to around 60 percent in recent years.
   Officials are looking into developing a new lethal gene to
further reduce the wild rabbit population, he said.
   Australia's population is about 15.4 million.
</TEXT>
