<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-08 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penny Bancroft adopted two kittens a few
weeks ago, but it's her dog, Buttercup, that's taken over nursing
them.
   Buttercup, a 3-year-old poodle and cockapoo mix, has been
nursing and cleaning her adopted kittens for about four weeks.
   ``I was going to have her fixed, but it's like God meant it to
be,'' Ms. Bancroft said this week.
   Ms. Bancroft rescued the kittens, which she named Puss and
Boots, when she found them almost dead because their mother refused
to nurse them. She took them to a veterinary hospital, where they
were rubbed back to life.
   For five days, Ms. Bancroft's family fed Puss and Boots every
two hours. On the sixth day, Buttercup, who had been caring for and
licking the white and gold kittens, began producing milk for them.
   Ms. Bancroft said she and her family hadn't planned to have cats
as pets, but added, ``We can't give up on them now.''
   The kittens, who were bottle-fed to supplement the dog's milk,
are now eating baby food.
   Buttercup hasn't given birth to puppies for about a year and a
half and guards the kittens as if they were her own, Ms. Bancroft
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DANVERS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When mechanic Brian Pelletier began to
check out a customer's car to see what was wrong with the air
conditioning, he found a 3{-foot-long boa constrictor behind the
dashboard.
   ``I was laying right there on the floor, unscrewed the dash, and
all of a sudden I looked over and six inches from my head there was
this snake,'' said Pelletier, 45, an auto mechanic for 25 years.
``I was going to retire in three years, but I think this will move
it up.''
   A crowd of nearly two dozen mechanics, sales people and police
officers surrounded the car Wednesday, but were reluctant to move
on the reptile. After two hours, the snake finally was extracted by
former Peabody dog officer Nancy Kiley and William Ramsey, a game
warden with the state Environmental Police.
   Ramsey said he was not sure whether the snake crawled into the
car in Massachusetts or if it accompanied the vehicle from Detroit.
A lump in the snake's belly indicated it had recently eaten
something.
   ``They eat about once a month, so it could have come from
Detroit,'' said Ramsey, who said boas prefer cool places.
   ``How it got in there, no one knows, but he was in there a
while,'' he said. ``He was all tangled up in the wires, and they
usually don't get into corners like that.''
   Ramsey took home the snake, which he named Lester, and plans to
turn it over to the state Division of Wildlife and Fisheries for
placement with a new owner.
   ``All I want is the car back,'' said Frank Luongo, whose
daughter, Jessie, purchased it. ``I hope there are no babies in
there.''
</TEXT>
