<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-TankerWar 1stLd-Writethru   07-08 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Tanker War, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0514,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Supertankers Ablaze After Iraqi Raid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with report of second tanker
being hit. PICKS up 5th graf, `In a ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes attacked three
``maritime targets'' in the Persian Gulf, and shipping executives
said today that two supertankers were set ablaze in the raid.
   The gulf-based executives said the Iranians had chartered the
two vessels to shuttle oil from the key Kharg Island oil terminal
at the head of the waterway to the export terminal in the Strait of
Hormuz.
   They identified the tankers as the 264,108-ton Fellowship L and
the Cypriot 215,780-ton Star Ray. The Fellowship L flies the
Liberian flag but is owned by a Greek company.
   Both tankers were attacked in the vicinity of Kharg, said the
executives. They spoke on condition they not be named. No
casualties were reported.
   The executives also said they believed another Greek vessel on
charter to the Iranians might also have been hit.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which
monitors maritime traffic around the world, said the bridge and
crew quarters of each vessel were set on fire in the attacks.
   It said the Fellowship L, managed by Ceres Hellenic Shipping
Ltd. of Piraeus, was raided Thursday night when it was 30 miles
into its southbound trip after loading at Kharg.
   The tanker was hit once before, in February 1985.
   In a statement quoted by state-run Baghdad radio, an Iraqi
military spokesman reported the raids Thursday.
   The raids were carried out ``in continuation of our course to
destroy the Iranian regime's oil resources, which it exploits for
aggression,'' said the spokesman in the radio broadcast.
   He said two of the targets were ``large'' and one was ``very
large.''
   Iraq has used the term maritime target to refer to vessels,
mainly tankers, sailing to and from Iranian ports. It has been
attacking them since early 1984 as part of a blockade to throttle
the oil-based Iranian economy.
   The aim of the blockade has been to force the government of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to accept a negotiated peace in the war
between the two gulf oil powers. The war began in September 1980.
   Iran has been retaliating on a ship-for-ship basis in the
``tanker war,'' in which the London-based Lloyd's Shipping
Intelligence Unit estimates that 540 commercial vessels have been
attacked.
   Lloyd's said 88 of those attacks occurred in the first six
months of this year alone.
   The tanker war is fought in bursts, usually sparked by the Iraqi
strikes. The last two Iraqi strikes were on July 1, when the
supertankers Fortune Ship L, a sistership of the latest victim, and
Khark 4 which is Iranian, were struck and set ablaze.
   Because Iraq has had no ports in operation since the outbreak of
the war, Iran selects targets for its retaliatory strikes from
among neutral commercial vessels, especially those sailing to and
from Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
   U.S. and other naval task forces that patrol the waterway, have
been providing military escort to their national-flag vessels. The
U.S. warships also expanded their protective mantle in early May to
non-U.S. flagged vessels if attacked in their vicinity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     07-08 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Leader Predicts Vote Will Lead to Talks to End Script Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the Writers Guild of
America predicted that stalled negotiations between producers and
striking writers would resume soon following union ratification of
an interim contract.
   Brian Walton, executive director of the WGA West, said he hopes
to meet with the chief negotiator for the Alliance of Motion
Picture and Television Producers, the industry's bargaining group.
   ``I am hopeful that we can continue to explore ways of resolving
the impasse and that we can do so quickly,'' Walton said Thursday.
``The pressure is on both sides to get the industry working again.''
   Walton's optimism reflected a change in the tense environment
that has surrounded the strike since it began March 7.
   Union members voting in New York and Los Angeles Wednesday night
approved an interim contract with independent producers by an 8-1
margin. The interim contracts are a union effort to split the
industry's ranks.
   Thirteen companies have already signed the new deal, including
Carolco Pictures, makers of the ``Rambo'' movies, and actress
Shelly Duvall's Platypus Productions Inc., union officials said.
   Walton said that he and J. Nicholas Counter III, negotiator for
the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers, met
through the night Tuesday with talks concluding Wednesday.
   The Alliance has said it is not in negotiations with the WGA and
that its last contract offer to the guild, rejected by the WGA by a
3-1 margin June 22, is final. But Walton said he believed
Wednesday's vote would lead to talks that could end the 18-week
strike that has idled most Hollywood production.
   Referring to the interim contract, Walton said, ``It is now
clear that the writers' guild has a contract that can put the town
back to work. It is fair, reasonable and works for both sides. The
obstacle to ending the strike, therefore, is not obviously the
writers' guild.''
   Walton predicted the new interim agreement, in conjunction with
a previously approved independent contract, would mean that between
300 and 500 writers would resume work in coming weeks.
   As of Thursday, 124 production companies, mostly small
operations, had broken ranks.
   The two sides in the strike remain divided on payments for
television reruns and foreign television syndication.
</TEXT>
