<1ST_LINE>r i PM-U.N.-Environment     07-08 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-U.N.-Environment,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Leaders Gathering In Oslo To Discuss Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIK A. WOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de
Cuellar arrived in Norway today to head a high-level meeting on how
the United Nations can respond to environmental threats without
stunting world development.
   The heads of 25 specialized U.N. agencies and economic
commissions are to meet Saturday and Sunday at a closed-door
session called by Norway's Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland.
Mrs. Brundtland headed the U.N.-sponsored World Commission on
Environment and Development and drafted a landmark report called
``Our Common Future.''
   ``The intention of this meeting is to get the U.N. system to
give higher priority to environmental issues,'' said Morten
Wetland, a special advisor to Mrs. Brundtland on foreign and
environmental affairs.
   Among the issues to be raised at the conference are
deforestation, land degradation and desertification, acidification,
loss of biological diversity, and air and water pollution.
   Also scheduled to attend are the head of the World Bank, Barber
B. Conable Jr.; Michel Camdessus, chairman of the International
Monetary Fund; and the heads of the World Health Organization, the
International Atomic Energy Commission, the U.N.Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and the U.N.
Children's Fund (UNICEF).
   The conference was being held amid growing awareness of
potential environmental disasters, from the depletion of the
atmosphere's ozone layer protecting the earth from harmful
radiation, to the gradual warming of the earth due to the
entrapment of gases, the so-called ``greenhouse effect.''
   ``Everybody is conscious of the importance of the environment,''
Perez de Cuellar said Thursday on a stopover in Stockholm, Sweden.
   Perez de Cuellar was meeting privately in Oslo today with Mrs.
Brundtland, Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg and King Olav V.
</TEXT>
