<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EpiscopalConvention     07-08 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Episcopal Convention,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Pass Resolutions Condemning Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Episcopal Church leaders have approved a
resolution calling abortion ``a tragic dimension'' that should only
be used in unusual cases such as incest, rape or if the pregnancy
endangers the mother's life.
   The church's House of Bishops passed the resolution by voice
vote Thursday, and continued discussions on homosexuality, the role
of female bishops and an economic package to help the poor.
   ``The mood of our culture swings toward accepting abortion,''
said the Rt. Rev. Craig B. Anderson, bishop of the diocese of South
Dakota. ``The church is saying, `Hey, wait a minute, let's
acknowledge that life is sacred.'''
   ``We acknowledge in this country that it is the legal right of
every woman to have a medically safe abortion,'' the resolution
said. ``This church emphatically opposes abortion as a means of
birth control, family planning, sex selection or for any reason of
mere convenience.''
   ``This is an attempt by the church to reach out with compassion
on both sides and not to close off dialogue,'' said the Rt. Rev.
Donald J. Davis, bishop of northwestern Pennsylvania.
   The statement now must be considered by the House of Deputies.
   Church leaders, meeting in Detroit through Monday, hold a
General Convention every three years.
   During debate Thursday, members decided further study of the
homosexuality issue would be necessary.
   ``I believe we have given signals all over this church that we
are very divided,'' said South Carolina Bishop FitzSimons Allison.
   The church also upheld a controversial resolution that would
permit a congregation in a diocese with a female bishop to call in
a visiting male bishop to officiate at sacraments.
   Opponents attacked the vote in the House of Delegates as
discriminatory to women and a questioning of their right to
ordination.
   Also Thursday, Mayor Coleman Young urged church leaders to pass
an economic package that would assist poor people in beleaguered
cities such as Detroit. They plan to vote on the economic package
later this week.
   Young told leaders that Detroit has the country's highest
unemployment rate, 20 percent, prompting mass migration from the
city.
   ``No city in the country has experienced the wholesale
abandonment that Detroit has. We have the same borders as we did in
1950, but half the population,'' the mayor said.
   The economic package, dubbed the Michigan Proposal, has been
passed by the House of Deputies of the bicameral convention and now
goes before the House of Bishops.
   The proposal, written by H. Coleman McGehee, bishop of the
diocese of Michigan, calls for $250,000 to be allotted by the
national Episcopal Church in a bid to raise $4 million for six
years through foundation grants and other denominations to aid
areas in economic crisis nationwide.
   If passed, the resolution would establish cooperative housing
and employee owned businesses and develop community credit unions
as well as offering aid to the poor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
