<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraTroubles     07-08 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Troubles,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Leaders Announce Cuts, Slam Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meeting on budget cuts turned into an airing of
political differences among Contra leaders as the Nicaraguan rebel
movement drastically trimmed its scope due to the U.S. aid cutoff
by Congress.
   A Contra leader speaking at a news conference Thursday to
discuss non-military budget cuts accused dissidents within the
movement of ``giving ammunition to the Sandinistas.''
   Resistance directors Alfredo Cesar and Aristides Sanchez
reportedly support Contra military commander Col. Enrique Bermudez,
whom dissidents accuse of corruption and close links to ousted
Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza Debayle.
   ``There is no doubt that the divisions, the lack of unity in the
movement, is giving ammunition to the Sandinistas,'' said Sanchez,
who complained that the declarations of dissident commanders were
showing up in the Nicaraguan press.
   ``Dissidence is a sacred right in all organizations that believe
in democracy,'' Cesar said. ``But not when it begins to damage the
Nicaraguan Resistance struggle against the Sandinistas.''
   On the budget cuts, Cesar and Sanchez said non-military spending
has been slashed by 42 percent and 130 of 320 employees worldwide
have been laid off. The long-anticipated cuts in political and
administrative staff will close some offices in Europe and Latin
America.
   Cesar denied this month's round of layoffs were politically
motivated but conceded politics ``was one of the priorities'' in
deciding whom to let go.
   The cuts will save about $250,000 on the monthly budget of close
to $700,000, said Cesar, emphasizing the cuts ``have nothing to do
with operations in the field.''
   At least some of those laid off had aided the dissidents,
including the Contra's Miami spokeswoman Marta Sacasa. Cesar said
Ms. Sacasa would be given a new position as head of public
relations for the directors.
   But asked later if she would assume that position, Ms. Sacasa
laughed and said, ``I doubt it.'' She said she expected to be gone
within a few weeks.
   Cesar and Sanchez strongly denied a New York Times report that
each Contra leader receives $75,000 a year in U.S. funds and a
monthly expense account.
   ``The directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance do not receive any
salary from the United States government,'' said Sanchez.
   Contra leaders also repeated their refusal to resume peace
negotiations with the Sandinistas until they agree to put President
Daniel Ortega at the head of their delegation, move the talks out
of Nicaragua and get better guarantees from Central American
presidents that Ortega will fulfill any agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
