<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthSeaAlert     07-08 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Sea Alert,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norwegians Issue Alert From Oil From Blazing Rig</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Rig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norwegian authorities issued a pollution
alert because of oil floating from the burned-out Piper Alpha rig
in the North Sea, an official said today.
   But the oil slicks from the striken Piper Alpha rig in the
British sector of the North Sea were breaking up and were not
expected to reach the coast of western Norway, said Erik Nygaard of
the State Anti-Pollution Agency.
   A Norwegian plane was being sent to observe and assess the
dangers, he said.
   ``The information we've got indicates that the slicks are being
broken down by the water and that the addition of new oil is small.
If this is correct, it's unlikely that the oil slick will drift
towards the Norwegian coast,'' Nygaard said on the national NRK
radio.
   A British surveillance plane reported one oil slick six miles
long and 1.2 miles wide near the oil rig, but it was considerably
smaller than on Thursday. Another smaller slick was observed 18
miles away from the rig, the agency said.
   It said the main slick would have to be 20 times larger to be a
threat to Norway.
   An explosion Wednesday night broke the rig apart, and 166 people
were believed killed.
</TEXT>
