<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz-Asia     07-08 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Asia,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Central to Cambodian Peace, Says U.S. Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
today said that Cambodia's resistance leader, Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, is central to a political solution in Cambodia, and he
gave Sihanouk a letter of support from President Reagan.
   Reagan invited Sihanouk to visit Washington, possibly this fall,
said State Department spokesman Charles Redman. The former
Cambodian leader once branded the United States as Cambodia's No. 1
enemy.
   Shultz and Sihanouk met for 40 minutes to discuss the threat of
the Khmer Rouge guerrillas returning to power in Cambodia, the
withdrawal of Vietnamase troops from that country and talks among
the warring sides in Jakarta, Indonesia.
   After meeting with Shultz, Sihanouk said he was ready to go to
Jakarta with the partners of his resistance coalition for talks
July 25 with Cambodian and North Vietnamese government officials.
   The resistance partners include the Khmer Rouge, which
brutalized Cambodia after taking power in 1975 until it was ousted
in a 1978 Vietnamese invasion. According to some estimates, up to 3
million Cambodians died during Khmer Rouge rule.
   Redman said Shultz reaffirmed that the United States found a
Khmer Rouge return to power totally unacceptable.
   In remarks to reporters after the meeting, Sihanouk said the
Khmer Rouge aimed to retake power. He said disarming the
Chinese-supported guerrillas would be difficult.
   Shultz and Sihanouk met as part of a three-day ``dialogue''
between the six-member Association of Southeast Asian Nations and
six close partners _ the United States, Canada, New Zealand,
Australia, Japan and the European Community.
   Although some ASEAN countries are hoping the United States plays
a more direct role in Indochina, Washington's position has been to
follow the Southeast Asian organization's lead.
   ``We believe the United States has a key role to play in
underwriting a solution to the Cambodian problem,'' Foreign
Minister Suppiah Dhanabalan of Singapore told Shultz and the six
ASEAN ministers. He praised the United States for playing ``an
indispensable role'' in maintaining stability in the region.
   Shultz signed an agreement under which the United States will
provide an additional $5 million to assist Thai villagers living
along the embattled borders with Cambodia and Laos.
   The U.S. Embassy said the funds will assist about 300,000 people
in 412 border villages.
   Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda of Thailand presented Shultz
with the Most Exalted Order of the White Elephant, a high-level
royal decoration first issued by Rama IV in 1861.
   Shultz leaves Thailand on Saturday for an eight-country swing
through Asia and the Pacific. He holds talks with Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad of Malaysia before flying on to Jakarta, the
Indonesian capital, the same day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
