<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0524,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Stabs Four Jailers; Troops Wound Two Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with suspect arrested, condition
of fourth guard, other details. Pick up 9th graf pvs: `The army...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian youth visiting jailed relatives
in the Gaza Strip stabbed four Israeli jailers today and seriously
wounded three of them before being arrested, a prison spokesman
said.
   Soldiers arrested the 17-year-old after a chase outside the Gaza
Central Prison, said Johnny Tester, the prison spokesman. He said
the assailant's brother is a prison inmate. Tester and Israel radio
said the assailant is believed to be a member of the underground
fundamentalist group Islamic Jihad.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, troops wounded two youths in a
clash with Palestinian demonstrators who hurled rocks and bottles
in the city's open-air market, hospital officials and Palestinian
witnesses said.
   Police and soldiers closed Jerusalem to Palestinians from the
occupied territories to prevent violent protests called for by
underground leaders during Moslem prayers at the city's Al Aqsa
mosque.
   The leaders called for a ``day of confrontation'' at the mosque,
one of the holiest sites of Islam, and police poured hundreds of
reinforcements into Jerusalem, doubling the city's normal police
force.
   Since the uprising broke out Dec. 8 in the territories Israel
seized in the 1967 Middle East war, 215 Palestinians and four
Israelis have been killed.
   Ilana Ziv, a spokeswoman at Barzilai Hospital in Ashkelon, said
two of the jailers hurt in the prison attack were rushed to the
hospital by helicopter, and one was in serious condition with stab
wounds to the heart. Israel radio said two others were taken to Tel
Aviv's Tel Hashomer Hospital, where one was in moderate condition
and the other lightly wounded.
   The radio said the assailant carried two knives and the attack
appeared to have been plotted in advance.
   The army said it was investigating.
   In Nablus, Palestinians heeded a general strike called for by
underground Islamic fundamentalist leaders. Arabs in the city
blocked roads with rocks, burned tires and ordered merchants to
close their shops, Palestinian reporters said.
   Israeli troops opened fire on the protesters, wounding
17-year-old Saed Atallah in the right thigh and Mohammed Abdul
Karim, 22, in the right leg, Al Ittihad Hospital officials said.
The army said it was investigating.
   Observance of the strike was viewed as a test of strength among
rival Palestinian groups vying for leadership in the occupied
territories.
   Two groups identifying themselves as the United National
Leadership of the Uprising issued conflicting leaflets. One called
for a weeklong general strike beginning today, while the other
ordered two days of strikes on Saturday and Sunday.
   The Islamic fundamentalists also issued a leaflet calling for a
weeklong strike beginning today.
   In Bethlehem and Ramallah, demonstrators threatened shopkeepers
who opened their stores. One witness in Ramallah said he heard
masked youths telling merchants: ``Close, you dogs, or we will burn
you down.''
   In Gaza City, transportation and commerce were halted.
Palestinian youths burned tires, set up roadblocks and hung dozens
of outlawed Palestinian flags from electricity poles, Palestinian
reports said.
   The army today erected roadblocks at the entrances to Jerusalem
barring Palestinians from entering the city.
   An Associated Press reporter saw four roadblocks on a four-mile
stretch of road between the occupied West Bank town of Bethlehem
and the southern outskirts of Jerusalem.
   On one roadblock, security forces hung a sign which said in
Arabic: ``It is forbidden to enter Jerusalem.'' Troops turned back
all West Bank cars and hundreds of vehicles were backed up at the
checkpoints.
   Police spokesman Rafi Levy said hundreds of extra police were on
duty to maintain order in Jerusalem.
   Undergound leaders of the Palestinian uprising, which entered
its eighth month today, ordered Palestinians to ``observe holy Al
Aqsa day ... by striking painful blows at the occupation forces.''
   Al Aqsa, on the Temple Mount, is the third holiest site in
Islam. The area also abuts the Wailing Wall, the last remnant of a
temple holy to Jews.
</TEXT>
