<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AmericanFreed     07-08 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Freed,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colorado Man Released From Cambodia After 14 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colorado man detained since May 1987
for illegally entering communist Cambodia has been freed, and a
U.S. Embassy official said today that the man soon will return to
the United States.
   Sterling Brian Bono, 35, had been detained since he crossed into
Cambodia from eastern Thailand. He was released and flew to Bangkok
on Thursday after his brother flew to Cambodia to pick him up.
   Bono, of Las Animas, Colo., will return to the United States
shortly, said the spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, Ross
Petzing.
   Bono told reporters in Cambodia's capital of Phnom Penh last
week that he was searching for his son in a refugee camp when he
wandered across the border and was captured by soldiers. He said he
served with a U.S. Army engineering unit in Soc Trang, Vietnam,
during the Vietnam War.
   Efforts to secure Bono's release were hindered by the lack of
diplomatic relations between the United States and the Cambodian
government. The United States has not recognized the government
that Vietnam installed after a 1978 invasion.
   Negotiations were handled by the Phnom Penh office of the
Swiss-based International Committee of the Red Cross.
   It had appeared the Cambodians were using the Bono affair to
extract some form of U.S. recognition, but they recently announced
Bono was free to go. No reason for the release was given.
   ``We are pleased to report that Mr. Bono has already arrived
safely in Bangkok,'' Petzing said. ``We hope we can now move ahead
as well with the repatriation of the remains of American servicemen
lost in Cambodia during the Indochina war.''
   A total of 83 American servicemen are listed as missing in
Cambodia.
   On June 20, David Lambertson, deputy assistant secretary of
state for East Asia and Pacific affairs, told a congressional task
force there was no progress on the remains in Cambodia.
   He said: ``Despite our interventions through the Vietnamese, the
Lao, and the ICRC (and) direct communications by the National
League of Families, the Vietnamese-installed regime in Phnom Penh
has refused to cooperate in returning these remains to the U.S.''
</TEXT>
