<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hospital-AIDS     07-08 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital-AIDS,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Attorney General Tells Children's Hospital to Rescind
AIDS Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware children's hospital must
rescind its controversial policy of not treating patients with the
AIDS virus or face legal action, the state's attorney general said.
   Charles M. Oberly III said Thursday the policy violates
Delaware's public accommodations law.
   ``We've said emphatically that unless they rescind the policy
immediately we will take whatever action that is necessary, whether
it be through the courts or through the state Human Relations
Commission,'' he said.
   The attorney general's order was contained in a letter sent
Wednesday to officials of the Alfred I. du Pont Institute, a $150
million, 90-bed pediatric hospital in Rockland, just north of
Wilmington.
   So far, hospital administrators have not responded to Oberly's
letter.
   The attorney general's order was the latest development in a
growing controversy sparked two weeks ago by the announcement of a
policy that all prospective patients would be tested for exposure
to the human immunodeficiency virus, and those who tested positive
would be sent elsewhere.
   Amid a storm of criticism, hospital officials later said they
might agree to care for children in extreme cases, but the policy
did not define an extreme case.
   Earlier this week, about a dozen doctors from the Children's
Hospital of Philadephi in response to a plea from top Delaware
health officials angered by the policy.
   ``Its our belief that a hospital, to some extent, is subject to
the public accommodations sections of the state law,'' Oberly said.
``They just aren't free to discriminate against who can come in and
who can go out of their institution. ...
   ``I disdain the idea that AIDS patients are becoming the lepers
of the 20th century,'' Oberly said. ``I think we have to be a
little more compassionate.''
</TEXT>
