<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BundyAppeal     07-08 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bundy Appeal,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bundy Vows to Fight Death Sentence to Supreme Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condemned killer Ted Bundy's lawyers vowed to
fight to the Supreme Court if necessary to contest a federal
appeals court ruling upholding his death sentence for the murder of
a 12-year-old Florida girl.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which stayed Bundy's
execution just seven hours before it was to be carried out in
November, agreed with a lower court that none of Bundy's claims had
merit.
   Bundy has also been convicted of killing two women in Florida
and is a suspect in at least 10 other slayings.
   One of Bundy's attorneys, Polly Nelson, said lawyers will either
ask for a rehearing before all 12 judges of the 11th Circuit or
appeal Thursday's decision by a three-judge panel to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   ``The state is very pleased that the federal appeals court has
found no merit in this defendant's claims. We are hopeful that the
process of seeing that justice is served can now continue,'' said
Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth.
   Bundy is also under death sentence for killing two sorority
sisters in Tallahassee, Fla., three weeks before 12-year-old
Kimberly Diane Leach of Lake City, Fla., was abducted. The 11th
Circuit has stayed that death sentence, ordering a lower court to
review the appeal, which Ms. Nelson said involves issues similar to
the Leach case.
   Bundy had challenged his conviction in the Leach case by
claiming he was incompetent to stand trial, had been denied his
choice of attorneys and had ineffective assistance of counsel.
   Thursday's 60-page decision said Bundy had presented a ``cogent,
well-reasoned argument'' to the trial judge, and he had a
``rational understanding of the proceedings.''
   ``Consequently, a `hard look' at the record evidence supports
the conclusion that Bundy was competent to stand trial,'' Circuit
Judge Frank Johnson wrote.
   Bundy was an escapee from a Colorado jail, where he was being
held on murder charges, when the Florida murders were committed. He
is also a suspect in seven to nine slayings dating back to 1974 in
Seattle, three disappearances and two slayings in Utah and one
murder and three disappearances in Colorado.
</TEXT>
