<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-Anthrax     07-08 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Anthrax,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Reports First U.S. Human Anthrax Case Since 1984</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials have reported the
nation's first case of human anthrax since 1984, which apparently
started with contaminated cashmere at a textile plant.
   A 42-year-old maintenance man at the North Carolina textile mill
became ill in July 1987 with a small red lesion on his arm, and
developed pain, fever and chills over the following week, the
Centers for Disease Control said Thursday in its weekly report.
   The patient was diagnosed with a cutaneous form of anthrax, a
severe and potentially fatal disease most commonly found in cattle
and sheep.
   Only nine other human anthrax cases have occurred in the United
States in the past decade, the CDC said.
   Vaccination programs were recommended for workers at the North
Carolina plant and at a Texas plant where the cashmere was washed,
said the CDC, which, as is its custom, did not identify the
locations involved.
   The patient, who later recovered, hadn't recently been out of
North Carolina, the CDC said. However, his mill used wool from
Australia and New Zealand, cashmere goat hair from China,
Afghanistan and Iran, and camel hair from China and Mongolia.
   Eight of 59 textile samples from the mill tested _ including
five samples of West Asian cashmere _ showed contamination with
anthrax bacteria, the CDC said in its weekly report.
   ``The West Asian cashmere was probably the contaminant,'' the
CDC reported. ``Western Asia is an endemic area for anthrax.''
   The other three contaminated samples were either debris or
Australian wool, which may have been cross-contaminated while
stored near the cashmere, the agency said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
