<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pilot'sFamily     07-08 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pilot's Family,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Pilot's Family Lives In Oklahoma</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of the Iranian pilot whose
jetliner was shot down last weekend say there's no way he could
have been on a suicide mission.
   ``No, no. If you had known him, if you could talk to him once,
you would never imagine that,'' Nahy Sadeghi said of her
brother-in-law, Mohsen Rezaian.
   ``It's not even possible. He was a very good human being. He
valued people. He valued people's lives. He would never do such a
thing,'' Mrs. Sadeghi, of Norman, said in an interview Thursday
night with KWTV in Oklahoma City.
   The Defense Department acknowledged Thursday that the Iranian
A300 Airbus shot down by the U.S. warship was within a commercial
airline corridor, but said that alone did not guarantee its safety.
Iranian authorities say 290 people died in the downing.
   Mrs. Sadeghi's husband, Kamran, also told the television station
that it's unlikely the plane was off course when shot down by a
U.S. Navy ship Sunday.
   ``I think he flew that route many times and just like me and you
going from our homes to work and come back, we know our way. I
think it's the same way for him. So he should have been quite
familiar with it. I am positive,'' Sadeghi said.
   The Sadeghis said their brother-in-law was trained by Boeing in
Texas and dreamed of coming to live in the United States someday.
   Rezaian's wife, Mrs. Sadeghi's sister, gave birth to their
youngest child in Oklahoma, the Sadeghis say.
   Rezaian was a 15-year veteran of Iran Air, the couple said.
   The Iranian Embassy identified the pilot on Thursday. KWTV said
the Sadeghis provided documentation that they were related to the
pilot.
</TEXT>
