<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NIreland-Bomb 2ndLd-Writethru a0531 07-08 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Bomb, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0531,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Launch Mortar Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with IRA statements, other
details. Pick up 5th graf pvs: `The mainly...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IRA guerrillas today shelled
two police stations and mistakenly hit a school and several houses.
A British soldier was killed by a bomb blast near a swimming pool
where two people were slain earlier, police said.
   The Irish Republican Army said one of its fighters, Seamus
Woods, 22, died in a mortar attack on a police station at Pomeroy
in County Tyrone. Police said his body was found in a field
alongside a tractor-trailer used in the attack.
   Six people suffered minor injuries when a mortar raid on a
second police station in Stewartson, about 10 miles from Pomeroy,
went astray and damaged a primary school and several houses, police
said. They said 80 families were evacuated.
   The IRA claimed reponsibilty for the attacks.
   The IRA said the bombing of a swimming pool in west Belfast on
Thursday evening was an ``operation that went tragically wrong.''
The outlawed group said in a statement to Belfast media that the
bomb, which killed two civilians, was accidentally triggered by one
of its men.
   The British soldier, a bomb disposal expert, was killed early
today by a blast only yards from the swimming pool where he was
involved in clean-up operations, police said.
   The mainly Catholic IRA targets security forces in its guerrilla
war to end British rule in predominantly Protestant Northern
Ireland and unite it with the overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of
Ireland under socialist rule.
   On Thursday, police said a bomb was planted against the inside
wall of a building housing the swimming pool in the predominately
Roman Catholic Falls Road area of West Belfast. The blast killed
two people and injured four others.
   The bomb exploded after armed and masked men ordered staff and
members of the public out of the swimming pool.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said the bomb apparently was meant
to bring the walls of the building down on a security patrol
passing by outside. But the blast missed the patrol and hit
civilians instead.
   Local residents identified the two dead people as Elizabeth
Hamill, 60, and Eamonn Gilroy, 24, both Catholics from west
Belfast. Among those hurt was a 4-year-old girl.
   RUC Chief Inspector Ian Williamson said: ``The first explosion
was a disgusting atrocity compounded by the second blast. Here was
a soldier engaged in trying to make the area safe again for local
people.
   ``It clearly demonstrates the lengths these fiendish people will
go to pursue their bloodlust.''
   In the mortar attacks, police said the station at Pomeroy
suffered little damage when one mortar exploded inside a fenced-in
area. The second attack 15 minutes later missed the Stewartstown
station but damaged the school and nearby houses, they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
