<DOCNO> AP880708-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OilRig-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0442 07-08 0886</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Rig-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,0910</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to include resignation of contract
workers; picks up 10th graf pvs bgn, ``The Daily ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's worst offshore oil platform disaster
is raising questions about safety in an industry in which hundreds
have died, and the carnage has led some Britons to wonder whether
the oil is worth the human cost.
   ``The price of North Sea oil and gas is written in blood,'' the
Daily Mirror said in an editorial today.
   More than 160 people were killed or missing and presumed killed
in the the explosion and fire Wednesday on the Piper Alpha platform
in the North Sea.
   ``Charges of putting oil production above life preservation are
bound to resurge in the coming weeks,'' The Times of London said in
an editorial today.
   ``The general attention to safety in the North Sea is extremely
high ... but it is not always enough,'' the paper said. ``On
Wednesday night it was not enough.''
   Roy Carey, who was badly burned, said from a bed in Aberdeen
Royal Infirmary in Aberdeen, Scotland: ``We had all that water
around us and no way to get it to us. We had sprinklers but they
weren't strong enough.''
   The deaths bring to more than 300 the number of people who have
died in the British sector of the North Sea since gas was first
pumped ashore in 1967.
   Drilling accidents killed 76 and a helicopter crash killed 45.
Last year, six workers were killed and 59 seriously hurt among the
28,000 British workers.
   Three workers from Piper Alpha died after being thrown into the
sea when a gangway collapsed in 1982. In 1984, a non-fatal
explosion and fire forced the evacuation of 174 men.
   Today, more than 100 contract workers refurbishing oil rigs in
the North Sea resigned, citing concerns about safety of the
offshore industry in the North Sea.
   ``They felt some action had to be taken ...,'' Keith Gibson, a
spokesman for the General, Municipal, Boilermakers and Allied
Trades Union, told the British Broadcasting Corp.
   The Daily Mirror, which supports the socialist opposition Labor
Party, said: ``We must harness the talents of the best engineers,
scientists and managers to develop new and better materials,
systems and services to make the crews safer from all hazards,
including human error.''
   Occidental Petroleum, which operates the platform, said
Wednesday's fire apparently was caused by a gas leak.
   The liberal London newspaper The Guardian wrote: ``If, as
initial diagnosis suggests, only a leak of gas could have triggered
the series of explosions which wrecked the platform, there are
obvious questions about standards of maintenance, the handling and
storage of flammable materials and the rest.
   ``Account must be taken of the testimony from the unions ...
that they were frozen out of safety management procedures and that
complaints and warnings were insufficiently heeded.''
   Ron Todd, general secretary of the 1.3-million member Transport
and General Workers Union, some of whose members work on North Sea
oil rigs, said Thursday: ``The tragedy will clearly raise questions
regarding safety in the North Sea oil industry.''
   Labor unions also have complained about the quality and
avilability of survival gear and too few rescue helicopters. They
see a conflict of interest in making the Energy Department
responsible for oil production as well as safety.
   In Parliament, lawmaker John Prescott of the opposition Labor
Party contended that inspection and maintenance of rigs had been
reduced in recent years. He said insufficient money was spent on
training and that government health and safety legislation did not
apply fully to the North Sea oil and gas industry.
   Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson said serious North Sea
accidents had declined from 101 in 1986 to 59 last year. ``But that
is too high a figure and we wish to keep the pressure on to ensure
that improvement is maintained,'' he said.
   The department Thursday postponed the process for granting new
off-shore licenses, which would open up more areas for exploration.
   Meanwhile, the price of Brent Blend, the most widely traded
international crude oil, jumped on Thursday to $15.05 a barrel for
September delivery, up 32 cents from late Wednesday.
   Occidental Petroleum said the rig produced 167,200 barrels a
day. A barrel contains 42 gallons.
   The Energy Department said that in addition to the Piper oil
field, five other fields were shut down, cutting production by
about 220,000 barrels a day to 250,000 barrels a day, or about
one-tenth of the British sector's production.
   ``There's pressure on the immediate availability for North Sea
crude,'' said Philip Morgan, an oil analyst with the London
investment firm Warburg Securities.
   But Lucy Mullins, an oil analyst with the London investment firm
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., said the shortage would be short-term.
She said the related fields should be back in production in a week,
and Piper Alpha should be back in about a year.
   But there were concerns about claims against the company, and
Occidental Petroleum's stock fell 62.5 cents to close at $26.25
Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The disaster could prove expensive for the North Sea oil
producers in general, Morgan said.
   ``Obviously, questions are going to be raised about safety which
might involve companies in a lot more expenditure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
