<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Airliner-F-14 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 07-08 0872</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-F-14, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>F-14s Not Typically Armed To Attack Ships</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-6 to include February incident and use of F-14
radar, and delete source quote that F-14 never used in combat.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, That raises.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. commanders in the Persian Gulf were on
watch over the July 4th weekend for a handful of Iranian F-14
fighters recently stationed near the mouth of the Persian Gulf but
rarely risked in combat.
   The commander of the USS Vincennes, Capt. Will C. Rogers III,
thought he was under attack by an Iranian F-14 when he fired two
SM-2 anti-aircraft missiles at Iran Air flight 655, an A300 Airbus
with 290 civilians aboard.
   But the F-14 is primarily designed for combat against other
aircraft. And Pentagon sources said Iran hardly ever flies any of
its few operational F-14s in combat.
   Assistant Secretary of Defense Richard Armitage said last
February that it appeared Iran had begun increasing its use of
F-14s because of the plane's strong radar, and that one of them
shot down an Iraqi Mirage over the the main Iranian oil terminal at
Kharg Island last Feb. 9.
   ``This is the first effective use in combat we've seen in
several months, as I remember,'' Armitage said then.
   A U.S. military source with gulf experience said the Iranians,
although using the F-14s more in recent months to monitor the
movement of tankers carrying Iranian oil, seemed wary of sending
them into combat. ``They have sent them up to escort tankers, and
put them up when Iraqi fighters were around, but they always veered
off and stayed out of danger,'' said the source, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   That raises yet another question in the mystery of why a $1
billion Aegis cruiser, with the most sophisticated radar and
tracking system in the Navy, mistook an Iranian A300 Airbus with
290 civilians aboard for an F-14 and blasted it out of the sky at a
range of nine miles.
   To be effective against a ship as large as the Vincennes, 567
feet long and displacing 9,600 tons when fully loaded, the F-14
would need to be equipped with armaments that it does not
ordinarily carry, such as anti-ship missiles or bombs.
   Or, said one air industry source, ``if somebody loaded that
sucker with 30,000 pounds of fuel, it would make one hell of a bomb
on a kamikaze run.''
   The commander of U.S. forces in the region, Marine Corps Gen.
George B. Crist, told reporters last Thursday that Iran recently
moved an unspecified number of F-14s from their main base at
Isfahan, central Iran, to Bandar Abbas on the Persian Gulf.
   Iran Air flight 655 took off from the joint civilian-military
field at Bandar Abbas while Iranian Boghammar gunboats were
attacking the Vincennes in the Strait of Hormuz, and headed for the
U.S. warship.
   The airliner broadcast an identification signal similar to one
used by Iranian F-14s, said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard.
   ``I don't think it is related to us ...,'' said Crist. ``I think
this has to do with reaction to the Iraqis'' attacking tankers in
the southern gulf, and ``not so much the Americans.''
   But the development clearly worried U.S. skipper in the gulf.
   Asked why the Vincennes was afraid of a plane that had never
been used against a surface target, Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard
said: ``We do know that the Iranians have Harpoon (anti-ship
missiles) in their inventory which they can sling under an F-14
with no difficulty.
   ``We have suspected for some time that they have been working
with Standards in an air-to-ground or air-to-surface mode. And the
iron bomb is another possibility. So, if your question is, `Does an
Iranian F-14 constitute a threat to U.S. naval vessels?' the answer
is, `Yes.'''
   The chaiman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe,
told a news conference Sunday that ``we have alerted our forces of
indications that Iranian units might carry out attacks against our
forces over the July Fourth period.''
   Before the fall of Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi in 1979, Iran
acquired about 80 of the F-14s from the Grumman Corp. of Long
Island, New York.
   Hundreds of American technicans were stationed at Isfahan,
maintaining the F-14s and teaching the Iranians to fly them.
   After the revolution, U.S. arms shipments were cut off, and Iran
more or less grounded its F-14s once its war with Iraq began in
September 1980.
   Only within the past year has Iran managed to get the spare
parts it needs to make as many as 15 of the F-14s operational,
according to administration officials.
   It is not clear where Iran is getting the parts, but U.S.
intelligence reports that a North Korean ship docked at Bandar
Abbas at the end of June, and may have contained F-14 components
and possibly weapons.
   The F-14 can fly faster than Mach 2, twice the speed of sound,
or about 1,320 mph at an altitude of 30,000 feet, and those in the
U.S. Navy carry six Phoenix, four Sparrow and four Sidewinder
anti-aircraft missiles and are armed with a 20mm Vulcan Mk-61
cannon, capable of firing up to 6,000 rounds a minute.
</TEXT>
