<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MortarAccident     07-08 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mortar Accident,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Identify Two Killed in Mortar Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen survivors of a mortar accident that
left two other Marines dead have been flown to Honolulu for further
medical treatment, officials said.
   The Marines were conducting a night training exercise Wednesday
night when they were hit by shrapnel from exploding 60mm shells at
the Pohakuloa Training Area on Hawaii Island, Maj. Kerry K.
Gershaneck said Thursday.
   Ten Marines were taken Thursday to Tripler Army Medical Center
near Honolulu, where they joined four other Marines wounded in the
accident, hospital spokesman George Vidis said.
   Vidis said all 14 were listed in satisfactory condition.
Gershaneck had earlier said only eight Marines were hospitalized.
   Investigators were working to determine why the mortar shells
landed among about 30 Marines, Gershaneck said. The names of the
injured would be released once all their families were notified, he
said.
   The dead were identified as Gunnery Sgt. Howard E. Harris, 34,
of Philadelphia, and Cpl. Clifford L. Carlisle II, 21, of Roswell,
N.M.,
   Harris was the platoon sergeant and Carlisle was a mortarman for
the 81mm mortar platoon of the Marine 2nd Battalion, 3rd Marine
Regiment stationed at the Kaneohe Marine Corps Air Station near
Honolulu, Gershaneck said.
   Lt. John Renfro, the battalion's chaplain, was one of the first
people to arrive at the scene of the accident.
   ``These are young men, who don't have a lot of experience with
death and a lot of experience with injury,'' Renfro said. ``So the
men, many of them, were just sitting, stunned.''
</TEXT>
