<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachesClosed 1stLd-Writethru a0570 07-08 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beaches Closed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0570,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Medical Debris Washes Ashore; Some Long Island Beaches Closed
Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with beaches closed again,
picking up at the 3rd graf previous.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Long Island beaches were closed even
to sun bathers today after more medical waste washed ashore, and
one official said ``midnight dumpers'' were suspected of illegally
disposing of the debris.
   ``We are concerned that these people may be inadvertently hurt
by picking up this material,'' said Michael Asheroff, deputy
regional director of the Long Island State Park Commission. ``The
public is being kept from using this absolutely gorgeous facility.
It's a pity thery are being denied its use.''
   Jones Beach and Robert Moses State Park were closed today after
plastic refuse, including syringes, washed ashore.
   Asheroff said any decision about reopening the beaches for the
weekend will be made after they are inspected each morning.
   The state park was closed to swimmers Thursday, hours after
health officials lifted a ban initiated Wednesday when the first
wave of hospital waste hit parts of Long Island's South Shore.
   Similar orders were given for Nassau Beach County Park and at
four Fire Island beaches: Kismet, Fair Harbor, Dunewood and
Atlantique. Several other beaches that were closed Wednesday were
reopened.
   Elsewhere, Bayonne, N.J., officials found four more glass blood
vials Thursday, bringing to 145 the number of vials found since
Sunday. Five of 105 vials tested were found to have the AIDS
antibody; 36 vials were still awaiting testing.
   The discovery came a month after five vials of blood were found
along the beach in Ocean County on the New Jersey shore. Two of
those vials were contaminated with the AIDS antibody, while a third
tested positive for the more highly infectious hepatitis B virus.
   On Thursday, New Jersey investigators met in New York with
representatives of the Nassau County District Attorney's Office and
the New York Attorney General's Office to discuss the cases.
   New York officials ordered the beach closings as a precaution
against the risk of infection from the potentially hazardous waste,
which also included intravenous tubing, gauze, rubber gloves and
pill containers.
   R.W. Groneman, a spokesman for the Department of Environmental
Conservation in Albany, said ``midnight dumpers'' were suspected _
haulers unwilling to abide by New York's toughened regulations on
medical trash disposal who get rid of it at sea under cover of
darkness.
   Groneman said the volume of debris indicated that it came from a
hospital or large clinic, and that any such institution's disposal
of medical trash would be regulated by the state. Such garbage must
be incinerated at the hospital or trucked by an approved hauler to
an incinerator or approved dump site.
   Inspectors combed the beaches collecting the material but found
no identifying markings, said Russell Keller, senior sanitary
engineer for the environmental conservation department.
   The Nassau and Suffolk County health departments took samples of
the ocean water to test for quality, with results expected today.
   Thursday's debris appeared to be heavier than the amounts that
forced the Wednesday shutdown of a 25-mile stretch of beaches,
including the Robert Moses and Jones Beach state parks, said
Michael Asheroff, deputy director of the Long Island State Park
Commission.
   Despite a summer heat wave, attendance at the beaches seemed
light Thursday. Normal attendance during weekdays is 50,000 to
60,000 at the state beaches.
</TEXT>
