<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FuelSpill     07-08 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Spill,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSHA Proposes Fines Against Ashland Over Tank Rupture That
Polluted Rivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Labor is seeking
$31,800 in penalties against Ashland Oil Inc. in connection with an
oil tank collapse that fouled water supplies in Pennsylvania, Ohio
and West Virginia.
   The Jan. 2 collapse of the 4 million-gallon storage tank near
Pittsburgh spewed more than 700,000 gallons of diesel fuel into the
Monongahela and Ohio rivers in one of the worst inland oil spills
in U.S. history.
   Some 23,000 suburban Pittsburgh residents were without tap water
for a week, and cities all along the two rivers had water supplies
contaminated until the oil slick was finally diluted.
   The Labor Department's Occupational Health and Safety
Administration accused Ashland of willful violations in failing to
properly weld steel plates that formed the tank wall and failing to
repair defective welds after they were discovered. OSHA proposed a
$30,000 penalty on those points.
   OSHA also claimed a serious safety violation, with a proposed
penalty of $1,000, because the dike surrounding the tank was
inadequate to contain the oil, said Garry Griess, OSHA area
director in Pittsburgh.
   The agency is seeking an $800 penalty because Ashland failed to
establish a plan for responding to such an emergency and failed to
have a written safety plan for the Floreffe Terminal.
   Ashland officials are reviewing the citations and weighing their
options, which include formally contesting the civil charges, said
company spokesman Roger Schrum.
   OSHA spokesman Al Belsky in Philadelphia said Thursday that
Ashland had not yet contested the citations.
   The company did contest citations issued Jan. 28 totaling
$18,000 concerning alleged violations during the river cleanup.
</TEXT>
