<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0477 07-08 0953</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0477,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Weighs Bentsen as VP; Bush Trips' Financing Questioned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 11 grafs with Dukakis remarks, Bush spokesman
on Kirk allegations, picking up in 5th graf pvs, Jesse Jackson;
deletes grafs 17-19 pvs, The financing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis campaigned in Texas today, repaying
Republican George Bush's trip the previous day to the Massachusetts
governor's home grounds. Dukakis, standing by Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, said he was still deciding whom to choose as his running
mate.
   At a brief news conference in Texarkana, Texas, Dukakis
commented briefly about possible U.S. actions in the aftermath of
last Sunday's shooting down of an Iranian airliner by a U.S. ship.
``I think some form of humanitarian assistance would probably be
appropriate,'' he said, without elaboration.
   In Atlanta, meanwhile, Democratic Party chairman Paul Kirk
released his letter to the White House accusing the Bush campaign
of not reimbursing the government for use of Air Force Two and
other vice presidential benefits on campaign trips.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said Kirk's statements ``are
totally without merit and are obviously designed to distract public
attention from the real issues. ... While I have not yet seen
Kirk's letter, the events I am told he questioned were financed in
accordanace with the law, and in no case were public funds used to
defray either campaign or Republican National Committee expenses
associated with trips.''
   The vice president was flying to Atlanta today to give a pep
talk at a Republican unity dinner.
   Dukakis, in Bush's adopted home state, praised Bentsen as
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee and was asked whether
Bentsen would be more valuable in the Senate than as a vice
presidential running mate.
   ``I'm pondering. He could make a great contribution to the
country in many, many ways. He already has,'' Dukakis said.
   Bentsen, asked if he wanted the job, said, ``I don't think we
have to worry about that.''
   Dukakis spoke at an outdoor rally with Bentsen, Arkansas Gov.
Bill Clinton and Arkansas Sen. Dale Bumpers at his side.
   On Thursday, Bush campaigned in Dukakis' Boston back yard and
said he shares the traditional values of the Greek-American
community from which the Massachusetts governor hails. Dukakis,
describing Bush's pledge to appoint a Hispanic to his Cabinet as
too little and too late, said Americans are ``tired of waiting for
opportunity to trickle down'' from a privileged few.
   The two candidates also sparred from a distance over taxes, as
Dukakis accused the vice president of abandoning ``ironclad
commitments'' and favoring $7 billion in new taxes.
   Jesse Jackson, meanwhile, was traveling to Dallas today for a
meeting with Dukakis aides, his campaign said. The Dukakis camp is
still negotiating with Jackson's forces over the civil rights
leader's plan to pursue as many as 13 minority planks at the
convention in Atlanta July 18.
   Bush, on Dukakis' home turf, spoke well of his rival.
   ``What a tribute it is to Greek-Americans, to our political
system, and to this great country of ours that we find it totally
natural that the son of an immigrant is one of two men still
contending to be president of the United States,'' Bush said in a
speech to a conference of the Greek Orthodox Church.
   ``Family, faith, education, hard work _ those are the keys and
no one knows it better than you,'' Bush said. ``It's the same
message you preach in your homes, the same way I was raised, the
same way Barbara (Bush's wife) and I raised our family.''
   Dukakis, however, portrayed Bush on Thursday as an elitist and
said the vice president's pledge to appoint a Hispanic-American to
his Cabinet comes after years of Reagan administration neglect of
minorities.
   ``Some people think it's enough to wake up after eight years and
then promise opportunity for one Hispanic,'' Dukakis told the
League of United Latin American Citizens, the same group Bush had
addressed a day earlier. ``I want to stand with you and create
opportunity for 20 million Hispanic citizens across the country.
   ``I've campaigned from one end of this country to another, and I
know that we Americans are ready for a change. We're tired of
waiting for opportunity to trickle down from a few privileged
neighborhoods into our cities and into the small communities of
rural America.''
   Earlier Thursday, while still in Boston, Dukakis said Bush had
broken his pledge to oppose any new taxes. He said Bush supported a
provision of the trade bill that calls for $1 billion in taxes for
job training programs and catastrophic health care legislation that
included $6 billion in taxes on elderly people who opt for the
comprehensive care.
   ``So much for ironclad no-tax commitments,'' said Dukakis.
   Bush responded in Boston by referring to Dukakis' recent signing
of a state cigarette tax and his support for another measure
raising taxes. ``I'm against raising taxes, and I think recent
events here in this state that I don't plan to go into demonstrate
we have a different view on taxes,'' he said.
   In an effort to limit public disagreements as November nears,
Reagan and Bush directed their chiefs of staff Thursday to
coordinate campaign policy pronouncements and strategy.
   `I think everyone agrees that the main issue is, `No
surprises,''' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said after
Reagan, Bush and aides met over lunch at the White House.
   Jackson, meanwhile, announced plans Thursday to lead a three-day
``Jackson Action Rainbow Express'' bus trip from Chicago to the
Atlanta convention.
   Jackson, in Atlanta, said his presidential campaign also will
sponsor workshops for people outside the convention hall. He said
the emphasis on non-delegates is intended to strengthen the party,
not detract from Dukakis.
</TEXT>
