<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Congressmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Will Visit Iowa Radio Station Where He Got His Start</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will travel to the Midwest
Thursday to talk to drought-stricken farmers in Illinois and
revisit the Iowa radio station where he got his start in
broadcasting, the White House said today.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the exact location of Reagan's
Illinois farm visit had not been determined.
   ``He wants to talk to farmers about the problem,'' Fitzwater
said. ``We are developing a legislative package and he feels it is
important to get some first-hand knowledge before sending the
package up.''
   After the Illinois farm stop, the president will go to WOC in
Davenport, Iowa, to dedicate the station's new building and help
observe its 60th anniversary.
   He will speak at a lunch sponsored by the station and the
Davenport Chamber of Commerce, to be held in Palmer Auditorium on
the Palmer College campus.
   Reagan began his career in radio by broadcasting Big 10 football
games on WOC in the fall of 1932, Fitzwater said.
