<DOCNO> AP880708-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Airliner-Pentagon     07-08 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Pentagon,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Studying Whether Controllers Monitored</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon officials said today they are
awaiting results of an official investigation to learn whether U.S.
naval forces in the gulf were monitoring air traffic control
conversations with Iran Air flight 655, communications which Iran
says made clear that the airplane was civilian.
   ``We are looking forward to an analysis of the tapes to help
clarify the issue,' said Lt. Cmdr. Chris Baumann, a Pentagon
spokesman.
   The chief of Iran's air force, Brig. Gen. Mansour Satari, told
reporters in Tehran on Thursday that U.S. systems should have been
able to monitor 21 minutes of conversation in English between the
jetliner and the airport control tower in Bandar Abbas, near the
mouth of the Persian Gulf.
   Satari also said the downing of the A300 Airbus by the USS
Vincennes showed that the American military was ``unable ... to
control its sophisticated systems.''
   U.S. officials said the Vincennes mistook the Airbus for an
Iranian F-14 fighter because the plane was broadcasting an
identification signal on a frequency used only by military
airplanes, as well as sending a signal on a channel used by both
civilian and military aircraft.
   Satari said destruction of the plane was an ``intentional and
unprovoked attack,'' but he later qualified this by saying the U.S.
military ``accepted on purpose'' the risk of shooting down civilian
planes because they were unable to control their sophisticated
systems.
   And he said Iran had ``all the tapes needed'' to prove that
normal conversation was going on from the time the engines were
started up on the ground until the plane was shot down.
   The Iranian general also said the plane was traveling in ``the
center of the international air corridor'' between Bandar Abbas and
Dubai and could have deviated 10 miles either side but still have
been within the corridor.
   On Thursday, the chief Pentagon spokesman, Dan Howard, said that
Defense Department officials ``don't know whether (U.S. forces in
the gulf) were listening to the control tower or not. We will learn
that in the course of the investigation'' being directed by Rear
Adm. William M. Fogarty.
   Tapes from the Vincennes were flown from the gulf for analysis
at a specialized installation at Dahlgren, Va., said Howard. The
tapes contain data from the Vincennes sophisticated Aegis radar and
tracking system, said Howard, but he was unable to say whether they
included voice communications among the ship's officers, U.S.
commanders in the gulf and in the United States, or any intercepted
Iranian transmissions.
   ``It is probable that their highest priority at the moment was
not listening to the air traffic control radio discussions at
Bandar Abbas, said Howard. ``There are many, many radio
frequencies. ... It would take a heck of a lot of people to monitor
all of them.''
   Howard also said that Iranian Air Flight 655 was 4{ miles from
the center of a civilian air corridor stretching from Bandar Abbas
to Dubai, in the United Arab Emirates on the opposite side of the
Strait of Hormuz.
   According to the code governing international air flights, said
Howard, ``commercial airliners, those carrying passengers, are
expected to adhere to the centerline of the airway.''
   But he said it was unclear how wide the air corridor was at the
point where the Airbus was hit, because Iran claims a corridor 10
miles on each side and many other countries, including the United
Arab Emirates, recognize a corridor 4{ miles from the center.
   ``The aircraft was at least 4{ miles off the center line of the
airway and in that regard could be considered to be off the normal
track of commercial aircraft,'' said Howard.
   ``An airway is not a safety zone,'' he said. ``All this means is
that within that zone, within that area, the air traffic control
authorities have agreed to track aircraft.''
</TEXT>
