<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--DisasterTrial     07-08 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Disaster Trial,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Convicted of Manslaughter in Dam Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday convicted 10 men of
manslaughter in connection with a dam collapse in the alpine resort
of Stava that killed 269 people in 1985.
   The 10, who were responsible for running or making periodic
safety checks on the two-basin earthen dam, were sentenced to terms
ranging from 2{ to five years. Two other men were acquitted.
   The upper basin collapsed into the lower basin on July 19, 1985,
sending a flood of water, debris and mud into the valley below. The
torrent swept away three hotels and 20 houses.
   Among those convicted by the Trento Court were Fazio Fiorini, an
official of the Prealpi Mining Co., the owners of the dam, who
proposed building the second reservoir, and Giulio Rota, an owner
of the company.
   The court also ordered the defendants, the provincial government
that approved the project and the companies involved to pay $17
million in damages to the families of the victims.
   Investigators concluded the collapse was caused by negligence.
The team said the dam had been poorly constructed and inadequately
serviced.
</TEXT>
