<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--India-Attack     07-08 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--India-Attack,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribal Rebels Kill Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels ambushed and killed three members
of a paramilitary unit in the remote northeastern state of Manipur,
it was reported Friday.
   A soldier and two civilians also were wounded in the Thursday
night assault by underground Naga rebels, the Press Trust of India
said.
   The rebels attacked a jeep of the paramilitary Assam Rifles near
Ukhrul, about 15 miles west of the Burmese border, killing two
officers and a soldier, the agency said.
   It was the third ambush in the past three months blamed on the
National Socialist Council of Nagaland, an outlawed group fighting
for a separate nation for the Naga tribe. At least 20 people have
been killed in the raids.
   Radicals among the Nagas, a tribe of about 800,000, have been
battling for a separate homeland since the 1950s. In 1963, moderate
Nagas accepted the formation of Nagaland as an Indian state, but
radicals have kept up the battle.
   The rebels have underground bases in Nagaland, Manipur and
neighboring Burma. The paramilitary unit from Assam state and the
Indian army have been trying to quash the rebellion.
</TEXT>
