<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IranHelicopters     07-08 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran Helicopters,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Briton Pleads Innocent To Trying To Smuggle Helicopters to Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British airplane broker pleaded innocent today to
federal charges that he tried to smuggle 10 military-type
helicopters to Iran, and federal authorities said his co-defendant
was being sought in Spain.
   Colin Breeze, 33, of Manchester, England, who is being held
without bond, entered the plea before U.S. Magistrate Linnea
Johnson.
   His attorney, public defender Henry Bugay, criticized the
government's case in comments outside court. The two-count
indictment charges Breeze with conspiring to falsify export
documents and soliciting others to provide false information.
   ``It seems awfully weak to me,'' Bugay said. ``The things they
charge him with don't seem very positive.''
   Breeeze's indicted co-defendant, Graham Reavell, is being sought
in Spain under a federal arrest warrant, according to a source in
the U.S. attorney's office who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   However, the source said that even if Reavell were located, it
was not clear that he could be extradited under the U.S.-Spain
treaty, which may not cover the crimes he was indicted for in Miami.
   Reavell is also believed to be a British subject.
   The two defendants face a maximum sentence on each of the two
counts of 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
   The two men are accused of attempting to re-export 10 Sikorsky
S-76 helicopters now in Jordan to Iran.
   The helicopters, which are ideal for transporting troops under
desert conditions, had been sold by Sikorsky to the Jordanian air
force, U.S. Customs Service officials said. Some were traded back
to the company, but all remained in Jordan and were eventually put
on sale for a total of $6.8 million.
   Breeze, who was arrested June 21 in Fort Lauderdale, allegedly
made arrangements through Iran's ambassador to Spain to sell the
helicopters for $30 million to an Iranian-owned European company,
according to Miami Customs head Patrick O'Brien.
   Other co-conspirators are referred to in the indictment but not
named, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric A. Dubelier, who is
prosecuting the case.
</TEXT>
