<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeathInvestigated     07-08 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Investigated,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Investigating Publisher's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two reporters for the Providence Journal-Bulletin
are investigating the death last year of their publisher, even
though police concluded after a five-month investigation that the
death was accidental.
   Michael P. Metcalf, 54, who also was chief executive officer of
the Providence Journal Co., was found last Sept. 13 unconscious
with head injuries next to his bicycle in Westport, Mass.
   He never regained consciousness and died a week later at St.
Mary's Hospital in Fall River.
   Westport police said the death was accidental.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald Pina agreed to conduct
another investigation at the request of the Providence Journal Co.
His office and state police ended a five-month investigation last
February and came to the same conclusion, although Pina said the
case officially remains open.
   But reporters G. Wayne Miller and Robert Kramer began their
investigation in March and will continue as they think necessary.
   ``We decided there were enough nagging doubts, even after the
Pina investigation, that it would be wrong for us to just sit back
and not do anything, especially about something that was so
mysterious and touched so close to home,'' Carol Young, metro
managing editor of the Journal, told The Boston Globe this week.
   ``We didn't want to wake up two years from now knowing we hadn't
tested it,'' she said.
   Many rumors circulated following Metcalf's death, and Miller
told the Globe: ``Virtually all of them had something to do with
something other than a freak accident.''
   He said the rumors included theories that Metcalf was tripped by
an animal, knocked down by a hit-run driver, or murdered by
gangsters.
   Police estimated Metcalf was cycling at 20 mph, but doctors said
they were surprised he suffered such massive injuries at that speed.
   Steven Hamblett, who succeeded Metcalf as publisher, and
Metcalf's widow, Charlotte Metcalf, said they were not satisfied
with the outcome of the police investigation.
   ``We cannot forget that Mr. Metcalf was publisher of newspapers
known for their investigative stories and editorials on crime,''
Hamblett said. ``This fact, coupled with the unique circumstances
surrounding his death, make it impossible for us to rule out foul
play.''
   Pina said he would welcome new evidence but stood by the
conclusion his office reached.
   ``We don't know why he fell off his bicycle, but the evidence we
have is consistent with the fact that he fell off his bike, hit the
ground with his full body weight on the skull and fractured it,''
Pina said. ``It's a freakish accident, but it can occur....''
   The reporters sent more than 1,000 letters to people who may
have been in the area the morning of the accident, including
participants in a 100-mile bike rally on a route that passed the
spot where Metcalf fell.
   Miller declined to comment on what, if anything, the reporters
have learned so far.
   Metcalf had been publisher of the newspapers since 1979. His
father and his grandfather had been president of the company before
him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Hungary-Strikes     07-08 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hungary-Strikes,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Asked To Legalize Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian trade unions want parliament
to pass a law giving them the right to strike, it was reported
Friday.
   Such a law would make Hungary the first Soviet bloc country in
which strikes would be a legitimate form of worker protest.
   Current law makes a vague reference to the right to ``work
stoppage,'' but strikes virtually are illegal in Hungary.
   The state news agency MTI quoted Sandor Nagy, general secretary
of the Hungrian Trade Union Council, as saying parliament should
pass a trade union law ``with due stipulations ... about the right
to strike and the conditions of taking that industrial action.''
The next parliamentary session is in September.
   Nagy was elected to the post in June as part of the Communist
Party and government reshuffle. The moves followed a party
conference in May at which Karoly Grosz replaced longtime party
leader Janos Kadar.
   For decades, strikes were officially non-existent in Communist
Eastern Europe, and the goverments' official line was that they
were unnecessary because workers are the owners of factories under
Marxist doctrine.
   Strikes have occurred recently, however, in the Soviet Union,
Poland and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
