<DOCNO> AP880708-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Rice     07-08 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Rice,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Finalizes Lowering Of Rice Price</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan decided Friday to lower by 4.6 percent the
price paid to farmers for this year's rice crop, government
officials said.
   The Cabinet decision marks a second consecutive decline in the
producer rice price, which determines consumer rice prices as well.
Japanese customers now pay up to eight times the price paid for
rice in other countries.
   The government postponed for one year a new method to calculate
the producer rice price. Under the new price, producers will
receive $127 for every 132 pounds of rice.
   After going through Japan's complex distribution system, rice
costs about $4 a pound.
   Analysts pointed to excess rice production in the past few years
and the declining consumption as reasons for the price decline.
More than 1.8 million tons of rice are stockpiled.
   ``Excess production is the direct motivation to lower the
price,'' said Masatsune Adachi, an agricultural analyst.
   ``But the bottom line is the appreciation of the yen. The
Agricultural Ministry wants Japanese rice production competitive
enough to endure foreign competition in case foreign demands to
open the market is extended to rice,'' Adachi said.
   Rice is Japan's top agricultural product. The government
controls distribution by buying rice from farmers and releasing it
to the market. The country also bans the importation of rice.
   Japan has been under strong pressure from the United States to
open its agricultural markets, including rice.
   The government's decision to delay the introduction of the new
method is widely attributed to the strong political influence of
the farm lobby.
   Recent agreements with the United States to open Japanese
markets are expected to have a severe impact on Japanese farmers.
Tokyo has promised to open its agricultural markets to American
beef and oranges, which are considerably cheaper than domestic beef
and oranges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
