<HEAD>Manager Fired in Dispute Over Memo Against Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A department store manager has been fired
after company officials accused her of writing a ``racially
derogatory'' memo telling employees to turn away any black
customers attempting to return bed linen.
   Marshall's department store executives also issued a public
apology to Cynthia Sterling, 24, who said she saw the memo at a
checkout stand.
   Sterling, who is black, was trying to return a comforter. A
store employee showed her the memo and walked away.
   It read: ``If any black person returns any sheet sets, refuse a
cash voucher or exchange or credit for any reason.''
   Company spokeswoman Jane Maxwell said the memo was written after
a linen sale.
   In a statement, the company said store manager Eva Vidal
``independently issued a racially derogatory memo'' that ``in no
way reflects the belief, attitudes, or policies'' of the company.
It said Vidal's employment had been ``terminated.''
   Sterling said she had ``a 4-year-old girl who has not stopped
saying, `Why can't we do this, mama, because we're black?' It was
very hard to explain to her that I couldn't do something because I
was black.''
   Efforts to reach Vidal were unavailing. She did not return
telephone messages left on an answering machine.
