<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dolphins     07-08 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dolphins,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Flipper' Trainer Heading For China To Save Endangered River
Dolphins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American who trained dolphins for the
television series ``Flipper'' said he is leaving for China on
Saturday to try to save endangered river dolphins from extinction.
   Ric O'Barry, who has been working with dolphins for 25 years,
said only about 300 freshwater dolphins, or ``baiji,'' remain in
the polluted Yangtze River.
   ``The problem is that 10 percent of the world's population lives
along that river,'' he said in an interview from Hong Kong, where
he arrived Monday from the United States.
   ``It's not a traditional pollution problem involving chemical
waste but animal and human waste,'' O'Barry said.
   The Chinese plan to block off a loop in the Yangtze for a
dolphin preserve. But he said this might not be the solution
because of the Yangtze's pollution.
   O'Barry would like to move the dolphins to Taihu, a lake near
Nanjing on the Yangtze in southeastern China. He believes this
might be the only way to save them from extinction.
   The survival of the river dolphins, he said, ``is not a Chinese
problem but a world problem, a human problem.''
   O'Barry, 48, decided to go to China after a meeting in Miami
with Zhou Kaiya, dean of the Nanjing Normal University, when he
heard about the problems facing the river dolphins.
   He borrowed $3,000 from his 16-year-old son's college fund for
the trip but said he also is looking for corporate sponsorship for
the project.
   ``I don't have a lot of money but I have lots of patience _
that's a necessary tool,'' O'Barry said.
   After arriving in Hong Kong, O'Barry tried to telephone Zhou in
Nanjing, but ``they ... said they had no Dr. Zhou there.''
   Fearing failure in his mission, O'Barry contacted officials of
the World Wildlife Fund in Hong Kong and the conservationist
organization tracked down Zhou.
   From Nanjing, O'Barry plans to take a boat down the Yangtze
River to the Institute of Hydrobiology in Wuhan to see Qi Qi, an
8-foot, bluish grey male dolphin, the only Chinese river dolphin in
captivity.
   As a trainer at Miami's Seaquarium in the 1960s, O'Barry taught
five dolphins to play the part of Flipper on TV.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
