<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PersonalityPoll     07-08 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Personality Poll,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Poll Indicates Voters Want Change But Big Issues Scarce</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The voters want major changes in the nation's
direction but may face a presidential campaign based more on the
personalities of Michael Dukakis and George Bush, a new poll
suggested Friday.
   The Democratic governor of Massachusetts, apparently riding the
desire for change, holds a nine-point lead over Bush in the latest
poll conducted by Hamilton, Frederick and Schneiders, a Washington
survey firm.
   However, Charles Rund, a Republican consultant on the poll,
said, ``Americans are moving faster than their political leadership
is. We may be in for the biggest personality contest _ because of a
lack of big issues _ that we've ever seen.''
   The poll, conducted for the American Medical Political Action
Committee, also suggested that both parties are suffering from the
``sleaze factor,'' a perception of unethical conduct by the
nation's leaders.
   Recent national surveys have put Dukakis' margin over Bush in
single digits, down from a wave of polls giving him double-digit
margins earlier in the spring. The new survey gave Dukakis support
of 50 percent and Bush 41 percent. Nine percent were undecided in
the telephone interviews with 1,502 registered voters June 8-19.
The sampling error for such a survey is three percentage points in
either direction.
   Change is the major thought on the voters' minds, the poll
suggested.
   ``The need for change is driving this election,'' said pollster
William Hamilton. ``They want change but they don't want a
revolution.''
   By a 60-32 margin, those polled agreed that the next president
should ``make major changes ... and set new goals and directions
for the country.'' By a similar 61-31 edge, the registered voters
agreed they want the next president to initiate new economic
policies.
   And Dukakis does best among those who want change the most, the
poll said.
   For example, among respondents who took the strongest pro-change
stance on both questions, Dukakis led Bush 73-19. Among those
taking the strongest pro-status quo position, the result was
reversed, with Bush leading 78-13.
   While the drive for change is broad-based, it is not focused on
specific issues.
   Thirty-five percent named issues closely linking the government
and the economy _ such as the budget deficit and trade deficit _ as
the most critical. That complex of issues was followed closely by
social concerns such as AIDS, the homeless and medical care,
totaling 33 percent.
   Twenty-nine percent mentioned foreign policy and defense matters
and 26 percent talked about drugs and crime. Another 26 percent
cited unemployment and inflation. Respondents were allowed to name
more than one issue.
   The poll said, as others have, that Bush is viewed negatively by
many voters, while Dukakis is not clearly perceived yet by the
public.
   ``Bush has to get Michael Dukakis as a personality into this
race with some negatives on him,'' Hamilton said.
   Voters gave Bush a 53 percent positive rating, but a substantial
42 percent negative one. In contrast, Dukakis drew favorable marks
from 66 percent to only 23 percent unfavorable.
   Democratic strategists have been saying that Bush and
Republicans generally will be damaged in the fall elections by the
sleaze factor _ allegations of wrongdoing and unethical behavior by
Reagan appointees. Bush has been fighting back by pointing to the
investigation of House Speaker Jim Wright's finances.
   The poll suggested that it is losing issue for both parties.
   ``It's tarring everyone,'' Hamilton said.
   Two-thirds of those questioned said the leaders of business,
government and religious groups are less trustworthy and honest
than they were 10 or 15 years ago, up from 58 percent in a poll
taken in July 1987. In both polls, about one out of ten said the
leaders are more honest than they were.
</TEXT>
