<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Newspaper-Defense 1stLd-Writethru a0490 07-08 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspaper-Defense, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede UNDATED</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with newspaper lawsuit denied, Paisley
application rejected.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today rejected a newspaper's
attempt to obtain secret applications for warrants to search and
wiretap the offices of defense consultants under investigation for
alleged procurement fraud.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt denied a request by The
Washington Times to unseal applications for the searches and
wiretaps that he had authorized in the nation's capital.
   Pratt ruled there was a compelling public interest to keep the
material secret until the investigation into contract fraud
proceeds further along.
   Asistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Aronica argued at a hearing that
the Justice Department was seeking to keep the documents under seal
``only for a limited time to permit major steps'' in the
investigation.
   ``We don't have any great dispute for the public's right to
know, what we are saying now is not the appopriate time for that,''
Aronica said.
   Pratt agreed, saying:
   ``All this material is going to be in the public domain in the
reasonably near future. There is no denial of the public right to
know. What we do deny is when that right to know is to be
effective.''
   Jerome Barron, a George Washington University law professor who
represented the newspaper, said the Times had both a common-law and
First Amendment right to obtain the affidavits.
   Barron argued there was a compelling public interest to obtain
information about the contract-fraud investigation. He noted that
the release of an affidavit in Dallas prompted Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci to freeze payment on a number of defense contracts
that might be tainted.
   The Washington Times suit was among several filed by a number of
newspapers in several cities. The Times has another action pending
in Alexandria, Va., where the investigation is based and the
largest number of sealed affidavits located.
   On Wednesday, the Washington Post made a similar request in
Hyattsville, Md., while the St. Louis Post-Dispatch applied for
unsealing in St. Louis.
   Newsday, published in Long Island, N.Y., and New York City,
filed in Brooklyn June 23.
   The Washington Post cited ``a strong public interest'' in
unsealing the documents supporting three searches in Maryland. A
hearing is scheduled for next week.
   The Post said the papers were sealed, presumably because
disclosure originally would have impaired the investigation. But,
said the application, ``these interests, no doubt well-founded in
the first instance, cannot justify secrecy for an unlimited period
of time.''
   Said the Post: ``It is hardly a secret any more that the
government is conducting a wide-ranging probe of defense
procurement practices.''
   The Pulitzer Publishing Co., which publishes the Post-Dispatch,
seeks information about a search of the offices of Thomas Gunn, the
vice president for marketing of McDonnell Aircraft Co., a
subsidiary of McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   The newspaper claims constitutional guarantees of freedom of the
press give it the right of ``immediate access'' to the affidavits.
   U.S. District Judge Clyde S. Cahill in St. Louis issued a search
warrant June 14, authorizing the FBI to seize documents and
computer records related to the work of two consultants, Melvyn R.
Paisley and James A. ``Ace'' Lyons, who have worked for McDonnell.
   Paisley is one of the major targets of the FBI's nationwide
investigation into defense purchases, an investigation called
``Operation Ill Wind.'' He was the Navy's assistant secretary for
research, engineering and systems from 1981 to last year.
   Paisley's application to inspect the application for the warrant
FBI agents obtained to search the office of Paisley Associates,
Inc. was denied during a hearing before Pratt.
   The judge told Paisley's lawyer the application was merely ``an
attempt on your part to find out information the government has
with respect to your client.''
   Pratt, who had originally scheduled a closed proceeding on
Paisley's motion, held the hearing in open court.
   In St. Louis, McDonnell Douglas, an aerospace giant, has denied
any wrongdoing and has promised to cooperate with the Pentagon
probe.
   Cahill allowed the search warrant and the inventory of material
seized in the search to be made public, but he agreed to a request
by prosecutors that the affidavits in support of the warrant remain
sealed indefinitely.
   The U.S. attorney's office said Wednesday that it opposed the
publishing company's request. Release of the affidavits would
disclose classified information and harm national security,
prosecutors said.
   James R. Reed, a corporate spokesman for McDonnell, said the
company had not seen the affidavit but wanted to discuss its
contents with the government before any consideration of its
release.
   Cahill gave prosecutors until Monday and McDonnell Douglas until
Tuesday to respond to the request for disclosure; he said he hoped
to rule by July 18.
   Meanwhile, Judge Pratt in Washington unsealed portions of
affidavits the FBI submitted to search the offices of United
Technologies executive Eugene Tallia and defense consultant William
Galvin last month.
   The unsealed portions do not shed any new light on the
government's continuing investigation. The passages, which the
government did not object to being released, merely describe in
general terms the Pentagon procurement system and the role of
defense contractors.
   Pratt refused a request by United Technologies to review the
rest of the affidavits' contents.
</TEXT>
