<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Heat     07-08 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Heat,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches 31, Another 3,000 Go To Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from a six-day heat wave
rose to 31 on Friday and officials said 111-degree temperatures
sent more than 3,000 people to hospitals.
   The government ordered Athens' 100 biggest factories to reduce
their emissions output by 30 percent to cope with high smog levels
over the city.
   Hospitals nationwide remained on alert to handle smog and heat
wave victims. The National Weather Service said the temperature in
Athens reached 111 degrees Fahrenheit at 3 p.m.
   ``The temperature will remain much the same tomorrow amd we're
expecting it to start dropping on Sunday,'' said a weather service
spokeswoman.
   The National Center for Emergency Help said 3,143 people went to
hospital outpatient clincs with heat related problems and 558 were
hospitalized, most of them with heart and breathing problems.
   A spokesman for the center said six people died of heat stroke
overnight. Coroner Nikos Benardis reported another 10 heat-related
deaths, bringing the total for the past five days to 31.
   ``Three of them were in their 80s and died of heart failure due
to dehydration, while the others had chronic illnesses that were
agggravated by the heat,'' Benardis told The Associated Press.
   The soaring temperatures also forced several hundred people to
seek refuge at a 15,000-seat, air-conditioned indoor sports stadium
in Athens' port city of Piraeus.
   ``Many of them are pregnant women or couples with infants. There
are some elederly people as well. They're coming in steadily,''
said Panayiotis Kontozamanis, the stadium's director.
   Government anti-pollution measures have failed to eliminate a
brown smog mass that has plagued the city for years. Known as the
nefos, the Greek word for cloud, the smog mass forms in the lower
atmosphere on warm, still days.
</TEXT>
