<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Texas     07-08 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Texas,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Cities Duel over Ramses; Dallas Wins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIMI MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dallas beat out San Antonio in a Texas-sized
duel for the right to hold an exhibition featuring artifacts of
Ramses II, one of Egypt's greatest pharaohs.
   Cairo's archaeological circles dubbed it the second ``Gunfight
at the O.K. Corral.''
   Each city was armed with what it considered a valid
letter-of-intent signed by Egyptian officials promising the popular
exhibit of the pharoah who ruled Egypt 3,200 years ago.
   The Ramses exhibit will go to the Museum of Natural History in
Dallas in April and then return to Egypt. A compromise worked out
Thursday won't leave San Antonio empty-handed.
   The San Antonio Museum of Art will be second in line for ``Art
of Ancient Egypt,'' a new exhibition of art treasures from Egypt's
Nile Delta region. The exhibit debuts in November at Washington's
National Gallery and then travels to San Antonio in March 1990.
   ``I think it's a good solution,'' said Zahi Hawass, the
archaeological adviser to Egypt's Minister of Culture who drafted
the compromise.
   The Ramses exhibit opened in Montreal in 1985 and is on display
in Boston.
   The U.S. tour opened in Provo, Utah, in October 1985, and it has
been an attraction at Jacksonville, Fla.; Memphis, Tenn.; and
Denver. It heads to Charlotte, N.C., in September before moving to
Dallas.
   Hawass said the problem between Dallas and San Antonio occurred
because both cities thought the Ramses exhibit was going to their
museums.
   ``Dallas has been interested in Ramses for about two years,'' he
said. ``And there is letter signed by Egyptian officials, which
Dallas considered a letter of intent, and San Antonio later signed
a regular letter of intent.
   ``So we were left with two cities, each wanting Ramses and each
thinking its letter was legal. We had to reach some sort of
solution.''
   Money from both exhibits will help finance a new Museum of the
Egyptian Civilization to be built in Cairo and the Nubia Museum at
Aswan, 615 miles to the south.
   Hawass said Dallas' contract calls for payment to the Egyptian
Antiquities Organization of $750,000, plus $100,000 for the use of
a 27-foot-tall Ramses statue restored by Egyptian and American
experts in honor of the exhibition.
   He said the agreement also calls for the organization to receive
5 percent of profits from the catalog and related items sold in the
museum shop.
   ``In the past Egypt didn't get a proper financial return for its
exhibits sent abroad. The Tutankhamun exhibit that toured England
and the United States is the best example,'' Hawass said. ``We know
every museum hosting such an exhibit makes $10 million to $12
million. Each exhibit draws more than a million viewers.''
   The exhibit featured gold and other items from Pharaoh
Tutankhamun's tomb, which toured several countries in the 1970s.
Egyptian officials complained that contracts were too tightly
drawn, leaving them out in the cold as far as sharing the profits.
   Hawass said the Culture Ministry has decided to demand for
future exhibits a minimum of $850,000, plus 50 percent from the
sale of catalogues and other items.
   ``We take a risk in sending artifacts out of Egypt,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     07-08 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Loyalists Evacuate Last Beirut Stronghold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 120 Palestinian guerrillas loyal to
PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat evacuated a devastated refugee camp
Friday, surrendering their last stronghold in Beirut to a rival
Syrian-backed faction, police said.
   Members of the mainstream Fatah group left Bourj el-Barajneh
camp early in the day for to Sidon, a port city about 25 miles
south of the capital.
   Three leftist Lebanese militias supervised the evacuation at the
request of Sultan Abul-Ainen, the commander of Fatah forces in
Bourj el-Barajneh.
   Bourj el-Barajneh fell to the forces of Col. Saeed Mousa's
Fatah-Uprising late Thursday after more than two months of fighting
between the rival Palestinian factions.
   By police count, about 127 people were killed and 527 wounded
since the fighting began May 1 for control of Bourj el-Barajneh and
the nearby Chatilla camp.
   Chatilla fell to Mousa's guerrillas June 27. A day later, 147
Fatah fighters left the camp for Sidon, where they joined the
Palestine Liberation Organization bases in the area.
   Arafat's loyalists, armed with Soviet-made AK-47 assault rifles
and waving Palestinian flags and photographs of Arafat, emerged
from Bourj el-Barajneh camp at 7 a.m. Friday and quietly boarded
vehicles for the evacuation to Sidon.
   Mousa's men watched from a distance, waving victoriously as
Arafat's fighters withdrew from the camp.
   The evacuees were the last group of Arafat's guerrillas in
Beirut.
   Israel's army invaded the Lebanese capital in 1982 and forced
Arafat and his fighters to leave. Police have estimated that 5,000
hardline PLO guerrillas have filtered back to Lebanon since then,
and most were based in the Sidon region.
   A Syrian first lieutenant and four soldiers in a jeep
accompanied the evacuees Friday from Bourj el-Barajneh to the Awali
bridge at the northern entrance to Sidon. Syrian troops police the
coastal highway connecting Beirut and south Lebanon.
   Representatives of the Progressive Socialist Party, the Lebanese
Communist Party and the Syrian Social Nationalist Party supervised
the evacuation from Bourj el-Barajneh and accompanied Arafat's men
to Sidon.
   The evacuees arrived at Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp and
were greeted by fellow Fatah guerrillas.
   ``The heroes are welcome amongst their brothers,'' chanted a
group of guerrillas, firing their automatic rifles in the air in a
traditional welcome.
   Women threw rice and rose water at the convoy as it drove slowly
into the shantytown, the largest Palestinian refugee camp in
Lebanon with a population of nearly 50,000.
   Abul-Ainen, talking to reporters at Ein el-Hilweh, said Fatah
fighters were ousted from Beirut ``as a result of an
American-Syrian plot.''
   ``The plot aims at finishing the PLO,'' Abul-Ainen charged. He
declineds to elaborate.
   Mousa, with Syria's backing, broke away from the Palestine
Liberation Organization in 1983 and set up headquarters in
Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   Fighting between Mousa's followers and Arafat's loyalists
erupted two months ago despite a reconciliation meeting between
Arafat Syrian President Hafez Assad in April.
   The PLO has claimed Syria, despite the reconciliation, was
behind the effort to drive Arafat's forces out of Beirut. Syria
denied any involvement.
</TEXT>
