<1ST_LINE>u i PM-AfghanBomb 1stLd-Writethru a0642 07-08 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MOSCOW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes in Afghan City; 31 Reported Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Radio Kabul report, details
of blast. Picks up 4th pvs, `On May...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck filled with explosives blew
up in the Afghan city of Jalalabad today, killing 31 people,
wrecking nearby buildings and setting other vehicles on fire, Radio
Kabul reported.
   The explosion ripped through a crowded business district in the
city, the capital of eastern Nangarhar province, the report said.
It was the third bomb in three days to explode in an Afghan city.
   Two car bombs exploded in the capital, Kabul, this week, killing
seven people and injuring several more.
   The Jalalabad blast heavily damaged 45 buildings and destroyed
25 vehicles, Radio Kabul said, quoting Afghanistan's official
Bakhtar news agency. It said the damaged buildings included a
cinema and several shops and homes.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, did not mention injuries.
Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said 33 people were badly
injured.
   Many of the victims were children, Tass said.
   Bakhtar blamed ``Afghan extremists'' for the attack, apparently
referring to guerrillas fighting the pro-Soviet government.
   On May 15, Soviet troops pulled out of Jalalabad to begin the
end of the Red Army's involvement in Afghanistan. The city, about
70 miles east of the Afghan capital of Kabul, has been the scene of
heavy fighting in the country's civil war.
   The Kremlin sent troops and tanks into Afghanistan in December
1979 to back the government. In April, the Soviets agreed to a
U.N.-brokered pact that commits them to pull out the more than
100,000 troops they deployed in Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
