<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     07-08 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Believes Sihanouk Key To Cambodian Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration believes
guerrilla leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk is the key to peace in
Cambodia, according to a letter delivered to him Friday by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   The letter from President Reagan also invited the resistance
leader to visit Washington and reaffirmed U.S. opposition to a
return to power by the communist Khmer Rouge, said State Department
spokesman Charles Redman.
   Shultz and Sihanouk, who once described the United States as
Cambodia's No. 1 enemy, met for 45 minutes Friday in Bangkok, where
both attended discussions between the six-member Association of
Southeast Asian Nations and six allies.
   Shultz told Sihanouk that the United States believed he had a
``central role to play in whatever will be arrived at in
Cambodia,'' Redman said.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in 1978, has pledged to withdraw
all troops by 1990. That would leave a fragile pro-Hanoi government
facing a three-party, Sihanouk-led coalition. The Khmer Rouge,
which killed hundreds of thousands of people during its 1975-78
rule, is considered the strongest force in the anti-Vietnamese
coalition.
   Redman declined to say if Sihanouk had asked Shultz for U.S.
military aid for his own followers in the coalition. Washington
says it supplies only non-military, humanitarian assistance.
   Sihanouk said he was ready to go to Jakarta with his coalition
partners July 25 to take part in informal discussions among the
warring Cambodian factions.
   The 65-year-old Cambodian leader also proposed a national army
which would include all Cambodian factions, helping to neutralize
the Chinese-armed Khmer Rouge.
   Sihanouk's return to center stage is one of many in his career
that has included kingship as a youth; political leadership of
Cambodia in the 1960s and ouster from power by U.S.-backed Gen. Lon
Nol in 1970. He then acted as nominal head of a Khmer
Rouge-dominated front which fought the Lon Nol government.
   Not long after their 1975 victory he was kept under house arrest
by the Khmer Rouge. He was released only to plead Cambodia's case
before the world community as the Vietnamese invasion force neared
Phnom Penh.
   Also Friday, Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda of Thailand
presented Shultz with the Most Exalted Order of the White Elephant,
a royal decoration first issued by Rama IV in 1861.
   On Saturday, Shultz will meet with officials in the Malaysian
capital of Kuala Lumpur and then will fly on to Jakarta, Indonesia.
   In Kuala Lumpur on Friday, about 50 Moslem youths demonstrated
in front of the U.S. Embassy to protest Sunday's downing of an
Iranian airliner by U.S. missile cruiser in the Persian Gulf. The
United States said it mistook the jetliner for a F-14 fighter plane.
   Also Friday, 19 members of Malaysia's Parliament demanded the
release of 42 people being held without trial. Shultz may discuss
human rights issues Saturday with Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
