<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCResidency     07-08 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Residency,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Change Capital Workers' Residency Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Friday to replace a District
of Columbia rule requiring city employees to live in the nation's
capital with a hiring plan giving preference to city residents,
modifying earlier House action that killed the residency rule.
   The Senate approved by voice vote an amendment offered by Sen.
John Warner, R-Va., that would direct the city to adopt a
preferential hiring plan by May 1, 1989, and implement the law by
Sept. 30, 1989, or else forfeit federal money used to enforce the
requirement.
   The amendment, crafted in a flurry of talks late Thursday and
early Friday between Warner and Sens. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., and
Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., came as the Senate debated the district's
$3.2 billion budget for the 1989 fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
   The city is slated to receive $430.5 million in federal money in
1989 to compensate for tax-exempt property the federal government
occupies and the public services it receives.
   Congressional involvement in the city's residency requirement
was sparked by concerns that the law was restricting police hiring
while crime was on the increase. Opponents charged that Congress
was interfering with the city's right to self-governance.
   Rep. Stanford Parris, R-Va., attached an amendment to the city's
House appropriations bill on Tuesday that eliminated the 8-year-old
residency rule. After House Democrats removed a preferential-hiring
clause from the amendment, the measure passed the House by a
246-163 margin.
   The two bills now go to a House-Senate conference to draft a
compromise version. But supporters and opponents of the residency
requirement both praised the Senate's action.
   Opponents of the rule persuaded members of Congress that the
district's high cost of living made it difficult for municipal
workers to reside in the city, leaving crucial positions vacant.
   Police union officials pointed to a steady decline in police
department applications in the midst of a record-level crime wave
in the city.
   Police statistics indicate that crime climbed by 17 percent in
the first four months of 1988 compared with the same period last
year and police blame a surge of drug-related violence for much of
the record pace of 157 homicides.
   There were 107 homicides at this time last year and 228 in all
of 1987.
   Supporters of the rule argued that police applications are
declining nationwide, and that the city's residency rule could not
be blamed for hiring difficulties.
</TEXT>
