<1ST_LINE>r i BC-SalinasText     07-08 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Salinas Text,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text of Speech by Carlos Salinas de Gortari</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the speech by Carlos
Salinas de Gortari claiming victory for the Institutional
Revolutionary Party in presidential elections.
   The speech was made Thursday and translated by The Associated
Press:
   Fellow citizens:
   Yesterday, we Mexicans lived through an extraordinary day. We
showed that we wish to live in peace and in freedom and plot our
own destiny within the framework of the law.
   We have achieved national victory in the election for president.
We have achieved it in one of the most contested elections in our
history and also one of the most peaceful. The national triumph is
clear and without doubt. The information coming to our party so
shows it.
   I want to thank the millions of Mexicans who voted for me for
their confidence and support. My commitment is with all of them
and, from now on, with the nation as a whole.
   I am aware that the enormous and encouraging affluence of voters
and the scrupulous and careful counting by all the parties makes
this a very complex process and, consequently, the official figures
will continue to flow in the hours to come as the law requires, and
I adhered to that.
   I want to extend my recognition for the extraordinary work my
party has done _ to the national leadership and to the state and
national ones. I want to do so especially for the farm, labor and
popular sectors for their sustained efforts while they accompanied
me during this long campaign.
   To the established sectors throughout the republic, I extend to
them my greatest appreciation for their delicate work.
   I reiterate my thanks to the voters who voted for me and my
respect for those who opted otherwise.
   The contest in the election is beginning to show the triumph of
our candidates for the Senate and the House of Deputies and, also,
more triumphs for the opposition than those they have obtained up
to now. I acknowledge therefore the plurality of the country that I
have pledged to respect and encourage.
   The information allows me to observe that the opposition is
showing majority strength in various districts of the country. It
is the new political reality of the nation with which we will have
to live in a harmonious and respectful manner.
   This expression of plurality is a demonstration of Mexico's
democratic progress, and I acknowledge it. The era of practically a
single party is ending, and we are entering now a new political
stage in the life of the country, with a majority party and a very
intense competition from the opposition.
   I have pledged to recognize legal victories by the opposition
and defend firmly within the law those of my party. I will do so
because of my deep democratic conviction and for the unity of the
nation.
   Onward my fellow citizens.
</TEXT>
