<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--PostalKilling     07-08 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Postal Killing,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Suspect Formally Charged In Death Of Mail Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing a rural mail
carrier by choking her with her mail-bag straps will was ordered
held without bond Friday on a murder charge.
   Joseph Williams, 39, of Pinetta, was arrested Thursday in the
death of Immogene Rogers, 42. He appeared Friday before Madison
County Judge Wetzel Blair.
   Mrs. Rogers' body was found June 20 in thick underbrush three
miles south of Pinetta, a small farm community near the border with
Georgia. Her mailbag straps were wrapped around her neck.
   She had completed about half of her 66-mile route, investigators
said. Postal workers had requested a search after receiving
complaints from people on Mrs. Rogers' route that their mail hadn't
been delivered.
   Madison County Sheriff Joe Peavy said Williams is an admitted
crack-cocaine addict whose possible motive for the killing remained
murky. Neither robbery nor sexual assault appeared to have occurred.
   No plea was entered, and no arraignment scheduled.
</TEXT>
