<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugFarm     07-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Farm,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Stiff Sentences For Family Marijuana Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge rejected a prosecutor's plea
for stiff sentences for seven members of a farm family who ran an
elaborate marijuana farm.
   In Montana's early days, District Judge Chan Ettien said
Thursday, ``More than one rancher saved the family homestead by the
manufacture and sale of moonshine whiskey.''
   The Richard Kurth family said it ran the high-tech farm to pay
off farm debts.
   He said the evil of marijuana use ``does not approach that of
alcohol,'' and noted ``an expanding argument that marijuana should
be decriminalized.''
   Ettien sentenced Richard Kurth to 20 years in prison with 15
years suspended. Kurth's wife was sentenced to five years, with the
judge saying she should be held accountable for involving her
children.
   The other five members of the family _ the Kurths' children and
their spouses _ were given suspended or deferred sentences.
Deferred sentences carry no permanent criminal record.
   Chouteau County Attorney Tom Sheehy proposed 30 years for Kurth;
10 years for his wife; 10 for one child; and suspended felony
sentences with some local jail time for the others.
   Sheehy described the marijuana operation as a
``controlled-growing situation, of essentially greenhouse quality''
with timed lights and electronic watering and insecticide spraying
systems.
   Just before the October 1987 raid on the farm, the family had
begun manufacturing hashish oil from the plants, he said.
   Over two years, the family took in about $400,000 for the
marijuana, Sheehy said. Law enforcement officials who raided the
farm estimated the street value of the drugs at $3 million to $5
million.
   The Kurths have maintained throughout the case that they got
into the marijuana business in an attempt to pay off debts on their
farm property.
   Officials estimated that, with good behavior, Richard Kurth
would spend about one year in prison, while his wife would spend
about two months.
   The sentences brought some angry reaction from the farming
community of Fort Benton, where the Kurths ran their operation.
   ``We might as well go out and pull up our gardens and plant
pot,'' Bev Dollar said. ``We're safer doing that than drinking
beer.''
   Mary Lynn Knudsen, who is involved in a local drug task force,
said the sentences send a message to teen-agers ``that just about
anybody could grow marijuana and it's OK. Justice wasn't done
today.''
</TEXT>
