<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan     07-08 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Lee Chosen Party Leader, Boosts His Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui was elected
chairman of the ruling Nationalist Party on Friday in a vote that
strengthens his power in the factional leadership that followed the
Chiang Kai-shek family dynasty.
   Lee is the first native Taiwanese to lead the party in its
94-year-history.
   The 65-year-old Lee was elected at a congress of the party,
known as the Kuomintang, which was formed in 1894 on mainland China
and still claims to be the legitimate ruler of all China. The
Nationalists fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to the
Communists.
   Lee follows Sun Yat-sen, Chiang Kai-shek and his son, Chiang
Ching-kuo, as party leader. He became president and acting party
leader upon the death of Chiang Ching-kuo on Jan. 13.
   The congress also received a discussion paper on China policy
issued by party leaders that proposed only a limited relaxation of
civilian contacts with the mainland. Last year, a ban on travel to
mainland China was lifted so Taiwan residents could visit relatives.
   Overshadowing the official business of the congress, however,
was the surprise appearance of aging Madame Chiang Kai-shek, who
received an emotional standing ovation from the nearly 1,200
delegates.
   Madame Chiang, who is at least 87 and rarely appears in public,
sat on the stage as party secretary-general Lee Huan read her
statement praising elderly party comrades set to retire and urging
the Nationalists not to forget their goal of reunifying China.
   ``We are facing a critical moment as our senior members are
retiring and are succeeded by the new blood,'' she said in the
statement, reminding delegates the old guard's ``contribution to
the party and the state should never be ignored.''
   Wearing a white traditional Chinese dress and black vest, she
shook hands with Lee Teng-hui before leaving the stage.
   All but eight of the 1,184 delegates attending Friday's session
stood up to support Lee's nomination. Jaw Shau-kong, a young
Nationalist lawmaker, did not stand because he wanted a secret
ballot as an expression of democractic change from past practice.
   The congress is the first in which delegates were not picked by
top party officials and in which the Central Committee election
will not be restricted to candidates proposed by the party leader.
   The selection of Lee is the first of several crucial personnel
moves to be made. New faces are expected in the party's
policy-making Central Standing Committee and the Cabinet as some
old-guard Kuomintang conservatives from the Chinese mainland step
down.
   During nearly 40 years of the Kuomintang's authoritarian rule,
Taiwan developed into an export-fueled economic powerhouse. Chiang
Ching-kuo in his final years also introduced democratic change by
lifting martial law and allowing opposition political parties.
   Lee has vowed to continue the democratic trend and also supports
reforming the state-dominated financial system and other
liberalizing moves.
   Polls have shown Lee to be immensely popular as the first native
Taiwanese to lead the country. Native Taiwanese, ethnic Chinese
whose families settled in Taiwan before 1949, account for about 85
percent of its nearly 20 million people.
   Lee's popularity and his efforts not to alienate conservatives
have helped increase his influence as he deals with powerful
Nationalist mainlanders including Lee Huan, Premier Yu Kuo-hwa and
Gen. Hau Pei-tsun, chief of the military general staff.
   In Beijing, China's Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang sent
congratulations to Lee, saying he hoped it would lead to
reunification, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   Taiwan has rebuffed Beijing's overtures to reunify under a ``one
country, two system'' program.
</TEXT>
