<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShieldLaw     07-08 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shield Law,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shield Law Doesn't Exempt Reporters From Eyewitness Testimony,
Court Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Shield Law doesn't exempt
journalists from giving eyewitness accounts when called on to
testify, an appeals court ruled.
   Arguments by lawyers from the Los Angeles Times that a reporter
and photographer were protected from disclosing ``unpublished
information'' regarding an arrest they witnessed were unanimously
rejected Thursday by the three-justice 2nd Appellate District Court
in Los Angeles.
   Reversing a Superior Court ruling, the justices said reporters
have the same duty as any bystander if called to testify about what
they witnessed in public.
   ``I think the Shield Law was never intended to protect news
reporters,'' said Gerry Ensley, a Long Beach deputy city
prosecutor. ``It was intended to protect reporters' confidential
sources.''
   In cases where reporters aren't protecting confidential sources,
``there is no basis to differentiate the newsperson's observation
of the event from that of any other citizen,'' said the opinion
written by Justice Robert Devich.
   The ruling takes effect 30 days from Thursday.
   Times general counsel William Niese said a request for a state
Supreme Court review was likely.
   ``If reporters are converted into automatic witnesses, the
ability of reporters to retain their objectivity and be objective
witnesses ... would be seriously undermined,'' Niese said.
   The case stemmed from the prosecution of a Long Beach man for
alleged possession of brass knuckles in September 1986.
   Sean Patrick Delaney, 21, contended that police never asked his
permission to search his jacket pocket, where officers allegedly
found the weapon.
   Reporter Roxana Kopetman and former photographer Roberto
Santiago Bertero witnessed the search and arrest, but their news
account did not mention whether officers asked such permission.
   Called to testify in Municipal Court, Ms. Kopetman and Bertero
declined to answer questions about whether permission was requested.
   They contended that since the information wasn't included in the
story, the Shield Law protected them from having to answer. Both
were found in contempt of court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Balloons     07-08 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Balloons,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austrian Balloonist Wins Three-Day Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The writer took to the air in a balloon to
gather information for this dispatch.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOVE THE NEGEV DESERT, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Austrian won Israel's
first international balloon race Friday, capping a three-day event
in which more than 40 balloons glided through skies and Israeli
fighter planes buzzed overhead.
   First place earned Hubert Kusternigg $4,000.
   Bill Arras of Redmond, Ore., and Wallace Henderson of Vienna,
Va., took second and third places at the International Hot Air
Balloon Goodwill Fiesta, organized as part of Israel's 40th
anniversary celebration.
   About 40,000 spectators braved scorching heat and dust clouds to
watch the colorful 70-foot balloons, which floated thousands of
feet above Israel's southern Negev Desert.
   On one balloon, competitor Ron Bush rose to about 5,000 feet in
a blue and white striped balloon and then got stuck during a lull
in the wind.
   Bush, 48, of Lubbock, Texas, didn't seem worried when he saw
that he was far from the target and not moving any closer.
   ``It's peaceful up here,'' he said, pushing his Stetson to the
back of his neck. ``I'm doing this for fun, not to win
competitions.''
   The calm was interrupted several times by Israeli fighter planes
which flew loops around the balloonists, sometimes buzzing them
from only 200 feet away.The planes flew in formation, spewing blue
and white smoke, Israel's national colors.
   Forty-one people participated in the race, including 19 from the
United States and competitors from Canada, France, Hungary and West
Germany.
   The competitors were graded on how close they came to a certain
target.
   Spectators thronged the balloonists between races, asking
technical questions and pleading to be taken for a ride.
   Balloonist Alfred Riesser, 40, of Vienna, Austria, said his most
enjoyable moment came when the wind carried him into a nearby
Bedouin tent village.
   ``A little boy was so afraid that at first he threw a stone and
then screamed for his dad,'' Riesser said. ``The adults also didn't
come near us, but then we handed out some stickers with a picture
of the balloon and that broke the ice.''
   Ted O'Hara, 44, an insurance agent from Schenectady, N.Y., said
he was startled Thursday when two men armed with submachine guns
rushed to the landing site as he touched down.
   It turned out they were spectators trying to help him steady the
balloon, he said.
   O'Hara said he was not conerned about his safety in Israel,
despite a seven-month wave of clashes between Arabs and Jews.
   ``I heard there's been shooting in Jerusalem for the last couple
of days but I still think it's safer than in some parts of New York
City,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HendersonRelief     07-08 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Henderson Relief,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Criticize Decision on Federal Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has for a third
time denied aid to residents affected by the May 4 explosion at the
Pacific Engineering plant.
   Gov. Richard Bryan said Thursday he was informed that the third
request for aid was turned down by the Federal Emergency Management
Agency because insurance covered most of the $73 million in
property damage caused by the explosions. Henderson officials have
estimated uninsured damage at $20 million.
   ``I was disappointed and a bit frustrated,'' Bryan said. ``The
federal government makes an appeal to our patriotism, which
Nevadans respond to, and then when a problem arises of this nature,
the federal government says these are problems you have to take
elsewhere.''
   City Manager Gary Bloomquist said he was upset that the federal
government would help rebuild the plant while denying help to those
who suffered damage.
   ``The fact is the plant damaged many people in the area and now
the federal government is going to see it is rebuilt again,''
Bloomquist said. ``That's not reasonable.''
   The blast killed two people and injured 326.
   The government has agreed to pay surcharges on the ammonium
perchlorate produced by Pacfic Engineering to assist in rebuilding
the plant. Company officials have indicated they will rebuild
outside the Las Vegas Valley.
   Ammonium perchlorate is a key ingredient in solid rocket fuel
used in the space shuttle and military rockets. The Kerr-McGee
plant in Henderson is the only facility in the U.S. producing the
rocket fuel oxidizer.
   Bryan said he would continue to make state services available
and urged Congress to create a special fund to compensate victims
of such disasters.
   The cause of the blast remains under investigation.
</TEXT>
