<DOCNO> AP880708-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Moore     07-08 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Moore,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dudley Moore's Arthur Goes On The Wagon In `On The Rocks'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dudley Moore's lovable drunk in ``Arthur''
returns in the sequel ``Arthur 2 On The Rocks,'' just as lovable
but not quite as drunk.
   Moore, who won an Oscar nomination for his portrayal of the
pickled millionaire Arthur Bach, said his approach to the character
this time was different because of a heightened awareness of
alcoholism.
   ``There was no official pressure from the studio or from any
organized groups,'' Moore said in a recent interview. ``But I
personally have an educated awareness of the problem, and there
were discussions on how aware we should make Arthur. It was
difficult to decide, but eventually we decided to make him aware.''
   The producers also avoided any scenes in ``Arthur 2 On The
Rocks'' of Arthur drinking and driving, unlike the original in
which Arthur is seen cruising in his Rolls Royce swigging from a
bottle.
   ``There's a scene in which Linda (Liza Minnelli) says she never
lets him drink and drive,'' Moore said. ``And you can tell that
Arthur knows exactly what he should or should not do. He still gets
very drunk, but that's because he feels panicked and isolated
sometimes and unable to cope with the world.''
   Moore is quick to point out, however, that the film doesn't
preach.
   ``We never intended to make a documentary,' Moore said.
``Arthur's behavior doesn't have to mirror real life.''
   The sequel opened Friday at theaters nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
