<DOCNO> AP880708-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Airliner-F-14s     07-08 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-F-14s,0878</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian F-14s Used Sparingly in Gulf War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Iran, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's small fleet of F-14 fighters has
become one focus of attention in the investigation of why the U.S.
missile cruiser Vincennes shot down an Iranian airliner with 290
people aboard.
   The Pentagon has said transponder signals from the Iran Air
Airbus A300 civilian aircraft caused the warship to mistake it for
an Iranian F-14.
   The American-built fighters, called the Tomcat, are part of a
depleted inventory of combat-ready warplanes that Iran has used
sparingly in its war with Iraq.
   The swing-wing interceptors were one of the most advanced
aircraft in the world when about 80 of them were sold to Shah
Mohammed Reza Pahlavi's air force in the mid-1970s.
   After nearly eight years of warfare, Tehran's F-14 force was
believed to have dwindled to fewer than 10 operational aircraft,
according to some military analysts.
   U.S. officials put their numbers somewhat higher, in ``the
teens,'' and have said in recent days that the force may have been
increased by Iran's success in acquiring badly needed spare parts.
   The Grumman aircraft saw combat action in 1985. Since then it
has been used primarily for its powerful radar systems that can
alert other Iranian fighters to the approach of Iraqi warplanes.
   The operational area of the F-14s was around Iran's Kharg Island
oil terminal in the northern Persian Gulf and over the coastal
sealanes used by Tehran's oil shuttle tankers carrying oil from
Kharg to the Larak island terminal in the Strait of Hormuz.
   On Feb. 9, Iran claimed it shot down three Iraqi jets during a
raid on Kharg.
   Days later, U.S. Assistant Defense Secretary Richard Armitage
disclosed in a Pentagon briefing that one Iraqi aircraft was shot
down by an F-14, using a U.S.-made Sidewinder air-to-air missile.
He said it was the F-14's ``first effective use in combat that
we've seen in several months.''
   U.S. officials said recently that some of the F-14s had been
shifted from the northern gulf to the big military base at Bandar
Abbas on the Strait of Hormuz.
   It was from Bandar Abbas that the Iran Air Airbus took off last
Sunday.
   U.S. sources, who spoke on condition they not to be named, said
Friday that the transfer of F-14s from Bushehr to Bandar Abbas may
have been motivated by Iraq's devastating, long-range air strike on
May 14 on the Larak island terminal in the strait, where
international tankers pick up the oil brought south from Kharg.
   In that raid, the world's biggest ship, the Seawise Giant, which
Iran uses as a storage and transfer tanker, and four others were
damaged.
   The F-14s were airborne in the skies around the strait in the
days prior to the Iran Air incident, but had not taken part in any
combat action. As interceptors equipped with air-to-air missiles,
they are not designed for ttacks on ships.
   In addition to the F-14s, Iran has some aging F-4 Phantoms and
some F-5s, acquired from the United States during the shah's regime.
   Although they watch the aircraft carefully, U.S. warships in the
gulf have not faced many serious threats from Iran's warplanes. The
Iranian fighters generally give the Americans a wide berth, and
observe good radio protocol when challenged, U.S. officers say.
   U.S. commanders have worried most about Iraqi pilots,
particularly in view of the May 17, 1987 attack on the missile
frigate Stark by an Iraqi Mirage, in which 37 American crewmen
died. Washington officially accepted Iraq's explanation that the
attack was a mistake.
   Several subsequent incidents, including one in which a U.S.
missile cruiser Richmond K. Turner came within a second of shooting
down three Iraqi warplanes, led the two governments to work out
procedures to protect U.S. warships from another Iraqi attack in
the northern gulf.
   U.S. officials said they had no information to support a
published report that another U.S. missile cruiser, the Halsey, had
fired a flare in a brush with two Iranian F-14s on July 2 _ the day
before the Airbus disaster.
   ``This is the first we've heard of the Halsey firing a flare or
any of those other details,'' said one source, who has access to
operational reports, and spoke on condition he not be named.
   The Pentagon on Thursday released the transcript of a radio
exchange between the Halsey, on station in the northern Gulf, and
an Iranian F-14 on that same day.
   The brief exchange was presented by the U.S. officials to show
that the Iranians routinely respond to such queries from the U.S.
Navy ships in the gulf.
   The Pentagon says the Vincennes and another U.S. ship issued 12
warnings to the Iran Air jetliner before it was shot down.
   There have been some reports in the aftermath of the tragedy
that the two sides do not routinely communicate by radio.
   ``The idea that the Iranians don't answer our queries is
baloney,'' said one American source. Added another: ``To say that
there are routine exchanges between U.S. ships and Iranian military
aircraft is an accurate statement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
