<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     07-08 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chita Rivera is still ``picking 'em up
and putting 'em down,'' as she calls her dancing, and she's
high-kicking these days in the company of some of the best-known
legs in show business.
   Rivera, who's appearing with 13 members of the Radio City Music
Hall Rockettes in ``Can-Can'' at Caesars Palace, says she hopes her
six-month national tour of the production will help educate the
public about the theater.
   How did she get her start?
   ``I loved music,'' the 55-year-old entertainer recalled. ``But I
was very much a tomboy. I was breaking a lot of furniture so my
mother said she'd better channel this energy.''
   She dreamed of becoming a ballerina, but cast aside her ballet
slippers when she won a part in ``Call Me Madam'' at age 17. Her
1957 performance as Anita in ``West Side Story'' established her as
a Broadway star.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Ronald Reagan turns over the Oval Office
to his successor, he'll already have a place to put his pens and
paperweight.
   The Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation will have a 34th-floor
office ready for the chief executive when it's time to put
``former'' in front of ``President Reagan.''
   The foundation, which is managing construction of the $60
million Reagan presidential library in Ventura County, plans to
move into a new Century City high-rise in the fall, said C. Ronald
Kimberling, foundation executive director. It currently has offices
elsewhere in Century City.
   Terms of the president's lease on the office were not disclosed.
   A group of Reagan associates has arranged for the Reagans to
live in a Bel-Air home after the president leaves the White House.
The couple has already signed a three-year lease with an option to
renew or buy the house.
   The Reagans also have their Rancho del Cielo property in the
Santa Ynez Mountains above Santa Barbara.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hit singles in French and English
are nothing new in West Germany, but Israeli pop singer Ofra Haza
is riding an ``ethno-disco'' craze to the top of the charts with
songs in Hebrew and Arabic.
   ``This is probably the first time that a song in Hebrew has
taken the public by storm,'' spokesman Rolf Hoefler of Saturn
Hansa, one of Frankfurt's largest record stores, said of Haza's
``Im Nin Alu'' (``If the Gates of Heaven Closed''), a catchy blend
of folk and funk.
   Haza's album with the English-language title, ``Yemenite
Songs,'' is also a hit.
   ``It has nothing to do with Israeli music per se,'' Hoefler
said. ``There's just a craze right now for non-European music. We
call it `ethno-disco.'''
   The 31-year-old singer, long celebrated in Israel, learned
Yeminite folk songs from her mother, who is from the Yemen Arab
Republic, the Hamburg-based magazine Stern said in a profile Haza.
Her music is a potpourri of languages, folk and disco sounds with a
funk rhythm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Aya, a grandson of Emperor Hirohito, will
begin a two-year course of study at Oxford University in Britain in
October, the Imperial Household Agency announced Friday.
   Aya, 22, second son of Crown Prince Akihito and Crown Princess
Michiko, will take a graduate zoology course at Oxford's St. John's
College, said Junko Iino, spokeswoman for the agency, which handles
the affairs of Japan's imperial family.
   Prince Aya graduated from the Law Department of Gakushuin
University in Tokyo in March and has been interested in protecting
wildlife, Ms. Iino said. He is scheduled to leave for London in
early August to brush up on his English for two months before
starting coursework.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eugene and Carolyn Shoemaker have become
the most prolific comet hunters of the 20th century, bagging their
14th discovery on Mrs. Shoemaker's 59th birthday.
   The couple discovered their 13th comet on May 13, which tied
them with an Australian astronomer as the most successful comet
hunters of the century. And their 14th on June 24.
   Mrs. Shoemaker said she was scanning photographic negatives of
an asteroid, hoping to find its orbit, when she discovered another
bright, fast-moving object through her stereomicroscope.
   ``It's hard to tell when it's in the Milkyway. There's
wall-to-wall stars,'' she said. ``I decided I'd better let Gene
have a look. `That's a comet,' he said.''
   Comets are chunks of ice and dust that orbit the sun. Between
700 and 800 have been spotted, but as many as a trillion are
believed to exist in the outer solar system.
   Shoemaker, a U.S. Geological Survey research geologist, is
co-investigator on the imaging team of the Voyager 2 spacecraft,
scheduled to pass Neptune next year. Mrs. Shoemaker is an amatuer
astronomer.
   Although they live in Flagstaff, the Shoemakers do their
comet-hunting at Mount Palomar, east of San Diego, using a
wide-field 18-inch telescope to photograph large pieces of the sky.
</TEXT>
