<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Armenians     07-08 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenians,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group of Armenians Angry About US Immigration Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. decision to delay immigration of Soviet
refugees brought bitter disappointment Friday to Armenians who have
waited for years to join relatives in America.
   ``We moved out of our apartments, our homes,'' said Mushegh
Sarafyan, one of about 50 Armenians huddled on a street next to the
U.S. Embassy. ``We sold our clothes and quit our jobs, and now we
are left practically on the street.''
   Sarafyan and the others had come to Moscow from their southern
republic earlier in the week expecting to receive permission to
travel to the United States.
   But embassy spokeswoman Marguerite Squire said the U.S.
Consulate on Monday stopped processing Soviet refugees, most of
whom are Armenians, for travel to the United States.
   ``We want to emphasize this is only a postponement of
departure,'' U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock told reporters.
   Matlock said the U.S. government had run out of money to
resettle Soviet refugees for this fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30.
The process is to resume Oct. 1, when a new fiscal year begins, Ms.
Squire said.
   The embassy in June gave permission to a record 2,063 Soviets,
94 percent of whom are Armenians, to immigrate to the United
States. That was more than all of fiscal year 1987.
   The U.S. government has made Soviet emigration restrictions a
key human rights issue in relations between the two countries, and
the Soviets have eased their policy to permit thousands of citizens
who claim family ties in the West to leave the country.
   ``We are ready to start a new life in a new country and what
happens?'' asked Sarafyan. ``Already they are deceiving us.''
   The 50 Armenians said they had received permission after months
or years of waiting from the Soviet government to emigrate, many
hoping to join relatives in Los Angeles. Los Angeles has a large
Armenian population, and California's governor, Republican George
Deukmejian, is of Armenian descent.
   The Armenians said they had sent telegrams protesting the delay
to Deukmejian and Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Armenia, in the Caucasus Mountains, has been the scene of
strikes, rallies and violence since February as residents demand
control of Nagorno-Karabakh, a region now part of neighboring
Azerbaijan republic.
   The delay affects any Soviet applying to the embassy for
political asylum in the United States. Other than Armenians, the
other major group emigrating, Soviet Jews, generally leave the
Soviet Union on Israeli visas and many then pick up U.S. visas in
Western Europe.
   Sarafyan said the Armenian families now have no place to stay
and few belongings for the three-month wait.
   Matlock called the delays ``very regrettable'' and said the
embassy was trying to warn other Soviets scheduled for departure
interviews of the holdup.
   From Oct. 1, 1987, to this Sept. 30, the embassy expects to
grant 9,500 Soviets, mostly Armenians, permission to resettle in
the United States. From Oct. 1, 1986, to Sept. 30, 1987, 1,800
immigration requests were approved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
