<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Ramones     07-08 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Ramones,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pioneers Of Punk Pith Celebrate 15th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The band that gave the world ``Cretin Hop,''
``Teen-age Lobotomy'' and scores of other short, loud, fast and
somewhat silly punk tunes, is celebrating its 15th anniversary.
   The Ramones _ Joey, Johnny, Dee Dee, and Marky Ramone, who are
not related but took the surname for the stage _ have marked the
milestone recently by releasing ``Ramonesmania,'' a two-record
anthology of their best-known material _ 30 songs all so short they
fit comfortably on one compact disk.
   And except for an occasional guitar solo by Johnny Ramone _ a
lapse some fans equate with selling out _ the anthology shows that
the pioneers of punk pith have stuck to the formula of two-minute,
three-cord head-bangers.
   ``We're a band that our fans can count on,'' Joey Ramone said in
a recent interview. ``We'll always be there for them and won't let
them down. It's nice to hear the fans acknowledge that we aren't
changing, or selling out, or getting soft.''
   Joey Ramone, who wears a mop of black hair exposing only his
mouth and the tip of his nose, said his band is one of about 10
that have ``really captured the spirit of rock 'n' roll.''
   ``I'm very proud to walk down the street and maintain my self
respect, to be told by other artists or fans that they think we're
really great,'' he said.
</TEXT>
