<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ComputerSecurity     07-08 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Security,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Map Strategy For Computer Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of government officials gathered on
Friday to map strategy for safeguarding sensitive information
stored in federal computer systems, ranging from desktop models to
big mainframe facilities.
   ``We must give the federal government's computers a model for
security and reliability,'' said James Burrows, director of the
Institute for Computer Sciences and Technology at the National
Bureau of Standards.
   He spoke to about 700 officials from agencies throughout the
government who met at the bureau's headquarters in suburban
Gaithersburg, Md., to receive formal guidelines for implementing an
ambitious new computer security program.
   Charged with overseeing the program are NBS, a unit of the
Commerce Department, and the Pentagon's National Security Agency,
which for years has issued regulations for protecting classified
information.
   Other lead agencies for the program are the White House Office
of Management and Budget and the Office of Personnel Management.
   The effort is mandated by legislation signed into law early this
year by President Reagan, requiring that agencies establish
computer security training and awareness programs, identify
sensitive computer systems, prepare security plans for each system
and submit those plans to NBS and NSA for advice and comment.
   Due to be formulated by next January, the security plans are
intended to help deal with unauthorized computer system break-ins
by ``hackers'' as well as the threat posed by so-called computer
viruses _ small strings of computer code that can cause computer
programs to go haywire.
   Anthony C. Taylor, a technical consultant to the House Science,
Space and Technology Committee, said a recent survey of federal
agencies by the General Accounting Office had ``confirmed our worst
fears'' in finding that many computer managers are ``largely
unaware of the threats to their systems.''
   He told the meeting that although the danger from hacker
break-ins has been widely publicized, ``far greater damage comes
not from hackers but from insiders'' at agencies who may attempt to
steal, damage or destroy sensitive data.
   The computer security program faces a possible budget squeeze
because Congress so far has been unwilling to vote the additional
$3 million for NBS requested by the Reagan administration to pay
for implementing the program.
   A fiscal 1989 bill passed by the House includes no extra money
for the program, while companion legislation approved by a Senate
appropriations panel would provide only $1 million. Capitol Hill
proponents of the computer security program are expected to press
for full funding on the Senate floor and in a Senate-House
conference.
</TEXT>
