<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MoffordProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0704 07-08 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mofford Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mofford Probe Concluded; No Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 2nd to UPDATE with Mofford statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford will not be charged in
connection with gifts she gave as secretary of state or financial
disclosure statements she filed as a public official, the county
attorney announced today.
   Maricopa County Attorney Tom Collins said technical violations
in the statements were not ``significant in that they did not
involve large amounts of money or personal gain for Governor
Mofford.''
   Mrs. Mofford was not available for comment immediately, but
aides issued a statement on her behalf.
   ``Obviously I am relieved that this investigation has concluded
and I can continue to lead Arizona without any doubts about my
integrity,'' it said. ``It feels good to be exonerated from these
charges because every decision I have ever made in public service
has been for the benefit of the state of Arizona.''
   The gifts, Collins said in a statement, were ``given in the
state interest in Governor Mofford's official capacity'' and ``they
lack any clear element of personal gain in a thoroughly private
capacity.''
   State Attorney General Bob Corbin had asked Collins' office to
investigate omissions from financial-disclosure statements Mrs.
Mofford filed over the last 10 years and at thousands of dollars in
state money that went for gifts and office decorations while she
was secretary of state.
   Sources close to the probe said before the announcement that
investigators had concluded Mrs. Mofford had broad authority to
spend money. They also said the investigators had concentrated in
fairly narrow areas. For example, they said, no one was able to
discover to whom most of the gifts went, so Mrs. Mofford was taken
at her word that they went to appropriate people.
   And while they found some evidence of payments by Mrs. Mofford
of bills that her late husband incurred, sources said the
investigators had been unable to locate a will for T.R. Mofford
that could have helped prove or disprove her claim that items
omitted from her disclosure statements were not really hers because
they were being used to pay her former husband's debts.
   The investigation began after The Associated Press reported in
April that Mrs. Mofford had failed to list numerous land, loan and
partnership dealings in financial disclosure forms covering the
past 10 years.
   As secretary of state, Mrs. Mofford was in charge of ensuring
that forms were easy to fill out. She initially referred to the AP
story as nit-picking, but later filed amended reports, saying she
had made ``an honest mistake'' and didn't feel she had to list some
items because she was using the proceeds to pay off bills T.R.
Mofford incurred after their divorce but before he died.
   The investigation was broadened in May after the AP reviewed
five years of bills from the secretary of state's office and found
more than $50,000 spent on items including a joke-writing service,
kachina dolls and 30 expensive watches.
   The review also found that Mrs. Mofford had bought $10,000 worth
of U.S. and Arizona flags from unauthorized vendors at higher
prices than they could have cost if purchased from state-approved
vendors.
   Mrs. Mofford refused to discuss the disclosures, but said in a
statement that a $2,400 appropriation in her 1980-81 budget for
``other'' items and later lump-sum budgets gave her authority to
purchase gifts for visiting dignitaries, Arizonans who gave
outstanding service and groups that ``advance civic pride.''
</TEXT>
