<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AirlinerRdp Bjt   07-08 1002</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Discounts Radar Flaw as Factor in Airbus Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``minor degradation'' in radar aboard the
USS Vincennes was repaired before the warship entered the Persian
Gulf and played no role in the vessel's failure to correctly
identify the Iranian airliner it shot down last weekend, a Navy
spokesman said Friday.
   Other Pentagon officials said they were awaiting results of an
investigation to learn why the Vincennes missed air traffic
communications and other clues indicating that the Iran Air A300
Airbus was a civilian plane and not an F-14 fighter, as officers
aboard the ship believed.
   The chief of Iran's air force, Brig. Gen. Mansour Satari, told
reporters in Tehran on Thursday that U.S. systems should have been
able to monitor 21 minutes of conversation in English between the
jetliner and the airport control tower in Bandar Abbas, near the
mouth of the Persian Gulf.
   But Pentagon spokesman said they were not sure U.S. forces in
the gulf were monitoring, or were able to monitor, air traffic
control communications at the time of the incident.
   ``We are looking forward to an analysis of the tapes to help
clarify the issue,' said Lt. Cmdr. Chris Baumann, a Pentagon
spokesman.
   As the Vincennes steamed from its home port in San Diego toward
the gulf in May, said Navy spokesman Lt. Brian Cullin, an
unspecified part in the ship's sophisticated Spy-1 radar proved to
be unreliable.
   A replacement was flown to the Arabian Sea, outside the gulf,
the repair made and the Vincennes ``was fully operational on June
6, before she entered the gulf,'' Cullin said. The ship reported to
the battle group in the Arabian Sea on May 22, he said.
   The $1 billion ship's Aegis radar and tracking complex, of which
Spy-1 is part, mistook the Airbus for an Iranian F-14 fighter and
shot it down with all 290 civilians aboard last Sunday. Since then,
Pentagon officials have been trying to figure out why.
   In other developments Friday:
   _President Reagan said the question of compensation for the
families of those killed in the incident is one issue ``under
consideration.'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said there
were ``still some open questions'' on the compensation issue. He
said messages of condolence had gone to the victims' families in
Pakistan, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, India, Yugoslavia and
Italy.
   _Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, said the United States should adopt a new stance in the
Iran-Iraq war ``equidistant'' between the two warring countries.
``I do believe that we'd be much better served in trying to end the
war if we were really in a position of condemning both attacks by
Iran and by Iraq and also condemning the chemical warfare being
conducted against innocent people by Iraq,'' he said.
   At his Tehran news conference, Satari said the downing of the
Airbus showed that the American military was ``unable ... to
control its sophisticated systems.''
   U.S. officials said the mistake was made, in part, because Iran
Air Flight 655 was broadcasting an identification signal on a
frequency used only by military airplanes, as well as sending a
signal on a channel used by both civilian and military aircraft.
   The Iranian general said destruction of the plane was an
``intentional and unprovoked attack,'' but he later qualified this
by saying the U.S. military ``accepted on purpose'' the risk of
shooting down civilian planes because they were unable to control
their sophisticated systems.
   And he said Iran had ``all the tapes needed'' to prove that
normal conversation was going on from the time the engines were
started up on the ground until the plane was shot down.
   The chief Pentagon spokesman, Dan Howard, said Thursday that
Defense Department officials ``don't know whether (U.S. forces in
the gulf) were listening to the control tower or not. We will learn
that in the course of the investigation'' being directed by Rear
Adm. William M. Fogarty.
   Tapes from the Vincennes were flown from the gulf for analysis
in the United States, said Howard. He said the tapes contain data
from the Aegis system, but he was unable to say whether they
included voice communications among the ship's officers, U.S.
commanders in the gulf and in the United States, or any intercepted
Iranian transmissions.
   ``It is probable that their highest priority at the moment was
not listening to the air traffic control radio discussions at
Bandar Abbas, said Howard. ``There are many, many radio
frequencies. ... It would take a heck of a lot of people to monitor
all of them.''
   Howard declined to explain whether U.S. satellites, aircraft and
vessels routinely monitor Iranian radio communications, calling it
``an area of intelligence (that) I won't comment on ....''
   Another Pentagon official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that air traffic conversations are usually carried on VHF
wavelengths, which are best received when the transmitter is within
site of the receiver, as would be the case of an airliner near an
airport.
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe,
said last Sunday that no American surveillance or attack planes
were in the air near the incident, decreasing chances that U.S.
forces might have been able to overhear the air traffic
conversations.
   Crowe also said the aircraft made no voice transmissions after
it was picked by U.S. radar, a statement the Iranian appeared to
challenge.
   Another dispute centered on whether the airliner, which Howard
described as 27 minutes off schedule, was within the commercial air
corridor.
   Howard said the plane was 4{ miles from the center of the
corridor. According to the code governing international air
flights, he said, ``commercial airliners, those carrying
passengers, are expected to adhere to the centerline of the
airway.''
   In Tehran, Satari said the plane was traveling in ``the center
of the international air corridor'' between Bandar Abbas and Dubai
and could have deviated 10 miles either side but still have been
within the corridor.
</TEXT>
