<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsBonds     07-08 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Bonds,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Savings Bonds Sales Drop in June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. savings bonds dropped for the
third consecutive month in June, falling 6.1 percent to $615
million, the government said Friday.
   The Treasury Department said June sales were $40 million lower
than in May. Sales had dropped 0.9 percent in May and 6.4 percent
in April. Before that, they rose for eight months in a row, hitting
$706 million in March. June sales were 13 percent higher than a
year ago.
   With the inclusion of interest earnings, the value of
outstanding bonds rose $510 million to $106.16 billion.
   Since November 1982, savings bonds held five years or longer
earn market-based interest rates. The current rate, in effect until
Nov. 1, is 6.90 percent, down from 7.17 percent in the six months
that ended May 1.
   The Treasury Department began a new program on May 3 to sell
bonds by telephone, selling $1.5 million in May and $1.2 million in
June. Investors can use a credit card to purchase bonds 24 hours a
day by calling 1-800-US-BONDS.
</TEXT>
