<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Hollings-Veep     07-08 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollings-Veep,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Carolina Senator Favors Texan as Dukakis Running Mate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina Sen. Ernest Hollings, who last
month announced he would support presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson in the roll call at the Democratic convention, is
cautioning certain nominee Michael Dukakis against overly
accommodating Jackson.
   ``It was ill-advised under (1984 Democratic nominee Walter)
Mondale and now to fall into this same thing of calling him in is
not well-advised,'' Hollings said Thursday.
   Mondale was accused of pandering to Jackson in an effort to not
alienate black voters during the 1984 campaign.
   While Hollings reiterated his support for Jackson at the
national convention in Atlanta later this month, he indicated he
would not take a lead role in lobbying for him.
   ``I'll certainly have a good word for him,'' Hollings said.
``... I'll cast my vote for him and we'll see what happens.''
   Hollings declined to discuss the merits of those named as
possible Dukakis running mates, including Jackson, but he said he
leans toward Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   The South Carolina Democrat suggested Bentsen could draw votes
away from the oil-dependent states where Vice President George Bush
is strong.
</TEXT>
