<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OilRig-Impact     07-08 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-Impact,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Impact of Worst-ever Rig Disaster Spreads</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Rig, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Piper Alpha platform explosion is expected to
cost insurers more than $1 billion in claims, a spokesman for the
Lloyd's of London insurance market said Friday.
   David Larner, a spokesman for the Lloyd's insurance market, said
the insurance costs ``look as though they could top a billion
dollars. It would make it the largest loss in the North Sea and
probably the largest loss on any one unit.''
   A unit is one item, as opposed to the myriad of related claims
prompted from wider disasters.
   Also on Friday, more than 100 contract workers refurbishing oil
rigs in the North Sea quit over general concerns about safety in
the North Sea oil industry.
   In addition, Occidental Petroleum's stock fell 25 cents more, to
$26 in early trading on the New York Stock Exchange Friday, after
shedding 62.5 cents the day before.
   But oil prices retreated and trading calmed down after hectic
dealings Thursday after the fire broke out on the platform off the
coast of Scotland, killing 166 people in the world's worst oil rig
disaster. The company said it believed a gas leak was responsible.
   In addition to the Piper oil field, five other fields were shut
down, which meant production was cut up to 250,000 barrels a day,
or about one-tenth of the total output of the North Sea's British
sector. A barrel is 42 gallons.
   The oil markets relaxed when they realized that all but the
Piper's production of 167,200 barrels a day should come back fairly
quickly, said Chris Grudniewicz, an oil analyst with the London
investment firm Smith New Court Ltd.
   In the separate West Sole gas field, from 100 to 150 workers who
are employed by a contractor refurbishing three British Petroleum
Co. PLC platforms resigned over safety concerns in the North Sea in
general, BP confirmed.
   A BP spokesman said the workers issued a letter saying they
resigned ``due to current offshore working conditions in general in
the offshore industry.''
   The BP spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
negotiations between the contractor, Press Offshore Services
Division, and its employees were in progress.
   Occidental Petroleum said in a statement Thursday that the
company has ``adequate insurance to handle the situation in the
North Sea.''
   The company insured the rig, plus the costs of any loss of life
claims, salvaging the rig, redrilling and any pollution, Larner
said.
   The $1 billion figure dwarfs the estimated $172 million in
insurance costs for the previous worst North Sea disaster, the 1980
capsizing of the Alexander L. Kielland rig, which killed 123
people, according to Press Association, the domestic news agency.
   Occidental Petroleum said Thursday the destruction of the
platform would cut the company's annual profit by about 5 percent
to 10 percent.
   Occidental's profit in 1987 was $240 million, or $1.06 a share,
on revenue of $17.75 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
