<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate in Virginia agreed today
to give attorneys for defense consultant Melvyn Paisley a detailed
affidavit FBI agents filed to justify searching the former Navy
official's home in the Pentagon procurement fraud probe.
   U.S. Magistrate W. Curtis Sewell said Paisley's attorneys, but
not Paisley, should be allowed to see the government's papers so
they can provide their client with a ``reasonable defense.''
   Sewell's action in nearby Alexandria, Va., came just hours after
U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt denied Paisley
request to see the affadavit that accompanied a search warrant for
Paisley's office.
   Pratt, who sits in 's lawyers theirthe District of Columbia, told the
lawyers'
their request was merely ``an attempt on your part to find out
information the government has with respect to your client.''
   Search warrants were filed in two different jurisdictions
because Paisley lives in McLean, Va., but has an office in
Washington.
   While Sewell said the attorneys could scrutinize the affidavit,
he agreed with the prosecutors that allowing Paisley a look at the
affidavit could allow him to sabotagng business was legally proper.
   Aronica argued that the government wants to keep search warrant
applications under court seal for a limited period of time because
of concern about the ``possibility of the destruction of records as
well as other forms of possible obstruction'' of the investigation.
   Release of the detailed affidivits, which identify ``subjects
and targets'' of the probe, could hinder the investigation, Aronica
said.
   He noted that ``the government does not have possession of all
the documents we believe are relevant to the investigation,''
Aronica said.
   Aronica argued that ``the only reason we are here is because Mr.
Paisley wants to see what the government has on him.''
   ``If and when Mr. Paisley is indicted by a grand jury, the
federal rules of criminal procedure provide the means of
discovering the evience the government has on him,'' Aronica said.
   Barcella said ``the suggestion that destruction of documents
would take place if it (the affidavit) were given to us has no
basis.''
   Paisley was seeking to inspect the affidavit, not place it in
the public record and Barcella said he was willing to abide by any
court order to keep it secret.
   But Pratt said he was concerned about leaks of confidential
information about the case. Given the breadth of the investigation,
the judge said he couldn't guarantee that the Paisley affidavit
would not be leaked.
   The document ``is extremely detailed, it names a lot of names,''
the judge said.
   The investigation focuses on allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former military men,
bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that could be
vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Paisley resigned as assistant secretary of the Navy for
research, engineering and systems in 1987 to become a private
consultant for several defense contractors, including McDonnell
Douglas, Martin Marietta, Pratt & Whitney and LTV.
   His office telephone has been tapped for much of the 18-month
investigation. Pratt noted in court that he has been reading weekly
wiretap reports for 45 weeks, though he didn't specify if they were
about Paisley's telephone.
   The McLean, Va., home of Paisley and his fourth wife, Vicki,
also a defense consultant, was also searched by FBI agents.
   Aronica said the detailed affidavits identify ``subjects and
targets of the investigation, evidence the government has and the
government's theory of the case.''
   Expressing concern about leaks from the investigation, Pratt
cited a report in today's editions of The Washington Post about the
release of wiretap transcripts.
   The Post reported that Aronica's boss, U.S. Attorney Henry
Hudson of Alexandria, Va., is trying to track down who leaked
transcripts of wiretapped conversations to NBC news.
   The newspaper, quoting sources it did not identify, said Hudson
called for the investigation in a letter Wednesday to the Justice
Department's Office of Professional Responsibility.
   ``NBC Nightly News'' quoted the wiretap information two nights
this week. Hudson also requested an examination of other leaks that
have plagued the investigation since it became public June 14 when
federal agents searched more than 40 locations nationwide.
