<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Drought     07-08 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Drought,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canada Is Against Any Diversion of Great Lakes Water</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling Hnatyshyn is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada firmly closed the door Friday on proposals
to divert water from the Great Lakes into the parched Mississippi
Valley.
   Justice Minister Ray Hnatyshyn told Parliament that the Canadian
ambassador in Washington, Allan Gotlieb, would deliver a formal
notice to the U.S. State Department saying that Canada is
unalterably opposed to any diversion.
   The United States has no right to divert Great Lakes water and
cannot expect one, he said. ``There is no consent forthcoming.''
   Illinois Gov. James Thompson has proposed diverting water from
Lake Michigan through the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal into the
Illinois and Mississippi Rivers, where barge traffic is stalled by
low water levels.
   Although Lake Michigan lies entirely within the United States,
such a diversion would affect water levels in the other Great
Lakes, which are jointly managed by Canada and the United States.
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is studying the Illinois
proposal before deciding whether to begin the complex process of
seeking permission from the U.S. Supreme Court to open a lock at
the Chicago canal for the diversion.
   Hnatyshyn said Canada can veto any such proposal as a result of
several treaties. ``We control our resources. We will continue to
control our resources,'' he said.
   Environment Minister Tom McMillan said Thursday that Canada had
been officially informed of the proposal last month and assured of
full consultations. He termed the Illinois plan an ``insane idea''
and noted that other U.S. states bordering the Great Lakes are
against it.
   Opposition parties in Canada have criticized Prime Minister
Brian Mulroney's Conservative government for failing to exempt
water under the Free Trade Agreement negotiated with the United
States last year and now undergoing ratification.
   But in a policy statement, the government said it would never
approve large-scale diversions of water south of the border. Canada
has 9 percent of the world's renewable water supplies, but 60
percent of it drains north toward the Arctic. Ninety percent of the
Canadian population lives within 200 miles of the U.S. border.
   To dramatize the point, voluntary water restrictions are in
force in southern Ontario Province where crops are withering in
95-degree heat because of a prolonged dry spell. Heavy rains this
week in the prairie provinces of Alberta, Saskatchewan and Manitoba
eased a nine-month drought in that farming region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AegisProfile     07-08 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aegis Profile,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vincennes' Aegis Weapons Are Awesome, But Imperfect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's Aegis weaponry is awesome but
imperfect, according to experts trying to analyze how the 6
million-part, $1 billion system came to target an unarmed Iranian
jetliner.
   Some scrutinizing the tragedy this week in the Persian Gulf say
unleashing the Aegis cruiser Vincennes in the tiny, crowded waters
was the equivalent of letting a pit bull protect a playpen.
   Others say the system, a complex mix of radar, computers and
weapons, did just what it was designed to do: destroyed a presumed
hostile target on an apparent attack course.
   The target, thought to be an Iranian F-14 fighter, was actually
a civilian Airbus with 290 aboard. All were killed in the incident
Sunday.
   Questions have been raised, like why Aegis' super-sophisticated
technology could not separate civilian from military air traffic,
or distinguish a 63-foot-long fighter from a 176-foot airliner.
   The Navy and the key Aegis contractor _ RCA Corp. of Moorestown,
N.J. _ have given only limited answers.
   The technology, at sea only five years, is said to be able to
track some 200 targets from as far as 250 miles. So effective is
the system that crewmen on the first Aegis ship coined the motto,
``If it flies, it dies.''
   But there are problems, say experts, including Aegis' missile
marksmanship, its complex maintenance and its effectiveness in
close quarters.
   ``It is not meant to be sitting in the Potomac next to National
Airport,'' said one congressional staffer.
   The Persian Gulf, with its constant mix of civilian and military
traffic, may be too cramped for the system, said Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   ``The Aegis cruiser is essentially a blue-water ship that was
operating in a brown-water lake,'' said Nunn.
   In theory, experts surmise, the Vincennes' control-room screens
could show civilian routes and even expected flights. The Navy has
not said what flight information the crew had.
   The USS Ticonderoga, the first Aegis cruiser, acted as a ``de
facto'' control tower off Lebanon in 1983, according to its
combat-systems officer. The ship's Aegis systems ``routinely''
sorted out air traffic, Cmdr. James McClure wrote in a 1985 issue
of the naval journal ``Proceedings.''
   Experts say the Vincennes radar consoles likely showed the
Airbus as hostile, since Aegis _ like other anti-air warfare
systems _ has to assume unidentified targets may be enemies.
   Released by Vincennes Capt. Will Rogers III, the emotionless
Aegis let fly SM-2 Standard missiles. One found its mark.
   One Capitol Hill expert insisted Aegis is the world's best naval
system for fighting in cramped quarters. ``It's more suitable
because you can wait longer,'' said the researcher, who asked to
stay anonymous.
   Still, the Vincennes' skipper ``had about four minutes from the
time they picked up this target until it was declared hostile,''
Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said Sunday.
   That gave Rogers little time to do anything but trust his
computers, analysts said, and decide to protect his crew of some
300 and the billion-dollar ship.
   Pentagon officials say Rogers justifiably concluded the Airbus
was an enemy based on its flight path, its failure to identify
itself, and its confusing broadcast on both civilian and military
frequencies.
   ``They had a lot of indicators, all of which added up to enemy
aircraft,'' said Rep. H. James Saxton, R-N.J., in whose area Aegis
is assembled and tested.
   The information was likely flashed in white symbols on the blue
backgrounds of the four, 42-inch-square ``battle picture'' screens
in the Vincennes' Combat Information Center.
   The screens, providing a dim, unwordly glow in the windowless
chamber, do not show aircraft as traditional radar blips.
   Navy officials have declined this week to let reporters view an
Aegis display. But one expert says the boards designate planes by
showing circles around friends, diamonds around foes and squares
around unknowns.
   In trying to tell friend from foe, the system relies on aircraft
to emit, or ``squawk,'' their identities. Humans, using the system
as a tool, must make the ultimate decisions.
   ``It's not designed to classify targets,'' the congressional
staffer said. ``It's just designed to detect and track them.''
   Ironically, he said, an experienced radar operator using a less
sophisticated system might have been able to tell an Airbus from a
fighter by comparing the size of blips.
   During Aegis first combat deployment, the Ticonderoga's
computers reportedly failed to see a small, incoming plane visible
to the naked eye. In 1986 hostilities off Libya, the Aegis cruiser
Yorktown targeted and shot at what some analysts say was nothing
more than a dense cloud on the water's surface.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
