<DOCNO> AP880708-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SinaiForce     07-08 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sinai Force,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multinational Observer Force Gets New American Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wat T. Cluverius, a retired State Department Middle
East specialist, has taken over as director-general of the
multinational observer force in the Sinai, the force said Friday.
   Cluverius, 53, assumed the leadership of the Multinational Force
and Observers on Tuesday.
   The group, with headquarters in Rome, monitors compliance with
the military provisions of the 1979 Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty
with an observer force in the Sinai.
   Cluverius succeeds Peter D. Constable, another American, upon
completion of his four-year mandate, said MFO spokesman Frank
O'Halloran.
   Cluverius, a Massachusetts native, most recently served in the
State Department as a senior adviser for Middle East peace. A
former ambassador to Bahrain, he also served as a deputy assistant
secretary of state in the bureau of Near Eastern and South Asian
Affairs and, from 1983-85 as consul-general in Jerusalem.
   The director-general is appointed jointly by Egypt and Israel.
</TEXT>
