<DOCNO> AP880708-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Softball     07-08 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Softball,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soweto Softball Player Denied Visa To Watch Games In Canada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black softball player on
Friday appealed for help from Canada's prime minister after being
refused a visa to attend an international softball tournament in
Saskatchewan.
   Albert Ramovha was denied a visa because of the international
sports boycott of South Africa.
   Ramovha, 32, said he had been saving money since last year for a
ticket to Canada. The Soweto resident said he hoped ``to witness
softball at its best and learn new techniques to teach my brothers
and sisters back home.''
   Bill Farrell, a diplomat who handles visa matters at the
Canadian Embassy in Pretoria, said Canadian officials advised that
Ramovha could not be issued a visa because of boycott.
   The boycott normally applies to competitors. Ramovha wanted only
to watch the world championship that starts in Saskatoon at the end
of July, but Farrell said officials in Ottawa feared Ramovha might
be viewed as an official representative of the South African
Softball Federation.
   Ramovha, who plays and umpires softball, belongs to the black
federation and serves on a committee of umpires.
   Farrell also said Ramovha had been offered accommodation and
meals by the tournament organizers, thus putting him in a different
category than an ordinary spectator.
   ``He doesn't have to be on the field pitching to be seen as an
official representative of his federation,'' Farrell said.
   Ramovha, who works at a truck rental company near Johannesburg,
said he sent a Telex today to Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
appealing for reconsideration of his application.
   Ramovha said he had applied for the visa in February and did not
get a reply until June 30. In the interim, he said, he had borrowed
$1,400 to buy an air ticket, shifted his vacation dates and shopped
for the trip.
   ``I really feel frustrated and destroyed morally,'' Ramovha said
in the message to Mulroney.
   ``Allow me to learn,'' he wrote, appealing for a chance to
``visit your democratic land and learn not only more about softball
but about your way of life.''
   Softball has been played in South Africa since 1946. The
federation to which Ramovha belongs has about 4,000 members,
virtually all of them black. The 3,500-member South African
Softball Association is predominantly white despite being open to
all races.
   The International Softball Federation, which is based in
Oklahoma City and is sponsoring the Saskatoon championship,
suspended South Africa in 1975 as worldwide anti-apartheid pressure
increased. But Ramovha said the federation had encouraged him to
attend the tournament as an individual.
   ``My fellow Sowetans are aware of my intended trip and they are
also eager to learn from me,'' Ramovha said in his Telex. ``They
will be most disappointed to learn I cannot visit Canada.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
