<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-SaltyRiver     07-08 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Salty River,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$4 Million Worth of Oyster Beds Open After 20 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials opened thousands of acres of
oyster beds that were closed for 20 years because the
drought-slowed Mississippi River is carrying less sewage and
industrial waste into the Gulf of Mexico.
   The lack of moisture over the Midwest and Plains has left the
Mississippi flowing past New Orleans at about 114,000 cubic feet
per second, about a fourth of its normal flow. Upriver, barges run
aground on newly bared sandbars; downriver, a wedge of saltwater is
edging upstream from the Gulf toward drinking water intakes at New
Orleans and neighboring communities.
   ``The river is very polluted when it's flowing normally,'' said
Jim Cosgrove of the state Department of Health. With the river flow
dropping, it's spewing less pollution into coastal areas where
oysters grow.
   Plaquemines Parish officials estimate that about $4 million
worth of prime oysters soon will be heading to the market from the
areas opened Thursday.
   ``There's always perhaps a silver lining to the big clouds,''
said Ron Dugas of the state Department of State Wildlife &
Fisheries.
   ``It looks real good,'' said oysterman Kenny Fox of Pointe a la
Hache. ``These are quality oysters _ salty and fat and very
productive.''
   Fox has had leases in Cox Bay for 20 years, but pollution had
kept him from harvesting a single oyster.
   Plaquemines Parish officials had been monitoring the areas daily
for about three weeks. Recent samples showed that the counts of
fecal coliform bacteria had dropped from double digit numbers to
almost nothing.
   In another indicator of the river's weakness, biologists from
Louisiana State University say saltwater fish are making their way
up the Mississippi ahead of the leading edge of salty seawater
flowing upstream beneath the lighter river water.
   Without the river's normal flow pushing the saltwater back to
the Gulf, the tip of the wedge of saltwater was at New Orleans,
about 100 miles from the mouth of the river, and saltwater fish
were netted about 35 miles farther upstream.
   Sheepshead and saltwater catfish are among the species reported
caught by fishermen, and LSU researchers say they have caught
menhaden, flounder and Atlantic rays 130 miles from the mouth of
the river.
   Catching saltwater fish in the area of LaPlace is unusual, said
Allen Rutherford of the LSU School of Forestry, Wildlife and
Fisheries.
   Saltwater fish including sail catfish also are being caught by
fishermen in the Atchafalaya River 10 miles upstream from
Sherrington, said Sandy Corkern, LSU marine advisory agent. The
Atchafalaya also empties into the Gulf of Mexico.
   The Army Corps of Engineers said the tip of the saltwater slid
by mile 99 _ three miles past the city's water intake at Algiers _
on Thursday.
   The bulk of the saltwater is 20 miles behind the tip of the
wedge. Salt water hugs the bottom because it is heavier than the
river's fresh water.
   The Corps hopes to slow the salt's advance from the Gulf of
Mexico by constructing a dam of dirt 15 to 25 feet high across the
river bottom near Myrtle Beach, 32 miles downstream from Canal
Street.
   On Thursday, Gov. Buddy Roemer declared a state of emergency for
Orleans, Jefferson, Plaquemines and St. Bernard parishes. All draw
their public water supplies from the river, and are making special
preparations to combat the salt.
   Several industries below New Orleans have begun barging millions
of gallons of water a day to maintain operation.
   Salt concentrations at Chalmette, 10 miles downstream from New
Orleans, reached 129 parts per million Thursday. The federal
standard for safe drinking water is 250 ppm, but that is out of a
concern for corrosion and taste rather than health effects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
