<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Burma     07-08 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Burma,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Released Following Detention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday released 394
people, including 59 students, who had been detained as a result of
rioting in Rangoon in March and June, state radio announced.
   With the release of the detainees in Rangoon, Pegu, Prome and
Moulmein, ``all those detained in connection with the March and
June riots in the country have been freed,'' the radio said.
   The latest release brings the total of detainees freed in recent
days to 784, including 288 students, 22 government employees and
474 others.
   The report said that students expelled from various
universities, colleges, schools and instutitions will be readmitted
to their respective educational institutions. All educational
institutions in Burma are state-owned.
   The government closed almost all universities and institutions
of higher learning in the wake of riots in the past few months, and
imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew in Rangoon.
   The protests, three since October, appear to reflect mounting
opposition to the authoritarian rule of strongman U Ne Win, who
seized power 26 years ago in a military coup.
</TEXT>
