<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Emergency     07-08 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Emergency,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Branstad Declares ``Disaster Emergency'' Because Of Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Terry Branstad declared a statewide
disaster Friday because of the drought, saying experts had told him
Iowa faces the loss of half of its corn crop, the bedrock of its
economy.
   ``We clearly have a statewide disaster on our hands and a
disaster of national proportions as well,'' Branstad said.
   ``This drought came much quicker and hit much harder than
anything we've had before. This is certainly appropriate action in
light of the severity of the problem.''
   The declaration frees state vehicles for transporting feed and
water, allows use of the National Guard for well drilling or
hauling water, and waives some restrictions on transporting
oversized loads of hay.
   Also, state agencies begin spelling out disaster plans,
including water allocation plans if needed.
   Branstad also asked federal officials to open low-interest loan
programs and other disaster aid for drought-stricken farmers, and
said he hoped to make that case in person to President Reagan next
week.
   ``It is a natural disaster that is beyond the control of any
state,'' he said.
   Iowa joins Indiana, Missouri and Ohio in declaring statewide
emergencies because of the drought.
   ``There is no question the 1988 drought is one of the most
severe Iowa has ever experienced,'' Branstad said.
   Last year, Iowa was the nation's leading corn-producing state,
turning out 1.3 billion bushels valued more than $2 billion.
   The governor's decision came after he met with a task force of
farm experts earlier Friday and was urged by the state's
congressional delegation to take the step during a lobbying trip to
Washington on Thursday.
   ``It looks like the corn crop will be cut in half,'' Branstad
said. ``The best estimate we have at this point in time is that we
will have nearly a 50 percent loss.''
   ``We are the leading corn producing state, it's a very important
crop in this state and a loss of this magnitude is very
significant,'' Branstad said.
</TEXT>
