<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RoofCollapses-Gonzalez     07-08 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roof Collapses-Gonzalez,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Crawled Deep Into Rubble Does Not Consider Himself A Hero</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Roof Collapses Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freddie Gonzalez, who used his wiry
4-foot-8 frame to save lives Friday by crawling deep into the
dangerous rubble of a collapsed department store, considers himself
just another volunteer.
   Gonzalez, 34, was one of hundreds of people who flocked to the
site of the store. In the humid summer heat of the Rio Grande
Valley, he crawled into the teetering mass of concrete and steel,
all that was left of the Amigo Store.
   ``We went in through a little hole. We kept going in deeper and
deeper and making it bigger and bigger, digging it out with our
hands, and we found the people,'' Gonzalez said. ``We went right up
to them and pulled them out by their legs.
   ``We kept hearing them crying in there, so we kept digging and
digging. They were all tangled with wire and pieces of wood,'' he
said.
   Gonzalez works for Brownsville Equipment and Maintenance, the
company that will probably end up clearing the shattered block.
Shirtless and sweaty, he stayed at the accident scene all night
until 11 a.m. Friday.
   ``It was a little bit hot. The people were running out of
oxygen. That was their major complaint. We ran a little tube
through a small hole. Then we made a bigger hole and put in a
bigger pipe'' to get oxygen to the trapped survivors, he said.
   What if people call him a hero?
   ``No. Everybody did it,'' Gonzalez said.
</TEXT>
