<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndependenceDeclared     07-08 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Independence Declared,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Training School Residents Push For Freedoms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some residents at a school for the
mentally retarded said Friday the state had failed to live up to an
agreement aimed at moving more residents into community-based group
homes.
   A consent decree signed in 1986 sets as a goal 100 community
placements a year from the Southbury Training School. Just 35 were
placed in the year ending June 30, the residents said.
   ``I want to have my own apartment so I can be on my own,'' said
Mirabel Silva, a resident at the school for six years.
   Thomas J. Monroe, who lived at the school 11 years before moving
into a group home and then to his own apartment, said the issue was
one of civil rights.
   He said that almost all the 1,048 people living at Southbury
could make it on their own with the proper support services in the
community.
   The residents ``should be treated as people, not as a vegetable
or a dog on a leash,'' he said.
   ``Some of these people shouldn't be here now,'' he said,
gesturing to those at a news conference in an auditorium at the
institution. But, he said many people ``don't want group homes in
their communities.''
   School Director Steven D. Staugaitis, who spoke on behalf of
state Department of Mental Retardation officials, said the
residents' frustration is understandable. ``They were promised
something and they didn't get it,'' he said.
   He conceded that the state has complied with as much of the
consent decree as it can, but that support services, such as
nursing and therapy, are inadequate in most communities.
   Anne Rotzal, a woman whose son, Alan, has lived at Southbury for
29 years, scoffed at the notion of having virtually everyone move
out of the training school.
   ``Those that can go out, God bless 'em. They should go out,''
she said after listening to the news conference. But, she said,
it's not for everyone.
   Staugaitis said not all residents want to leave. Some have been
there more than 40 years and fear such a change, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
