<DOCNO> AP880708-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PotatoScandal     07-08 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Potato Scandal,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami Agent Pleads Guilty To Bribery Charge In State Potato Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The colorful mastermind of a North Dakota
seed-potato sale to Honduras that went sour and rocked state
politics pleaded guilty Friday to bribing a former key official in
the state Agriculture Department.
   William Messner, who helped arrange the deal two years ago as
president of a Miami-based trading firm, admitted Friday he gave
the department's former marketing director a $5,000 Caribbean
cruise and as much as $4,000 in cash for business considerations.
   Sentencing was deferred under a plea agreement under which he
can avoid jail and in which he also agreed to pay the state
restitution for expenses.
   Messner boasted the former director, Laurence McMerty, had made
him ``millions of dollars'' by using him as a middleman in the
state's effort to market North Dakota farm commodities in Central
America, according to Deputy Attorney General Bruce Quick.
   ``I think, if we were to sum this case up, is that it involves
the great expectations of most, the good intentions of some, and
the disappointment of all,'' Quick said.
   McMerty, who also faces two bribery charges, has pleaded
innocent and has not been trying to strike a deal with prosecutors,
Quick said. McMerty's trial has been set for Sept. 7. His attorney,
Orell Schmitz, declined comment Friday.
   The case is credited with ruining the political career of
Agriculture Commissioner Kent Jones, a Republican who was denied
endorsement for his third term in office because of the lingering
scandal.
   State officials had initially envisioned selling 4 million
pounds of seed potatoes to a Honduran farm cooperative within a
year after contracts were signed in June 1986.
   But the deal collapsed after Attorney General Nicholas Spaeth
raised questions about its financing, and the state has never been
paid for the only 400,000-pound potato shipment that was actually
delivered.
   McMerty has charged Spaeth and Gov. George Sinner, who are both
Democrats, helped to sabotage the potato deal and were bent on
using it for political gain. Both men, who are running for
re-election this year, deny the charges; Sinner declined comment
Friday.
   Jones became embroiled in the controversy when he and Herbert
Thorndal, former president of the state-owned Bank of North Dakota,
signed a $300,000 note meant to help finance the deal.
   Messner later sold the note to a Miami bank for $264,000,
putting $180,000 of the money in his personal bank account to cover
overdrafts, Quick said.
   Spaeth contends Jones and Thorndal had no authority to issue
either the $300,000 note or a subsequent $1.55 million note, signed
by Thorndal, that was given to Messner and later returned to the
state.
   Quick said Friday there were no grounds to prosecute Jones or
Thorndal.
   Messner was to have gone on trial Tuesday in Grand Forks on two
bribery charges. The felony counts were consolidated into one
charge Friday as part of a plea arrangement.
   Associates of Messner quoted him as calling the state officials
he dealt with a ``bunch of idiots,'' according to investigative
documents made public in the case. The associates said Messner
bragged of having ``the papers to rape, steal and pillage'' after
he set up the potato deal, according to the documents.
   The plea agreement calls for Messner to pay the state $60,888.38
in restitution, which Quick called the state's ``out-of-pocket''
expenses in connection with the sale.
   Messner will not have a felony conviction if he abides by the
agreement and completes three years of supervised probation without
incident, said his attorney, Michael Hoffman.
   Messner, who spent six months in jail after his arrest in
November, will not have to serve additional jail time if he
complies with the plea agreement, Quick said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
