<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CBSSchedule     07-08 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Schedule,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Sets Fall Schedule Due to Writers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS announced a fall schedule including
miniseries, original movies, and specials Friday despite the
writers' strike.
   Kim LeMasters, the network's entertainment division president,
said CBS is concerned about the strike and its impact, but added,
``We are nonetheless ready and able to program strong original
product for the fall season.''
   NBC and ABC have announced parts of interim plans to fill the
prime-time schedule in spite of the shutdown of motion picture and
television production caused by the 18-week Writers Guild of
America strike. CBS had said earlier the debut of its fall schedule
would be delayed by the walkout.
   LeMasters said CBS had a number of animated, entertainment and
news specials, and sports events for airing.
   ``The Cavanaughs,'' starring Barnard Hughes and Christine
Ebersole, will return on CBS with original episodes Aug. 8 and
continue into October. ``First Impressions,'' starring Brad
Garrett, Thom Sharp and James Noble, will debut Aug. 27 and run
through October.
   In addition, three original episodes of ``Murder, She Wrote''
will be presented.
   LeMasters said CBS had more than 30 made-for-TV movies and it
would telecast films Sundays, Tuesdays and Fridays. The network
also has a number of major theatrical films, such as ``Out of
Africa,'' ``Agnes of God'' and ``Cocoon.''
   Twelve hours of miniseries are available for the fall:
``Internal Affairs,'' starring Richard Crenna and Kate Capshaw;
``Dadah Is Death,'' starring Julie Christie; and ``Jack the
Ripper,'' starring Michael Caine, Armand Assante and Jane Seymour.
   CBS also has its first animated miniseries, ``This is America,
Charlie Brown.'' The first two hours will be telecast in the fall,
with the second two hours to come later.
</TEXT>
