<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-MassachusettsJobs     07-08 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Massachusetts Jobs,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts No Longer Has Lowest Jobless Rate Among 11 Most
Populous States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Unemployment,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in more than four years,
Massachusetts in June failed to have the lowest unemployment rate
among the nation's 11 most populous states, so Democratic Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis is losing a standard line in his presidential
campaign speeches.
   The government reported Friday that while the nation's civilian
jobless rate dropped 0.3 percentage point to a 14-year low 5.3
percent last month, unemployment in Dukakis' home state climbed to
3.5 percent from 2.8 percent in May.
   It was the first time since February 1984 _ before the collapse
of world oil prices _ that Massachusetts has not had the lowest
jobless rate of the 11 most populous states, according to the
Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   Texas then had the lowest rate, 5.6 percent, compared with 5.7
percent for Massachusetts.
   Last month, New York matched Massachusetts' 3.5 percent jobless
rate and North Carolina dropped below it, to 3.2 percent from 3.5
percent in May.
   Massachusetts officials attributed the June increase in the
state's unemployment to a flow of out-of-school teen-agers coming
into the labor market.
   Private analysts, while cautioning not to put too much store in
one month's figures, said it is the inevitable reaction to the
economic boom that Massachusetts has had over the past five years
and that Dukakis has been touting in his presidential campaign.
   ``Growth in Massachusetts has slowed down, there's no doubt
about that,'' said Roger Brinner, a labor market specialist for
Data Resources Inc. of Lexington, Mass.
   ``But not even the most ardent Republican would try to claim
that the Massachusetts miracle has become the Massachusetts
debacle,'' he said. ``If it holds at 3.5 percent or rises to 4
percent over the next several months, it will be shoved under
Dukakis' nose. But one month's figure is not enough.''
   Marlene Seltzer, director of the Massachusetts Division of
Employment Security, said 70 percent of the 112,000 people
unemployed in the state last month had been jobless for less than a
month, indicating many of them were new entrants in the labor
market.
   By comparison, only 47 percent of the nation's unemployed had
been jobless for less than a month, indicating a much smaller share
of people seeking jobs for the first time and unable to find them
in June.
   Larry Chimerine, president of the WEFA Group, a Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., economic forecasting firm, said it is impossible to draw any
conclusions about Massachusetts' economy from one month's
employment numbers.
   ``The monthly state-by-state rates are so unreliable because of
the small samples they are based on that I would not believe there
was a fundamental change occurring until I saw it continue for
several months,'' he said.
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist for the National Association
of Manufacturers, said he has seen no evidence of slackening demand
for workers in the state.
   ``Dukakis is really having some poor luck recently,'' Jasinowski
said of the figures. ``I'm getting reports that labor shortage
problems are greater in Massachusetts than any other state in the
country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
