<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0755 07-08 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0755,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifteen Guards Injured During Melee At Trenton State Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with no weapons found, lack of motive. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen guards were beaten Friday in a
planned attack by inmates at the maximum-security Trenton State
Prison, officials said.
   Corrections spokesman James Stabile said 14 prisoners were
charged in the beatings. The prison was closed to visitors, he
said, and inmates were locked in their cells following the
disturbance.
   Stabile said no prisoners were injured.
   He said the melee broke out in the mess hall about 7:15 a.m.
when an inmate struck a corrections officer from behind. An
undetermined number of prisoners joined in, punching and beating
other guards, Stabile said.
   There were 300 prisoners in the mess hall, he said.
   About 10 minutes later, inmates in another wing of the prison
surrounded and attacked guards, he said.
   By 8:30 a.m., other guards had restored order. Stabile said the
lockdown will continue until an internal investigation is completed.
   The injured officers were treated at St. Francis Medical Center
for broken bones, lacerations, possible concussions and puncture
wounds. All the guards were later released, he said.
   ``They had been beaten pretty badly,'' Stabile said. He said the
attacking prisoners ``went for the head.''
   ``Officers were down and guys were pummeling them,'' Stabile
said.
   No weapons were found, he said.
   Stabile said officials had not determined a motive, but that it
appeared some prisoners planned the attack and others joined
spontaneously.
   Fourteen inmates were charged with disciplinary violations. If
convicted, they face up to a year's loss in commutation time, 364
days in lockup with only limited privileges and 15 days in solitary
confinement.
   Stabile said corrections officials also will seek criminal
charges.
</TEXT>
