<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Kirk-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0711 07-08 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kirk-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Chairman Says Bush May Have Broken Campaign Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush comment, subbing 2 grafs for 2nd graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk said Friday
that Vice President George Bush may have used tax money on campaign
trips, and he questioned whether Bush can make any more trips in
the next month without violating federal spending limits.
   Bush denied Kirk's allegation, calling it ``an outrageous
charge.''
   ``We are not abusing the public trust,'' Bush said in Atlanta,
arriving for a fund-raising event several hours after Kirk's
remarks.
   ``We've bent over backwards to be within the letter, certainly
the spirit of the law,'' Bush said to reporters traveling on Air
Force Two with him from Washington. Friday's trip was political and
financed as such, aides said.
   Kirk made his statements at a news conference in Atlanta and in
a letter delivered to President Reagan's counsel, A.B. Culvahouse,
asking for ``immediate attention.''
   He also said the party may complain to the Federal Election
Commission.
   ``The only thing that matches the hypocrisy of the Republican
Party of the 1980s claiming to be the party of fiscal conservatism
is the Republican Party of the 1980s preaching about law and
order,'' Kirk told reporters.
   He said Bush, the expected Republican presidential nominee, may
have violated the law by using vice presidential funds for campaign
trips to Louisville, Ky., and Columbus, Ohio.
   Even if the Bush campaign pays for the trips, Kirk said, it may
be exceeding the limit for campaign expenses in the pre-convention
period.
   Kirk said Bush should disclose how he intends to pay for any
further campaign travel before the Republican National Convention
in August and whether he intends to borrow against the money
allocated for the post-convention campaign.
   Reminded that 1984 Democratic presidential nominee Walter
Mondale exceeded his pre-convention spending limit, Kirk said, ``In
1984, we learned a lesson. We'd like for both parties to come to
this issue with clean hands.''
   Kirk's news conference was held in the same hotel as a
Republican ``Unity '88'' meeting that the vice president was to
address later Friday. Bush representatives attended Kirk's news
conference to distribute copies of a response from Bush campaign
manager Lee Atwater.
   Atwater said the Louisville and Columbus trips were paid for by
the Bush campaign.
   ``Mr. Kirk is wrong on the facts, and I challenge him to come
forward with something more than political innuendo if he wants to
level accusations against this campaign,'' Atwater's statement said.
   Kirk's statements ``are totally without merit and are obviously
designed to distract public attention from the real issues of the
last two weeks _ Mike Dukakis' compulsion to raise taxes and his
reckless prison furlough program which has released first-degree
murderers and rapists onto the streets of America where they can
continue their reigns of terror,'' Atwater said.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the Reagan
administration is ``scrupulously careful in determining who pays
for political activities. This sounds like more political hot air
to me.''
</TEXT>
