<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-08 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Violence Trials Transferred out of Azerbaijan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legal cases against people who took part in
ethnic riots in the Azerbaijan republic were moved Friday to courts
in the Russian federation, as Armenians had demanding for months.
   Armenians say courts in Azerbaijan would be too lenient because
of ethnic bias.
   The Soviet Supreme Court and the prosecutor's office ordered the
transfer.
   Courts have been investigating riots Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijani
port of Sumgait in whch 32 people were killed, 26 of them ethnic
Armenians. Most of the suspects are believed to Azerbaijanis, who
differ in culture and religion from Armenians.
   Most Armenians are Christian and Azerbaijanis are predominantly
Moslem.
   Soviet officials have said more than 80 people have been charged
in the unrest in the Caucasus, in which six Azerbajanis have been
killed and 200 people have been injured.
   Pending cases involve premeditated murder, robberies and ``mass
disorders,'' according to the Friday announcement by the high court
and prosecutor's office.
   The announcement, read during the national evening television
news program Vremya, did not say why the cases were being
transferred, but Moscow officials may feel Russian courts would be
less prejudiced.
   Azerbaijan's Supreme Court on May 16 convicted an Azerbajiani
metalworker of murder in the rioting and sentenced him to the
maximum 15 years in prison.
   The riots sprang from a dispute over control of
Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian mountain enclave in
Azerbaijan. Armenians demand that the area be made part of their
southern republic.
   The dispute has also led to strikes and street rallies. The
latest round of strikes in Armenia began Monday, apparently
prompted by dissatisfaction with a national Communist Party
conference that failed to resolve the dispute.
   Soviet newspapers reported Friday that some Armenians have
returned to work after a general strike that has paralyzed Yerevan,
the capital of Armenia, but that a walkout persists in
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Armenia's Parliament has endorsed the annexation demand, but
Azerbaijan has balked. Armenia asked Moscow to intervene.
   On Monday and Tuesday, demonstrators stormed Yerevan's airport,
and one was killed by a plastic bullet fired by Soviet troops.
   The disturbances disrupted 65 flights, the newspaper
Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya reported. It said $16 million a day
was being lost in industrial production.
   The labor newspaper Trud said a strike in Stepanakert,
Nagorno-Karabakh's main city, had cost $64 million in lost
industrial production and that factories elsewhere in the Soviet
Union were suffering because Stepanakert enterprises failed to
deliver $32 million worth of supplies.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported the Stepanakert strike
continued Friday.
   But some workers were back at their jobs in Yerevan. A broadcast
journalist, speaking from Yerevan by telephone on condition of
anonymity, said about half of the city's public transport began
running Friday. Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya said food-producing
enterprises were operating.
</TEXT>
