<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nancy-Book     07-08 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy-Book,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Taps Ghostwriter of O'Neill, Mayflower Madam Books</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan has tapped one of the nation's
premier ghostwriters, Bill Novak, to help her write her memoirs,
the White House revealed on Friday.
   Novak has helped several personalities create best-selling books
about their lives. His credits include ``Iacocca,'' the
autobiography of Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca; ``Man of the
House,'' the political memoirs of former House Speaker Thomas P.
``Tip'' O'Neill, and ``The Mayflower Madam,'' the story of Sydney
Biddle Barrows, who detailed her life running a high-class
prostitution service.
   Mrs. Reagan, who has regularly kept a diary of her White House
days, will meet with Novak ``on a regular basis'' in order to
produce the book by the fall of 1989, said Elaine Crispen, Mrs.
Reagan's spokeswoman.
   The first lady has indicated that she might use her memoirs to
settle a few scores.
   The White House was embarrassed earlier this year when President
Reagan's former chief of staff, Donald T. Regan, used his book
``For the Record,'' to reveal that the first lady relied on an
astrologer to help formulate the president's schedule. Regan also
contended that Mrs. Reagan formed a cabal to force him from office
at the height of the Iran-Contra scandal.
   Although the first lady has staunchly refused to discuss the
issue of stargazing, she told reporters during the Moscow summit
that she intended to deal with it ``my way,'' in her own book.
   And, Mrs. Reagan contended, the former chief of staff will
``absolutely'' be interested in her version of the story.
   The first lady traveled to New York this week to make the
arrangements with her publisher, Random House, Mrs. Crispen said.
   Mrs. Reagan reached an agreement with the publisher in 1986 to
write the story of her personal life and her marriage to the
president, but no announcement has been made about an advance made
to the first lady, Mrs. Crispen said.
</TEXT>
