<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BeachesClosed     07-08 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beaches Closed,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Waste Closes Down Beaches; Weekend in Jeopardy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY55</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WANTAGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lifeguards tried a new way of protecting
swimmers Friday: keeping them off beaches altogether as medical
waste once again washed ashore.
   With temperatures in the 90s, Jones Beach and Robert Moses State
Park beach were closed because officials decided a ban on swimming
would be insufficient to ensure no one was hurt by the debris.
   The only people on the beach were cleanup crews searching for
additional garbage floating ashore _ bad news for the state and
concessionaires, who say the weekend after July 4 is traditionally
summer's biggest. A crowd of more than 100,000 would normally be
expected at the state beaches.
   ``It's really a creepy feeling sifting through this stuff,''
said Sharon Moynahan, 18, who assisted in the cleanup. ``I'm trying
to be really careful. I don't want to catch anything.''
   Ron Foley, Long Island regional director for state parks, said
no decision on reopening the beaches would be made until Saturday.
Officials wanted to see what the next tide brings.
   Jones Beach was reopened 4 p.m. Friday _ more of a token gesture
than anything else, as it was set to close at 7:30 p.m. and did not
mean beaches would be open Saturday, officials said.
   The assortment of syringes, bandages and blood vials could have
entered the ocean through the sewer system, either when washed off
a street or dumped into a sewer, said Environmental Protection
Agency spokesman Richard Cahill.
   ``We don't believe this is the result of illegally dumped
hospital waste,'' said Randy Braun, an EPA worker who examined the
ocean water by helicopter.
   James Marshall, another EPA spokesman, said debris collected
Thursday and Friday included fewer than three dozen syringes. Also
found were three blood vials, and numerous vials associated with
crack use, he said.
   Mixed in with the medical waste has been garbage consistent with
beach usage, littering and sewage overflow, he said.
   Although hospitals everywhere have to deal with the problem,
federal environmental officials say these kinds of incidents appear
to be confined to New York and New Jersey.
   ``We haven't found anything like this anywhere else,'' said J.
Winston Porter, the federal Environmental Protection Agency's
assistant administrator for solid waste.
   The garbage recovered from the beaches will be turned over to
the office of U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney to determine if it
can be traced and whether criminal charges are called for, said
U.S. Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y.
</TEXT>
