<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-08 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0678,0789</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Stabs Four Israeli Jailers, 10 Palestinians Ordered Deported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 16-20 pvs, ``They were ... the army said.'' with
7
grafs to UPDATE with another Arab reported wounded in Nablus,
details; picks up 21st graf pvs, ``Troops barred ...'' Minor
editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian teen-ager concealing two knives
under a flowing robe stabbed four Israeli guards Friday in a Gaza
Strip prison where he was pretending to visit his brother.
   The army ordered 10 Palestinians deported from the occupied
lands in apparent retaliation for the attack, which a prison
spokesman said was linked to an underground Islamic fundamentalist
group.
   One Palestinian was killed in a clash with army troops in the
West Bank.
   In a statement, the army said the deportees played ``a central
role in planning and carrying out'' anti-Israeli actions in the
territories in recent months.
   After Friday's stabbing in Gaza City's Central Prison, troops
chased the 17-year-old assailant and arrested him, said prison
spokesman Johnny Tester.
   Arab reports identified the youth as Yassir Mahmoud Al Khawajah,
a butcher from the Gaza Strip town of Rafah.
   Tester said the teen-ager was a member of fundamentalist group
that the army believes planned the attack.
   Two jailers were in serious condition, one with knife wounds to
the chest and head, and the other with stab wounds to the chest,
Tester said. A third guard had moderate wounds to the chest and the
fourth was slightly wounded in the face.
   Tester said the teen-ager, dressed in a traditional Arab robe,
approached the jailers during visiting hours, then pulled out the
knives and attacked them.
   The youth pretended he wanted to visit his jailed brother but
``he really came for the sake of attacking, not to visit anybody,''
Tester told The Associated Press.
   One of the wounded guards, Amiram Ravivo, told Israel radio he
was writing down the names of Palestinian visitors when the
assailant attacked.
   ``Just as I raised my head I saw someone coming at me with a
knife. I managed to grab his hand, then I tried to get up and he
slashed my face,'' Ravivo said.
   The army statement said six of the deportees are from the West
Bank and four from Gaza. They have all served prison terms for
anti-Israeli actions in the past and some are still in jail.
   ``All 10 are activists in the various terrorist organizations,''
the statement added, referring to factions of the PLO.
   No date was given for when they would be expelled and the
statement said the men would be allowed to appeal the order to a
military advisory board and to the Supreme Court.
   They were the first Palestinians ordered deported by Israel
since it expelled American-born civil disobedience-advocate Mubarak
Awad on June 13, claiming he also played a role in the Arab
uprising.
   Israel has expelled 21 Palestinians since the uprising against
Israeli occupation of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip began Dec. 8.
   Also Friday, soldiers shot and killed a 22-year-old Arab in a
clash with stone throwers in the West Bank town of Tubas, hospital
officials said. At least five Arabs were wounded as clashes erupted
in Tubas, the West Bank city of Nablus and Gaza on a ``day of
confrontation'' called for by uprising leaders.
   The army said the military was investigating the Tubas death,
which raised to 216 the number of Palestinians killed since the
uprising began. Four Israelis also have died.
   Among those reported wounded were two Palestinians who were shot
in a clash later Friday outside the Farah refugee camp near Nablus.
   Jamal Al Kadoumi, 26, was shot in the neck and crashed his
vehicle, Arab reports said. He was rushed to a Jerusalem hospital
in critical condition. A second man, Ahmed Ayyoub, 22, suffered a
bullet wound in the right hand, the reports said.
   The army said it was investigating.
   Palestinians in Nablus heeded a general strike called for by
Islamic fundamentalist leaders, blocking roads with rocks, burning
tires and ordering merchants to close their shops, Arab reporters
said. Three Palestinians were wounded in a confrontation with army
troops.
   Troops barred Palestinians from entering Jerusalem to prevent
violent protests called for by underground leaders during prayers
at the city's Al Aqsa mosque, one of Islam's holiest sites.
   In an underground leaflet, uprising leaders ordered Palestinians
to ``observe holy Al Aqsa day ... by striking painful blows at the
occupation forces.'' But the army measures and a police force twice
the size of normal succeeded in preventing protests at the mosque.
