<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackMemo     07-08 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Memo,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Store Manager Fired For Racist Memo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Venius cq 5th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A department store has apologized and
fired a manager over a memo that told employees to turn away black
customers who tried to return linen, but civil rights groups
remained outraged over the incident.
   Frank Arnone, president of Marshalls discount stores, said
Thursday he was ``personally embarrassed and appalled.''
   ``I apologize to Miss (Cynthia) Sterling and every person who
has been so greatly offended,'' said Arnone.
   A sympathetic Marshalls employee had pointed the memo out to
Sterling when she tried to exchange an $80 comforter on July 2 to
get clothes for her daughter.
   The memo, posted under glass at a cashier's counter, read: ``If
any black person returns any sheet sets, refuse a cash voucher or
exchange or credit for any reason.''
   Eva Vidal, a store manager, implied that the comforter had been
stolen because Sterling didn't have a receipt, Sterling said, but
declined to check store records. Vidal was fired for writing the
memo, company officials said.
   The local chapter of the NAACP plans a meeting to discuss the
incident and a possible boycott of the Woburn, Mass.-based company
with 297 stores.
   ``I think it's outrageous, for something like that to take place
in this day and time in southern Alameda County,'' said Venius
Winn, president of the Hayward National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People. ``In my observation, we've come a
long way and still have a long way to go.''
   ``I have a 4-year-old girl who won't stop asking, `Why can't we
do this, Mama? Because we're black?' It's very hard to explain to
her that I couldn't do something because I was black,'' said
Sterling, a 24-year-old former kindergarten teacher.
   Vidal did not respond to messages left by The Associated Press
on her telephone answering machine.
   Oakland attorney John Burris said he has filed a complaint with
the Alameda County district attorney's office consumer complaint
division. He said Friday he is trying to find out if others were
victimized and whether the store may have similar but more subtle
policies in other departments.
   Arnone said Marshalls will also investigate to determine if the
incident was isolated.
   Burris said Sterling was ``not happy at all'' with the apology,
which she felt came only after the problem was publicized. Vidal's
firing was appropriate, he said, but the apology ``might not be
enough.''
   Lucy Flores, 29, of Union City, who was in line with Sterling,
said she was also angered by the memo. ``A lot of customers were
just tripping over this, looking around at each other,'' she said.
   The company's regional operations director, Dave Nielsen, said
Marshalls is an equal opportunity employer and that another manager
of the Newark store is black.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
