<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-08 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sizzling Temperatures in Ohio Valley and Great Lakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Another sizzler hit much of the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes
states Friday, and temperature records again fell in more than a
dozen cities.
   Pittsburgh's 99 degrees broke a mark that had stood since 1876,
and the mercury in Akron, Ohio, also rose to 99, breaking a record
set in 1893.
   Other record high temperatures for the date were set in Alpena,
Mich., 100; Binghamton, N.Y., 94; Buffalo, N.Y., 95; Elkins, W.Va.,
93; Flint, Mich., 98; Harrisburg, Pa., 100; Huntington, W.Va., 101;
Knoxville, Tenn., 99; Mansfield, Ohio, 97; Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.,
97; Wilkes-Barre and Scranton, Pa., 97; South Bend, Ind., 97;
Williamsport, Pa., 99; and Youngstown, Ohio, 97.
   Heavy thunderstorms occurred in central Colorado and
southeastern Wyoming, and a tornado watch was in effect Friday
night for parts of those two states and Nebraska. A flash flood
watch also was issued for the eastern foothills of Colorado.
   West-central Texas got heavy rain, with the heaviest falling in
Andrews, where there were numerous reports of flooded intersections
in low-lying areas and stalled vehicles. Up to 7 inches of rain
fell in southeastern Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered throughout parts of the
Plains and upper Mississippi Valley. Heavier thunderstorms in
Nebraska caused some streams to run up their banks and leave
standing water in fields.
   While numerous record high temperatures for the date were being
set, some record lows were broken: Apalachicola, Fla., 67;
Montgomery, Ala., 63; Pinson, Ala., 56; Tallahassee, Fla., 59.
   The low temperature for the nation Friday morning was 31 degrees
at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 110 degrees at Palm Springs,
Calif.
   The National Weather Service predicted showers and thunderstorms
scattered across the Florida peninsula, parts of Texas, Oklahoma,
Kansas and Wisconsin on Saturday. Showers and thunderstorms also
were forecast in parts of Colorado, Arizona and New England.
   High temperatures likely should be in the mid to upper 80s
throughout the Plains and parts of the Missisippi Valley. The Great
Lakes, Ohio Valley and Atlantic Coast states were expected to see
highs in the 90s. Some temperatures should soar to near 100 in the
upper Ohio Valley, and between 100 to 110 in the desert Southwest.
Highs in the 70s to 80s were expected along the Pacific Coast.
</TEXT>
