<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     07-08 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Report Bombing Runs Along Front; Supertanker Afire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq reported making jet bombing
runs along their southern war front on Friday, and the Tehran
government accused Iraq of dropping chemical weapons on three
cities in the region. Iraq denied it.
   The Persian Gulf itself again turned into an arena in the nearly
8-year-old war. The burning Greek supertanker Fellowship L was
under tow in the northern gulf late Friday, almost 24 hours after
it was attacked in Iraqi raids on shipping off Iran.
   Shipping executives in the gulf and in London said flames were
extinguished aboard the 215,780-ton Cypriot tanker Star Ray,
another victim of the Iraqi raid.
   They said no injuries were reported on either ship.
   Gulf-based executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
they believe another Greek vessel on charter to the Iranians also
may have been hit. The executives said they feared the Iraqi air
raids off Iran may provoke Iran to retaliate on commercial shipping
elsewhere in the gulf.
   Tensions in the oil-rich region already ran high because of the
downing of an Iranian civilian airliner Sunday. All 290 people on
board were killed when U.S. naval missile fire downed the jetliner
in the belief it was an attacking warplane.
   An Iraqi military spokesman reported the latest raids on three
``maritime targets'' Thursday in a statement quoted by state-run
Baghdad radio.
   Since early 1984, Iraq has been attacking vessels sailing to and
from Iranian ports as part of a blockade to throttle the oil-based
Iranian economy. The targets were mainly tankers.
   Iraq's objective is to force the government of Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini to accept a negotiated peace in the war between
the two gulf oil powers. Iran retaliates by attacking any merchant
vessels in the gulf, regardless on whether it's doing business with
Iraq or not.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which
monitors maritime traffic around the world, said the two tankers
were attacked Thursday night off Iran's Kharg Island oil terminal
at the head of the waterway.
   Gulf-based shipping executives, and the London-based Lloyd's
Shipping Intelligence Unit which monitors maritime traffic around
the world, said the two tankers were raided overnight off Iran's
Kharg Island oil terminal at the head of the waterway.
   It said the Fellowship L was struck at 9:10 p.m. about 30 miles
south of Kharg as it was southbound after loading a shipment of
crude oil.
   It said the engine room and crew quarters were set ablaze in the
attack, while on the Star Ray, fire broke out in the bow.
   Lloyd's later reported that the fire aboard the Fellowship L was
partially extinguished and that the tanker was under tow but that
firefighting was still in progress. It said the fire on Star Ray
had been put out.
   Both tankers are on charter to Iranian oil authorities, part of
a shuttle fleet that ferries the Kharg oil to the Larak makeshift
export terminal, about 500 miles southward in the Strait of Hormuz,
to circumvent the blockade.
   The United States deployed its Navy in the gulf last summer in
order to protect 11 Kuwaiti tankers flying the American flag.
Several other Western navies protect their own flag vessels
carrying cargo through the gulf.
   The Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi jets and helicopter gunships
flew a total of 265 combat missions along the 730-mile front Friday
and that all aircraft returned safely.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, as was INA, issued a war communique saying Iranian
warplanes flew nine sorties, ``inflicting heavy casualties and
losses on the enemy'' at troop concentration points along the
northern and southern fronts.
   IRNA also reported that Iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs
on the cities of Khoramshahr, Abadan and Khosrow-Abad at the same
time the areas were ``subjected to heavy artillery fire of the
Iraqi troops.''
   Iraq's official news agency later put out a communique saying
such action and saying Iraqi targets Friday were limited to oil
installations and tankers.
</TEXT>
