<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NorthernIreland     07-08 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Attacks Kill Four, Including One of Its Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA claimed responsibility
Friday for two bombings and two mortar attacks that killed four
people, three of them by mistake.
   The attacks killed two civilians, a British soldier and one of
the Irish Republican Army's own men. The outlawed IRA apologized
for killing the civilians, both Roman Catholics.
   Ten civilians, including a 4-year-old girl and her grandmother,
were injured.
   Eighty families had to be evacuated when a mortar barrage missed
a police station and damaged a primary school and several houses,
police said.
   In a statement to Belfast news media, the IRA said a bomb at a
swimming pool in west Belfast was accidentally triggered Thursday
evening in an ``operation that went tragically wrong.''
   The IRA, fighting to end British rule and unite the mainly
Protestant province with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish
Republic, extended its condolences to relatives of those killed.
   Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's legal political wing Sinn
Fein, denied that the IRA changed its policy of targeting the
security forces, saying ``it wasn't an attack on civilians, it was
an accident.''
   But Dr. Joe Hendron, a leader of the moderate Catholic Social
Democratic and Labor Party, whose offices are near the swimming
pool, replied: ``Sickening apologies mean nothing to the dead and
injured. IRA savagery is with us again.''
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said the bomb, planted against the
enclosing wall of an indoor public swimming hall, apparently was
meant to bring the wall down on a security patrol passing outside
on the predominantly Catholic Falls Road.
   Instead, it killed civilians Elizabeth Hamill, 60, and Eamonn
Gilroy, 24.
   Among the four injured were Ellen McCormick and her 4-year-old
granddaughter, Ciara Burns.
   Mrs. McCormick said they went to buy ice cream and were walking
past the pool ``when the wall seemed to come out towards us. Ciara
started to scream and there was blood running all over me. She had
blood on her dress.''
   Both suffered cuts to the legs and other minor injuries.
   Seven hours later, a British army bomb disposal expert helping
to clear the area was killed yards away by another bomb, police
said.
   Unconfirmed reports said Warrant Officer John Howard's foot set
off the explosion. He was the 400th soldier to die in nearly 20
years of violence in the province.
   The IRA said one of its member, Seamus Woods, 22, died in a
mortar attack on a police station at Pomeroy in County Tyrone early
Friday. One shell exploded inside the station's perimeter fence but
caused little damage, police said.
   Woods' body was found in a field outside town, near a tractor
and trailer used in the attack, police said.
   The officers said that since police fired no shots, Woods' death
apparently was connected with the mortar fire itself.
   A second mortar attack 15 minutes later missed the police
station in Stewartstown, about 10 miles away, but damaged a primary
school and houses. Six civilians suffered minor injuries, police
said.
</TEXT>
