<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     07-08 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson: No Veto Over Dukakis' VP Choice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Friday he has no veto over the
running mate Michael Dukakis will pick and he doesn't want to
appear to have one.
   Jackson made the comment in the process of distancing himself
from his campaign manager's disparaging remarks about Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. as a possible Democratic vice presidential candidate.
   The civil rights leader, who has been pushing for an offer of
the No. 2 spot himself, said his campaign does not have a veto over
Dukakis' choice and does not ``choose to exercise the appearance as
though we have a veto over anyone in the process.''
   As for his own chances, Jackson spoke in terms of knowing the
rules and fitting qualifications.
   ``The issue is not so much who will be in office _ who will be
governor, who will be on the Supreme Court _ as that there are
rules, based on a tradition, on which we have been locked out,'' he
said.
   ``The hoop is too small,'' he said. ``I may not fit the rules,
but I know what they are, I can teach them to my children and they
will learn.''
   His comments on not having a vice presidential veto were in
reaction to a Boston Globe story. It said Gore had become a leading
contender and quoted Jackson campaign manager Gerald Austin as
saying such a choice by Dukakis would outrage Jackson supporters
and increase the Republicans' chances of winning black votes in the
November election.
   Jackson told reporters Austin was speaking only for himself.
   ``I have not made any negative statements, either privately or
publicly, on any value judgment'' concerning potential vice
presidential candidates, Jackson said. ``I think it would be
unethical to do so.
   ``Throughout our campaign, we have kept a moral tone'' on the
subject, he said. ``We will keep talking that way because it's good
for the process, it's good for the party, it's good for the
country.''
   Jackson was in Dallas to address the same League of United Latin
American Citizens convention that Dukakis and likely Republican
presidential nominee George Bush spoke to earlier this week.
   He drew cheers from the group when he declared that if Bush is
serious about helping Hispanics he should be calling for
appointment of one to replace Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Bush promised the group on Wednesday that he would appoint a
Hispanic to his Cabinet if elected president. But Jackson said if
that's so, Bush should recommend ``right now an Hispanic to replace
Ed Meese.''
   ``Bush came through here the other day talking about his
conversion to a new religion _ respecting Hispanics is a new
religion of his,'' Jackson said.
   On the subject of vice presidential considerations, Jackson told
reporters that his campaign staff attempted to call Dukakis'
campaign manager Paul Brountas late Thursday night, but Brountas
then called Jackson Friday morning.
   ``He was coming here for us to have a meeting,'' Jackson said.
``And he said he is still accumulating data and responding to the
data, and we will meet at some subsequent time, not very far from
now for a rather extended oral interview.''
   Jackson said putting him on the ticket as Dukakis' running mate
would give voters a balance between two candidates of divergent
economic and geographic backgrounds, he said. But he also said it
was Dukakis' decision _ if the Massachusetts governor is confirmed
as the presidential nominee.
</TEXT>
