<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Landslide     07-08 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Landslide,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landslide Kills 41 In Northwest China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landslide crashed through an ethnic Tibetan
community in northwest China and killed at least 41 people, the
official Xinhua News Agency said Friday.
   Xinhua said the landslide came after a rainstorm and buried
homes under mud and rocks Wednesday in Jone, a county seat in a
Tibetan autonomous prefecture of Gansu province. Jone is about 90
miles south of Gansu's capital of Lanzhou.
   The news agency said the avalanche swept away many houses and
destroyed local electrical facilties.
   Xinhua said rescue efforts were still under way, but did not say
if any survivors were expected to be found or whether the toll was
expected to rise.
   It quoted an unidentified local official as saying about 10,000
people were affected, apparently by the power cutoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2006EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0771 07-08 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0771,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says GOP Turning Campaign Attacks Into ``Two-Way Street''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush rally remarks as new grafs 4-8, bgng ``In
an,'' picking up 4th graf pvs, ``However, Bush's''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Friday that
allegations he has used public money for campaigning are just the
latest attack from the Democrats in a battle the Republicans are
only now turning into ``a two-way street.''
   Bush, at a news conference before a GOP fund-raising rally, said
in answer to a separate Democratic charge _ that he has gone back
on his no-tax-increase pledge _ that his definition of a tax
increase does not include the new levies on the elderly for
catastrophic illness coverage.
   He also said he might support paying reparations to the families
of the Iranian citizens killed when a U.S. Navy ship downed an
Iranian jetliner this week _ but not to the Iran government.
   In an evening address at the Republican rally, Bush stressed
national defense policy and contended Democrat Michael Dukakis, who
is expected to be his presidential rival in November, would leave
the United States generally depending on the United Nations to keep
world peace.
   ``Multilateralism seems to be my opponent's answer to Soviet
aggression,'' he told the gathering of GOP activists, including
most of his former rivals for the Republican presidential
nomination.
   ``Now he's proposing to cut the MX, Midgetman and SDI,'' the
Strategic Defense Initiative also known as Star Wars, he said,
adding: ``pre-emptive concessions are no way to bargain with the
Soviets.''
   Bush also attacked Dukakis' attempt, as governor of
Massachusetts, to block a president from deploying a state's
National Guard units without the governor's permission.
   ``You can't run a foreign policy if 50 state governors each have
the right to veto a presidential decision,'' Bush said. ``Thank
heavens (that) the courts rejected the case and didn't hamstring
the president's ability to defend our nation,'' he added.
   However, Bush's news conference was dominated by questions about
whether his campaign was properly repaying the government for the
costs of campaign trips on Air Force planes. Democratic National
Chairman Paul Kirk on Friday said he was raising the question with
the White House counsel in regard to two recent outings.
   ``We are not abusing the public trust,'' Bush said, calling it
``an outrageous charge.''
   The vice president, speaking to reporters earlier on the trip
from Washington, said, ``We've bent over backwards to be within the
letter, certainly the spirit of the law.''
   At the news conference, he said, ``If you abide by the law,
whatever you do is fair.''
   Bush put forward his campaign attorney, Ede Holiday, to answer
questions from reporters. She was unable to provide details about
how much of the trips were paid by the campaign and how much by the
government, but said it was determined by long-standing formulas.
   Bush said the intensity of Democratic attacks was no greater
than it had been for several months but that his campaign was
firing back.
   ``It's only now we're beginning to make it a two-way street,''
said Bush, who has for some time been deploying GOP officials to
attack Dukakis, the likely Democratic nominee, at events around the
country.
   The trip to Atlanta made it the second straight day the vice
president was invading what might be considered enemy turf. He
spoke to a Greek audience in Dukakis' Boston hometown on Thursday
night, and Atlanta will be the site of the Democratic National
Convention the week after next.
   Bush said the timing of the Atlanta appearance was not aimed at
the Democrats.
   ``We are not going to rain on their parade. That is not to say
we're not praying for rain,'' he said.
   Asked about Dukakis' statement that Bush's support of the new
catastrophic illness insurance program amounted to support of a tax
boost, the vice president said the increased levies on the elderly
to finance the program amounted to something different _ ``a
premium.'' He said that fit in with his earlier exclusion of ``user
fees'' from his no-tax pledge.
   ``I think the voters know what I'm talking about,'' he said.
   Bush said President Reagan's support of several tax bills during
his presidency didn't mean he himself would eventually do the same.
``What's that have to do with what I'll do as president?'' he asked.
   The vice president also expanded his criticism of Dukakis'
statements favoring a conventional weapons modernization program,
saying the Democrat was anti-nuclear-weapons to the degree that
``he moves us to a very different form of deterrence'' that would
be more costly.
   Bush said he felt ``terribly sad for the families of those
people'' killed in the downing of the Iranian Airbus and added that
the National Security Council was considering the matter of
reparations.
   ``I would never, ever under any circumstances offer reparations
to the Iranian government,'' he said.
   Dukakis said Friday in Texarkana, Texas, ``I'm as anxious as
members of Congress and the American people to get the results of
the investigation ... but I would think some form of humanitarian
assistance would probably be appropriate.''
</TEXT>
