<HEAD>Indelicato Sentenced in Federal Education Fraud Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4 grafs for 3rd graf, `He had ...' to UPDATE with
details of when Indelicato would be eligible for parole, judge's
comments. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Under a ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former top education adviser to Gov. Michael
S. Dukakis was sentenced Friday to 2{ years in prison and ordered
to pay up to $80,000 to the state in restitution for skimming money
from a program he ran.
   Gerard T. Indelicato, 42, was ordered to surrender to federal
officials Aug. 5. Where he will serve his prison term has yet to be
determined.
   He had pleaded guilty in federal court in April to five charges
of conspiracy, mail fraud and tax evasion in a scheme with three
others to bilk an adult education program of some $80,000.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ralph Gants said Indelicato would be
eligible to seek parole in 10 months. Based on precedent,
Indelicato would likely serve 12 to 18 months in prison, Gants said.
   The sentence handed down by U.S. District Court Judge Douglas
Woodlock was half the five-year term Gants recommended. But the
judge said it was more severe than most similar cases.
   Woodlock said it was important ``that white-collar pickpockets
are subject to the same punishment as those who use cruder
implements.''
   Under a plea bargain, Indelicato testified in the trial of
Michael Freedman, whom federal prosecutors identified as one of the
``minor players'' in the scheme. Indelicato was considered the
mastermind behind the plan that involved paying inflated rent and
receiving some of the money back, taking the salaries of fictitious
employees and skimming funds intended to pay for classroom
renovations.
   Indelicato has said he wondered whether the case would have
drawn the same level of publicity if he had no links to Dukakis,
the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee.
   All of the alleged activities occurred between 1979 and early
1983 and ended a few weeks prior to the time Dukakis named
Indelicato his chief education adviser.
   Dukakis has condemned Indelicato's activities and has said his
administration is cooperating fully with all pending
investigations. Indelicato is the highest ranking member of
Dukakis' administration to face criminal indictment.
</TEXT>
