<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Fighting     07-08 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Fighting,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Charge More Cease-Fire Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAGALPA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said
Thursday that the rebels were deploying land-to-air rockets that
could endanger civilian planes. He said the U.S. downing of an
Iranian A300 Airbus was an example of what could happen in
Nicaragua.
   The president also accused the U.S.-backed rebels, known as
Contras, of breaking the nearly 4-month-old cease-fire.
   He blamed the Reagan administration for the developments.
   Referring to the airliner disaster, Ortega said, ``The Contras
could do the same thing here. We now are experiencing the effects
of the dirty, illegal war and of the terrorist activity that has
been approved.''
   The Iranian jetliner was shot down by missile fire from the USS
Vincennes last Sunday, with the loss of 290 lives, in the mistaken
belief that the plane was an attacking F-14 fighter jet.
   Earlier Thursday, pro-Sandinista newspapers said rebels firing
mortars and rifles killed two children along the Caribbean coast.
   The purported attack on a Miskito Indian village Saturday was
among a series of increased raids reported in recent days as
violating the truce.
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada said Lackia Saballos, 5, and
Efram Martinez, died in a pre-dawn attack from rebel mortars and
rifles fired from the Honduran side of the Coco River.
   Ortega said in a nationally broadcast meeting with coffee
workers in the northern city of Matagalpa: ``The cease-fire has
been broken. They (the rebels) are deploying at this moment
land-to-air rockets, putting civilian aviation in danger.''
   Ortega did not say that he would end the truce his government
has extended unilaterally until the end of July. The Contras
agreed, but did not specify how long it would last.
   ``They are beating the war drums, and because of that we should
not let down our guard but rather repulse those criminals,'' Ortega
said.
   The Contras have been fighting the leftist Sandinista government
since 1981.
   The Sandinistas had played down reported violations of the
truce, which began March 21, two days before the government and
Contras signed an agreement to seek a negotiated settlement to the
war. On Monday, however, the Sandinistas issued their first monthly
casualty bulletin since March.
   The Defense Ministry reported 87 rebels killed and 31 wounded in
combat in June. It said 15 soldiers were killed and 62 injured. The
figures indicate that substantially more fighting was under way in
the isolated mountainous regions than was previously revealed.
   The government also said 184 civilians were kidnapped by the
rebels last month. On Wednesday the Defense Ministry said nine
civilians were kidnapped in northeastern Rio Blanco.
   Last Monday, a land mine blew up a military truck in central
Chontales province and killed seven non-combatants, according to
the government.
   The Contras denied responsibility for that attack.
   Reports of renegade Contras opposed to a negotiated settlement
surfaced almost immediately after the peace agreement was signed by
rebel leaders, who live in Miami and Costa Rica. Contra ranks are
deeply divided.
   Both sides agreed to suspend offensive military operations. The
Sandinistas twice extended a cease-fire that ended May 30. The
current truce, according to the government, runs out July 31. The
Contras prolonged the cease-fire without giving a date.
   A series of high-level talks since the March meeting have failed
to define ways to end the war that has killed more than 26,000
Nicaraguans and shattered the economy.
   The last round broke off June 9 when the Contras responded to a
government proposal with a new plan that went beyond points agreed
upon earlier. It would have disbanded the the supreme court,
established a constituent assembly and immediately freed all
political prisoners.
   The Sandinistas bowed to a Contra demand to move toward
democratic reforms but the rebels said it didn't go far enough.
   The government called for new talks to be held July 27. But the
Contras rejected the proposal.
   The Sandinistas came to power in July 1979, concluding a
revolutionary war that ended 42 years of rule by the rightist,
pro-American Somoza dynasty.
</TEXT>
