<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Rebels     07-08 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Rebels,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Sentenced In Airport Takeover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Newbery is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal court sentenced five
civilians to prison terms ranging from nine to 12 years on Friday
for their involvement in the January takeover of Buenos Aires'
metropolitan airport.
   An armed band seized Jorge Newbery Airport for four hours early
Jan. 18 in sympathy with a three-day rebellion led by former Lt.
Col. Aldo Rico at the Monte Caseros army camp in northeastern
Argentina.
   The civilians convicted of rebellion and interrupting air
traffic were: Oscar Hugo Calzada, sentenced to 12 years; Enrique
Calzada and Alberto Telias, 11 years each; Guillermo Ferrari, 10
years, and Rafael Cobo, nine years.
   Juan Jose Ariza and Daniel Cedres were absolved of all charges.
   Five other army camps also rebelled briefly before the uprisings
ended the same day with the rebel chief and 328 soldiers
surrendering. Rico is in a military prison awaiting trial.
   Rico was demanding an end to prosecution of officers accused of
human rights atrocities during the 1976-83 ``dirty war,'' when the
military ruled Argentina.
   The rebellion was the second led by Rico since April 1987, when
three revolts in camps at Campo de Mayo in suburban Buenos Aires,
Cordoba and Tucuman convulsed the government of President Raul
Alfonsin, in power since 1983.
</TEXT>
