<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0838 07-08 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0838,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Announces Presidential Vote Within 90 Days</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: NEW throughout with more details of speech and background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TALCAHUANO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet on Friday
announced that balloting to choose a president for the 1989-97 term
will take place within the next 90 days.
   ``There are less than 90 days left for the plebiscite,''
Pinochet told a rally of his supporters in this port city 330 miles
south of Santiago, the capital.
   The 72-year-old president and army commander, who has ruled this
South American nation since a 1973 coup, is considered the most
likely candidate for the balloting, a yes-or-no vote on a single
candidate.
   Chile's Constitution allows Pinochet to seek re-election and in
his speech, he said he already has a government platform for the
next presidential term, but declined to disclose it.
   Pinochet did not mention a specific date for the vote, but his
remark before a cheering audience at a sports arena seemed a clear
confirmation that the military government is planning the
plebiscite for September or October this year.
   According to a 1980 military-drafted Constitution, Chile's next
president will be elected in a plebiscite in which Chileans will be
able to vote only yes or no on one candidate nominated by the heads
of the three armed services and the national police.
   Pinochet, as commander-in-chief of the army, will be one of the
four military leaders making the nomination.
   If the single candidate is approved by voters, he will serve an
eight-year term starting March 11, 1989.
   If the candidate is rejected, an open presidential election
should be called within one year, with Pinochet remaining in power
until then.
   In his speech today, Pinochet blasted his opponents and said,
``we will wipe them out'' in the plebiscite.
   The opposition, which unsuccessfully tried to prevent the
plebiscite and promote a competitive election instead, has now
united to urge citizens to vote no in the referendum.
   Sixteen political parties, from left to right, have joined in a
``National Command for the Vote No'' campaign. The outlawed
Communist Party said it would participate in the plebiscite
supporting the opposition stance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
