<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Congress     07-08 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Congress,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Congressmen Probe Human Rights In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Tom DeLay said Friday upon
his arrival here with three other members of Congress that
political prisoners in Nicaragua are being overlooked in the search
for peace in Central America.
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government acknowledges the
existence of more than 3,000 political prisoners.
   The four members of Congress said they wanted to take a
first-hand look at the human rights situation in Nicaragua.
   ``We were very concerned that during this whole peace process
that we've forgotten the most important people here _ that's the
political prisoners,'' DeLay, a Texas Republican, told a news
conference at Managua airport.
   ``We're very concerned about the conditions and reasons they are
being held.''
   Release of the prisoners is called for by a Central American
peace plan signed by the region's five presidents on Aug. 7, 1987
and a cease-fire agreement reached in last March by the Sandinistas
and Nicaragua's U.S.-backed rebels.
   The Sandinistas pardoned and freed more than 900 political
prisoners last November as a goodwill gesture to get truce
negotiations going. More than 3,000 remain jailed.
   The truce still holds, despite occasional clashes.
   ``We are hoping with our visits to, once again, make sure our
concerns on political prisoners are heard,'' Rep. Beverly B. Bryon,
D-Md., said.
   Also visiting Nicaragua were Reps. Robin M. Tallon, D-S.C., and
Barbara Vucanovich, R-Nev. Both are sponsors of a resolution
calling on the Sandinistas to comply with the Central American
peace plan.
   The congressional team said their trip was not linked to
speculation in Washington about renewing U.S. military aid to the
rebels, known as Contras. The United States has been supplying such
aid off and on since the rebels began fighting to overthrow the
Sandinistas in 1981.
   The peace plan, which aims to negotiate an end to the civil war
in Nicaragua and leftist insurgencies in Guatemala and El Salvador,
also calls for political amnesties; an end to outside interference
and provision of military aid to insurgents, and reforms to bring
greater democracy to the region.
   ``If the government wants to tell their story, this is their
chance,'' DeLay said.
   The four representatives are scheduled to meet over the weekend
with opposition and government leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
