<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MoffordProbe     07-08 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mofford Probe,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Will Not Charge Mofford</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor will bring no charges against
Gov. Rose Mofford even though he said she violated financial
disclosure laws and the state procurement code.
   ``I think Governor Mofford would agree that she did something
wrong,'' Maricopa County Attorney Tom Collins said.
   However, he added, whatever she did wrong was not serious enough
to warrant prosecution.
   Arizona law says an officeholder or candidate who ``knowingly
files an incomplete financial disclosure statement is guilty'' of a
misdemeanor, but Collins said Mrs. Mofford's violations were ``just
not the kind of level where you impose criminal sanctions ... It's
just not worth the candle to the taxpayers.''
   Mrs. Mofford said: ``Obviously I am relieved that this
investigation has concluded and I can continue to lead Arizona
without any doubts about my integrity. It feels good to be
exonerated from these charges because every decision I have ever
made in public service has been for the benefit of the state of
Arizona.''
   Later, during an appearance with presumptive Democratic
presidential nominee Michael S. Dukakis, she complimented Collins
and his staff and said several times, ``I'm very pleased.''
   Her attorney, Mike Hawkins, said Mrs. Mofford planned to follow
up by calling for establishment of an ethics commission, but her
press secretary, Vada Manager, said such talk was premature.
   Collins' office was asked by Attorney General Bob Corbin to look
at omissions from financial disclosure statements Mrs. Mofford
filed over the last 10 years and at thousands of dollars in state
money that went for gifts and office decorations while she was
secretary of state.
   No record exists of where most of the gifts went, and Mrs.
Mofford has no recollection.
   But they were ``all arguably given in the state interest'' and
``they lack any clear element of personal gain in a thoroughly
private capacity,'' Collins told a news conference.
   Some of the items were purchased in technical violation of the
state procurement code, but Mrs. Mofford's office followed
procedures that were parallel to what the state procurement office
would have done in any case, Collins said.
   Omissions from her financial disclosure statements were not
``significant in that they did not involve large amounts of money
or personal gain for Governor Mofford,'' Collins said.
   The investigation began after The Associated Press reported in
April that Mrs. Mofford had failed to list numerous land, loan and
partnership dealings in financial disclosure forms covering the
past 10 years.
   It was broadened in May after the AP reviewed five years of
bills paid by the secretary of state's office and found more than
$50,000 spent on items that included a joke-writing service, dolls
and expensive watches. The review also found Mrs. Mofford had
bought about $10,000 worth of U.S. and Arizona flags from
unauthorized vendors at higher prices than the flags could have
cost if purchased from state-approved vendors.
   As secretary of state, Mrs. Mofford was in charge of ensuring
that financial forms were easy to fill out. She initially referred
to the AP story as nitpicking but later filed amended reports,
saying that she had made ``an honest mistake.''
   Mrs. Mofford, elected as secretary of state, became acting
governor in February after the House impeached Gov. Evan Mecham on
charges that he falsified his financial disclosure statements,
misused money from a state gift fund and obstructed an
investigation by Attorney General Bob Corbin.
   She became governor April 4 when the Senate convicted Mecham of
misusing state money and obstructing justice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
