<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Funeral     07-08 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Funeral,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delvalle Stays in Hiding, Misses Mother's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RODRIGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle failed
to attend his mother's funeral service here Friday, remaining
instead in hiding as he has since his February ouster by Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Family members told reporters Delvalle did not trust a
government offer not to interfere in the service and to help
facilitate the attendance of relatives.
   The offer was published in Thursday's editions of the
pro-government Estrella de Panama newspaper.
   A warrant for Delvalle's arrest has been outstanding since
Noriega, the country's de facto ruler and commander of the Defense
Forces, orchestrated his removal from office.
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle as Panama's
legitimate chief of state. Noriega, under U.S. indictments on drug
trafficking charges, replaced Delvalle with Manuel Palma Solis.
   Delvalle's 71-year-old mother, Abigail Henriquez de Delvalle,
died of a heart attack Wednesday at Mercy Hospital in Miami. Her
body was flown to Panama Thursday.
   U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis attended Friday's funeral service
at a local synagogue. He declined to comment to reporters
afterwards.
   Government officials attended the service, as did former Vice
President Roderick Esquivel, making his first public appearance
since he was ousted along with Delvalle in February.
   Esquivel said the political crisis had created a ``tragic''
situation in Panama.
   ``I think that the country really has descended to levels where
we are going to have to reconstruct it completely and make a new
republic,'' he said.
   The Reagan administration has applied a series of economic
sanctions against Panama in an effort to force Noriega to resign.
   The sanctions have produced a liquidity crisis in Panama, which
uses the U.S. dollar as its currency.
   Esquivel said the crisis was not limited ``to ousting Gen.
Noriega, it's a matter of constructing a country in whose
government all Panamanians can believe.''
</TEXT>
