<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Koop     07-08 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Koop,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former CBS Vice President Developed ``Face The Nation'' Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theodore Frederick Koop, a former vice
president of the Columbia Broadcasting System, died Thursday of
complications following surgery. He was 81.
   The Monticello, Iowa native began his nearly half-century-long
journalism career at age 10 as a $5 a week reporter for the
Monticello Express.
   A 1928 Phi Beta Kappa graduate from the University of Iowa, Koop
served as newsman-editor for The Associated Press and director of
the National Geographic Magazine news service before joining CBS in
1948 as director of news and public affairs in Washington.
   During his 23 years with CBS, Koop conceived the ``Face the
Nation'' program and participated in the expansion of the network's
news programming and move into television. He was named vice
president in 1961 and retired in 1971.
   A former national president of the Radio-Television News
Directors Association and Sigma Delta Chi, the Society of
Professional Journalists, Koop also authored a book, ``Weapon of
Silence,'' detailing his work with the Office of Censorship during
World War II.
   He is survived by a sister, Mrs. Laura Merikle of Green Valley,
Ariz., three nieces and two nephews.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
