<DOCNO> AP880708-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-VeteranReturns     07-08 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veteran Returns,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disabled Pilot's Solo Flight To Germany Ends In Crash Landing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disabled pilot Clark Harrison was making a solo
trans-Atlantic flight to visit the World War II battlefield in West
Germany where he was paralyzed, but he was ``pretty sure I wasn't
going to be in this life'' after his plane ran out of fuel over
Greenland.
   ``All I saw was mountains and rocks. I looked down and I saw a
little lake and it had a little green next to it and I said, `That
looks better than anything else','' Harrison said in a telephone
interview from the U.S. Air Force Base at Sondrestrom, Greenland.
   Harrison said he cut his face on the instrument panel, adding
``I'm a little bit sore,'' but otherwise all right.
   ``I was pretty sure I wasn't going to be in this life when I got
on the ground,'' said Harrison, a 63-year-old veteran. He was
piloting a single-engine, hand-controlled plane.
   Martha Foster, a spokeswoman for Shepherd Spinal Center in
Atlanta, said the Air Force would fly Harrison to the U.S. mainland
and he would return to Atlanta late Saturday.
   Harrison's trip was planned as a fund-raiser for Shepherd's
Center for Independent Living. Supporters pledged to donate up to
$1 for each mile covered by Harrison, a founding director of the
13-year-old center for patients with spinal cord injuries.
   Harrison left the Atlanta suburb of Decatur July 1 on the
4,669-mile flight. After reaching West Germany, Harrison had
planned to go to Stolberg, site of the battlefield where he was
wounded 43 years ago. City officials had planned a reception in his
honor.
   ``It was a one of those rescues that turned out the way it was
supposed to,'' said Col. Guy Sumter, commander of the Greenland
base. ``We knew he was late. We knew when he crashed, we knew where
he crashed and we found him right away.
   ``He did a real good job of getting it down. He put it down on
just about the only flat spot there was down there.''
   Harrison had been delayed by weather in Canada, leaving there
Thursday morning, three days after he had planned to reach
Greenland. He was scheduled to arrive in Germany July 11.
   He ran into bad weather off the coast of Canada and his plane
was blown off course.
   Harrison put in an emergency call for assistance as he
approached the coast of Greenland and was shocked when the call was
answered by Pat Epps, an old friend who owns Epps Air Service in
Georgia.
   ``I felt God was answering,'' Harrison said.
   Epps, who had been in Greenland on business, notified the base
that Harrison was lost and almost out of fuel. On Epps' advice,
Harrison climbed to 7,000 feet so the base could find him on radar.
   Although the plane was not very badly damaged, Sumter said it
may be impossible to remove the aircraft, which is nose-down in a
ditch next to a little pond.
   ``We've decided to leave it up there,'' Harrison said. ``It's
going to be a historical marker. I'm the first paraplegic to crash
in Greenland. A lot of people cross the ocean, but few crash into
Greenland and live to tell.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
