<1ST_LINE>a a PM-AnotherLook:Oil-Hydrogeologists Adv11   07-08 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Another Look: Oil-Hydrogeologists, Adv 11,0651</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday PMs, July 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jobless Petroleum Workers Find Relief In Hydrogeology Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Saturday in 8th graf is July 9</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When oil was king in Oklahoma, all was well
for geologists. They had steady jobs and big salaries. But the bust
sent many to the unemployment lines.
   Now, after eight months of night school, some hard-luck oil and
gas workers are hoping they don't have to look so deep for success.
They have opted for careers in hydrogeology, the study of
groundwater.
   And the drought in many parts of the country might even help
them find work.
   ``It's been an endurance test,'' said Kurt Lampi, one of the
students in the program that met three hours a night, three days a
week. ``But it has helped me in getting employment.''
   Lampi was a geophysicist for Diamond Shamrock in the Gulf of
Mexico when he was laid off in November 1985.
   He learned of the hydrogeology training program at Metro Tech in
Oklahoma City and was part of Saturday's graduating class, along
with 62 others, mostly unemployed or underemployed oil and gas
workers.
   Lampi said he has received two job offers _ one from an Oklahoma
City company and the other from a company in South Carolina.
   ``We went into this because there is a need, and the
university's role is to fill a need,'' said Wayne Pettyjohn, head
of the Department of Geology at Oklahoma State University. ``I was
aware of the market out there. Mainly people involved in
groundwater are poorly trained.''
   Pettyjohn said the idea of a crash course in hydrogeology
surfaced when he received an increasing number of telephone calls
from laid-off oil and gas workers looking for a way out of a
depressed lifestyle.
   At the time, hydrogeology courses were offered at night at
Oklahoma State, but that soon expanded to one-week short courses in
the summer.
   The big boost came, Pettyjohn said, when oilman Jack Taylor
lobbied to get $600,000 in funds from the Department of Labor's
Dislocated Workers Program for the state Deparment of Vocational
Technical Education.
   An agreement was reached for Oklahoma State in Stillwater to
supply faculty who would teach at Metro Tech in Oklahoma City.
   Although it's still too early to determine if the program will
pay off in terms of jobs for the students, Pettyjohn said, ``I've
got several letters on my desk and also phone calls from people
(companies) interested in seeing what we have to offer.''
   The drought in parts of the Midwest and South could help, he
said. ``If it continues, I would suspect people will be looking
more to groundwater as a source of supply. Therefore, (the drought)
would have a positive effect on job prospects.''
   Some students have said hydrogeology companies don't want to
take a chance on former geologists, fearing they will jump ship if
the oil industry should rebound.
   Pettyjohn doubts it. ``These people put in eight months of
intensive work. Several of them have lost their jobs. They've all
had a bad experience. They don't want to go through that again.''
   Lampi is one who insists that hydrogeology is his new career,
noting that it will pay him 75 percent of his petroleum industry
salary.
   Not everyone does so well. Pettyjohn said he knew of a former
student whose oil and gas management position had paid him
$125,000. ``If he (a hydrogeology student) starts out at $25,000,
he'll be lucky.''
   Harvey Vick decided to take the hydrogeology course even though
he still works in the oil industry.
   ``This is something to fall back on,'' he said, ``in case
something does happen to my job.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, July 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
