<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-08 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0577</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's two largest financial markets have
taken a joint step toward averting another stock crash, proposing
reforms that include special attention to small investors and
coordinated trading halts when the Dow Jones industrial average
falls 250 points.
   Thursday's announcement by the boards of the New York Stock
Exchange and Chicago Mercantile Exchange addressed many key issues
raised by government studies on the causes of the October crash,
particularly the need for cooperation between the nation's
financial markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
voted to limit American companies' ability to weaken the voting
power of their stockholders as a way of fighting hostile takeovers.
   The new one-share, one-vote rule, approved 4-1 on Thursday,
spells out how shares with reduced voting power can be issued.
   One popular takeover defense, in which companies entice
stockholders into giving up their voting rights by offering a
special one-time dividend, would be prohibited.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
decided against recommending legislation that would guarantee
investors the right to sue their stock broker in court.
   The commission had considered asking Congress to outlaw clauses
in brokerage account agreements requiring customers to settle
disputes through industry-sponsored arbitration panels, rather than
through the courts.
   The commission said Thursday it decided instead to ask stock
exchanges to study the matter and report back by Oct. 15.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators say it will cost $15.2
billion to bail out Texas' ailing savings and loan institutions,
more than double their previous estimate.
   The chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, M. Danny Wall
also told lawmakers Thursday that his agency would be able to raise
$42.5 billion over the next decade to cover insolvencies across the
country.
   The government had estimated the cost of bailouts nationally
would be in the $25 billion to $30 billion range and that the bank
board would have $30.2 billion at its disposal to merge, sell or
liquidate troubled thrifts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive oil rig fire off the coast of Scotland
will worsen a shortage of North Sea oil, but the disaster is not
likely to have a big impact on the industry, experts say.
   The fatal accident, which caused a jump in world oil prices
Thursday, prompted the British government to postpone the process
for granting new off-shore licenses, which would open up more areas
for exploration.
   The price of Brent Blend, the most widely traded international
crude oil, jumped to $15.05 a barrel for September delivery, up 32
cents from late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices soared in erratic trading but settled
off their peaks as traders assessed the impact of a rig explosion
in the North Sea and the chances for an emergency OPEC meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, the contract for
August delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 47
cents higher at $15.83 a barrel. The contract traded as high as
$16.35 per barrel during the session.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
closed up 2.56 cents a gallon at 53.12 cents after being up nearly
4 cents earlier in the day. Home heating oil advanced 1.68 cents a
gallon to 44.29 cents.
</TEXT>
