<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SamuraiOpinions Bjt   07-08 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Samurai Opinions, Bjt,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Samurai Conflict Raises Question: What Is Safe?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Controversy over the safety of the Suzuki
Samurai has accentuated a deep rift among American opinion leaders
and the general public over a basic question: What is safe?
   Consumer Reports says the jeep-like Samurai is too tall, narrow,
light and short and thus tips over too easily when the driver
swerves back and forth at high speed.
   Supporters say that although the Samurai's high center of
gravity makes it tippier than some other vehicles, it is safe in
the hands of a competent driver.
   ``There's no easy definition of what safe or unsafe is. It's
really a continuum,'' Jeffrey Miller, deputy administrator of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, said in a recent
interview.
   The conflict between consumerists and auto enthusiasts runs
through the public at large, said John Staudenmaier, a professor of
history and technology at the University of Detroit.
   ``One approach says the design ought to make it nearly
impossible to have an accident,'' Staudenmaier said. ``But auto
buffs would tend to say, `We're not idiots.'''
   Americans make decisions about safety every time they choose
between a car and a motorcycle, or between a big, heavy car and a
small, light one.
   Unfortunately for Suzuki, consumers' judgments about the Samurai
have been powerfully influenced by television news clips supplied
by Consumers Union that show the Samurai tipping over onto its
outriggers.
   For some people, the visual impact tends to overwhelm American
Suzuki Motor Corp.'s recitation of favorable accident statistics
and its counter-argument that nearly any vehicle can be made to tip
over by extreme driving maneuvers.
   The four-wheel-drive Samurai became one of the hottest imports
in 1986 and 1987 because of its emotional appeal as a fun, jazzy
and liberated little box on wheels.
   The charm faded in June as sales of the Samurai plunged 70.6
percent from their levels of a year earlier. It was mainly a
reaction to the June 2 report by Consumers Union, the Mount Vernon,
N.Y.-based publisher of Consumer Reports.
   Suzuki dealers are hoping sales will recover gradually in coming
months, but that will depend partly on how often the infamous
videotape reappears on the evening news.
   Editors of auto magazines tend to say that the primary
responsibility for car safety should fall on the driver rather than
the automaker.
   ``Any car has design intent. If the design intent is exceeded,
the car is going to do something weird and spooky,'' said Dennis
Simanaitis, executive editor of Road & Track.
   The Samurai had to be built high off the ground because it is
used off-road, Simanaitis said. A vehicle that can drive over
boulders and logs is by nature tippier than a low-slung sports car.
   ``If Suzuki gave no warnings it would be different, but they
have disclaimers galore,'' Simanaitis said.
   Suzuki's television ads quote a 1986 article by Car and Driver
that said ``if you want a rugged four-wheel-drive for the minimum
amount of money, the Samurai is the only game in town.''
   William Jeanes, the magazine's editor, said he stands behind
that statement.
   ``I think every car, taken to extremes, can do something
dangerous,'' Jeanes said. ``How high is too high for a center of
gravity? I don't know the answer to that.''
   Road & Track's own road test did not include the swerving
maneuver in which Consumers Union got the Samurai to tip over.
Simanaitis said he found no fault with the Consumers Union test but
added, ``If I look around hard enough, I can find a test that will
embarrass almost any vehicle except an out-and-out race car.''
   Consumers Union is calling on the government to develop
industrywide standards for for a national standard on resistance to
rollovers, but the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
has resisted that approach in the past.
   A strict formula for height, weight and other characteristics
could have the effect of banning certain classes of vehicles, and
courts have ruled that the federal agency should ``go to great
lengths to avoid that,'' Miller said.
   Miller said the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
is seeking ways aside from design rules that would lessen rollover
problems, such as improving brakes.
   ``We recognize that there are a wide variety of vehicles, and
you don't want to deprive people of vehicles that they need or want
to use, whether it's for work or for pleasure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880708-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 0127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   07-08 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warmer Weather Boosts Retailers' Flagging Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest general retailers report that their sales
improved in June following dismal performances in April and May,
but industry analysts say consumers still are spending cautiously
as they have all year.
   ``It's a reprieve,'' Jeffrey Edelman, an analyst with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., said Thursday after reviewing the June
numbers. ``It does not say the consumer is going on a wild spending
spree.''
   ``It's not a great environment, but things are better than they
were,'' said Linda Kristiansen, an analyst with the investment firm
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Industry-wide, sales were up between 3.5 percent and 4 percent
last month and have risen about 2.5 percent so far this year, Ms.
Kristiansen said.
   In reaching those estimates, she considered what retailers call
same-store sales, those from stores open at least a year. Analysts
believe same-store sales give a more accurate picture of a
retailer's performance than totals that include figures from new
stores.
   Analysts said the belated arrival of hot weather lured consumers
into stores to buy summer clothing and seasonal items such as
garden equipment and outdoor barbecues.
   Walter Loeb, who tracks retailers for Morgan Stanley & Co., said
sales were aided by the markdowns retailers continued to take to
clear their inventories. Analysts were watching closely for any
effect on sales from the Midwestern drought. Monroe H. Greenstein,
an analyst with Bear, Stearns & Co., said sales volume was
unaffected last month, but could be in July.
   Retailers generally have been disappointed by 1988 sales, which
have not kept pace with inflation. Consumer prices rose at an
annual rate of 4.4 percent through May, according to Labor
Department figures.
   Stores have been slumping for more than a year because of
economic uncertainty and disappointment with current fashions.
Sales worsened in April and May, with cold and wet weather blamed
for the deterioration.
   Edelman said the sales pickup so far was principally
weather-related.
   Morgan Stanley's Loeb was more optimistic. Although sales were
up only moderately last month, ``it certainly points to a better
fall season,'' he said.
   Storeowners and investors watch sales figures for an indication
of retailers' earnings, while economists monitor the results as a
barometer of economic health. Consumer spending accounts for
two-thirds of the gross national product.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest retailer, said its
overall sales were up 9.8 percent in June from year-earlier levels,
and rose 5 percent for the first 22 weeks of the fiscal year.
Sears' same-store sales were up 5.1 percent last month and 2
percent for the year so far.
   K mart Corp. said its overall June sales rose 7 percent, while
year-to-date sales were up 5.3 percent. Same-store sales rose 2.9
percent last month and 2 percent so far this year.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its overall sales rose 32 percent in
both June and the year to date. Same-store sales were up 13 percent
in June and 12 percent for the five months.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. reported its overall sales rose 3.4 percent
last month and 2.6 percent for the 22 weeks. Same-store sales rose
3 percent in June and 1.6 percent for the year so far.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said its overall June sales rose 19.6
percent and its year-to-date sales were up 18.4 percent. Same-store
sales increased 3.3 percent in June and 1.9 percent for the year to
date.
   May Department Stores Co. said its overall sales rose 22.3
percent last month and 10.1 percent for the year so far. Its
same-store sales were up 4.8 percent for June and 0.8 percent for
the 22-week period.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. reported sales increases of 11.7 in June and
12.1 percent for the year to date.
   Montgomery Ward & Co. said its June sales were up 3.6 percent,
and year-to-date sales rose 3.1 percent.
   The results reported Thursday are from general and apparel
retailers. Unlike the monthly retail sales report issued by the
Commerce Department, they do not include sales of car dealers,
supermarkets or restaurants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
