<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fizzled at the close of the trading week
in Tokyo today after gaining against the Japanese yen, while stocks
advanced in what traders described as moderate activity.
   After opening at 131.95 yen, the dollar closed trading only
slightly higher at 131.97 yen, down 0.33 yen from Thursday's close
of 132.40.
   Traders said the dollar recovered in midday dealings after
opening lower, but then lost steam in afternoon trading.
   ``The market is readjusting itself and waiting for
market-affecting material like seasonal U.S. trade figures due out
next Friday,'' said a dealer with a major city bank in Tokyo.
   The dealer, speaking anonymously, said there were no major
factors moving the yen-dollar market in Tokyo at present and ruled
out any effect of the U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner in the
Persian Gulf last Sunday.
   On Monday, the dollar closed at 134.80 yen, its highest closing
since Nov. 24.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which declined 38.47 points Thursday, recouped its losses by
advancing 188.95 points or 0.68 percent to close the week's trading
at 27,917.08.
   Volume in the first section totaled 1.4 billion shares, compared
to Thursday's turnover of 2 billion.
   Traders said while security houses and automakers posted gains,
the market appeared to be thrashing around in search of a new
direction.
   ``It's more of the same stuff,'' said one trader. ``Interest is
just shifting around aimlessly.''
   Some traders said a lower dollar helped relieve concerns over
possible higher interest rates and inflation that have hurt the
market recently.
   Futures trading in 20-year bonds began for the first time on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange today, with overall performance of the
benchmark September 2008 issues described as sluggish.
   The stock market, which opens for a half-day session on the
frist and fourth Saturday of each month, will be closed this
Saturday. There are no foreign exchange dealings in Tokyo over the
weekend.
</TEXT>
