<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0004 07-08 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0004,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>June Unemployment Rate Falls; Retailers Report Improved Sales in
June</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with June unemployment figures.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Analysts blamed ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's June unemployment rate fell to 5.3 percent _ its
best level in nearly 14 years _ as youths flooded the job market
and found a wealth of opportunity, the government reported today.
   The 0.3-percentage-point improvement from the previous month
marked the first time the rate has dipped so strongly since 1986
and sent it to its lowest since joblessness stood at 5.1 percent in
May 1974.
   The Labor Department said seasonally adjusted employment in June
jumped by 820,000 _ 75 percent of it among youths 16-24 years old _
to more than offset May's decline of 536,000.
   Unemployment among teenagers fell 2.0 percentage points to 13.6
percent, its lowest since 1970.
   Analysts had anticipated a surge in youth employment in the
tourism industry as unprecedented numbers of foreigners, buoyed by
the devalued dollar, are vacationing in the United States this
summer.
   On Thursday in the financial markets, stock prices lost ground
for the second straight session but finished well above their
midday lows. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down more
than 20 points at one stage, closed with a 7.47 loss at 2,122.69.
   Analysts blamed the market's downturn partly on the recent rise
of interest rates in the credit markets. Yields on long-term
Treasury bonds have climbed lately back above 9 percent, driven
largely by recurring worries about inflation.
   Those worries were refueled somewhat Thursday, when oil prices
surged in erratic trading. They later settled below their peaks as
traders assessed the impact of a rig explosion in the North Sea and
the chances for an emergency OPEC meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for August
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark crude oil,
settled 47 cents higher at $15.83 a barrel. The contract traded as
high as $16.35 per barrel during the volatile session.
   However, prices of key farm commodities plummeted as some
private forecasters predicted rain this weekend in the
drought-parched Farm Belt.
   Despite the June boost in retail sales, industry analysts
remained generally cautious about the outlook for consumer
spending, which accounts for about two-thirds of the nation's
economic activity.
   ``It's not a great environment, but things are better than they
were,'' said Linda Kristiansen, an analyst with the investment firm
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Walter Loeb, who tracks retailers for Morgan Stanley & Co.,
said, ``There was a modest increase in retail sales,'' as hot
weather gave consumers an impetus to buy summer clothing. Other
seasonal items, such as garden equipment and outdoor barbecues,
also sold well, analysts said.
   Sales were aided by the markdowns retailers continued to take to
clear their inventories, Loeb said.
   The analysts were watching closely for any effect on sales from
the Midwestern drought.
</TEXT>
