<HEAD>London Stocks Up 19.3 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were sharply higher Friday, helped by
a spate of rumors and renewed strength in the dollar.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 19.3
points, or 1 percent, at 1,874.8 at midday.
   Trading activity was brisk. Volume was 340.9 million shares by
midday compared with 277.3 million shares at the same time Thursday.
   The major gainer was British Aerospace PLC, which soared 32
pence, or 55 cents, to 437 pence in heavy trading on rumors the
Saudi Arabian government planned a substantial increase to its
orders of Tornado jet fighters.
   The rumors preceded a midday announcement by the British
Ministry of Defense that it had signed a major defense agreement
with Saudi Arabia involving the supply of aircraft and specialized
Navy vessels as well as a construction program in the Arab state.
   Elsewhere, international issues were higher on renewed strength
in the dollar while certain stocks were boosted by takeover
speculation.
   The market opened stronger, encouraged by Wall Street's recovery
from its worst levels on Thursday and by a rise in Tokyo earlier
Friday, dealers said.
