<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv11   07-08 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 11,0598</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday July 11</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dividends Struggle To Keep Up With Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Encouraged by brisk economic activity and strong
earnings growth, corporate America has lately been increasing the
dividends it pays at a stepped-up pace.
   But some Wall Street analysts argue that dividends have not been
growing fast enough to provide much support for a continuing
recovery in the stock market from last year's crash.
   The number of companies raising their dividends in June reached
106 this year, a 19 percent increase from 89 in the June 1987,
according to Standard & Poor's Corp.
   For the first six months of 1988, there were 893 increases,
compared with 863 in the like period last year and 829 in the first
half of 1986.
   Furthermore, says Arnold Kaufman, editor of S&P's investment
advisory publication The Outlook, the increases this year are
running larger than usual.
   Kaufman estimates that dividends paid by companies represented
in S&P's 500-stock composite index will grow 10 percent in 1988,
for the largest increase in recent years.
   That's all very nice, say some skeptics about stock-market
prospects, but it doesn't look so impressive when you consider the
competition stocks face from interest-bearing investments and the
possibility that the inflation rate might be picking up.
   As of early this month, the 30 stocks in the Dow Jones
industrial average had an aggregate yield of 3.5 percent.
   That is substantially higher than the levels below 3 percent
that prevailed last summer, when the market was headed for big
trouble. But it is still low by historical standards.
   A stock-market bull might well argue that dividends are just one
of many factors that influence stock prices, and a relatively minor
force at best. Certainly most stock investors are less
yield-conscious than people who put their money in bonds.
   A case can also be made that anticipation of future growth in
earnings and dividends can justify a relatively low current yield.
   Still, dividend yield has long been used as one primary
yardstick to measure whether stocks are cheap, fairly priced or
``overvalued.''
   And, of course, dividends are a component of the total return
professional money managers look for from their portfolios.
   In theory at least, stocks must pay their holders a premium in
their combined capital gains and dividends over the interest
payments available on high-grade bonds. Otherwise, why take the
extra risk that comes with stock investments.
   As reported in Barron's magazine, the interest yield on
top-grade corporate bonds stood recently at 9.44 percent _ 5.94
percentage points above the stock yield.
   That left the so-called stock-bond yield spread not very much
narrower than the gap of 6.43 percentage points that existed a year
ago.
   No single indicator like comparative yields can provide any
sure-fire answer to the future course of stock prices. However, the
pessimists warn that current stock yields don't provide much of a
cushion should inflation increase, interest rates go higher, or
both.
   The greater the stock-bond yield spread, they point out, the
more stocks would have to rise in price just to match the more
certain return available from bond interest payments.
   How to shrink the stock-bond spread? A decline in stock prices
would be one way. A lot of investors would prefer to see it
accomplished less painfully, perhaps by a combination of falling
interest rates and a continued rise in dividends.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday July 11</NOTE>
