<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was widely mixed today, faced
with news of unexpectedly strong employment growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up .18 to 2,122.87
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 301 up, 635
down and 470 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.15 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before the market opened, the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate fell three-tenths of a percentage point
last month, to a 14-year low of 5.3 percent.
   Nonfarm payroll employment, a figure watched especially closely
on Wall Street, increased by 346,000. That substantially exceeded
advance estimates in the financial community.
   While the news had many positive aspects, it also served as fuel
for recent fears among investors that inflation and interest rates
might rise as the economy heats up.
   Prices of long-term government bonds fell nearly $10 for each
$1,000 in face value after the employment report was made public.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose \ to 127~; Allied-Signal gained [ to 35{; General
Electric was unchanged at 44[, and Ford Motor dropped [ to 53].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.17 to 153.45. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .42 at 308.53.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 7.47 to
2,122.69.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 3 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 568 up, 845 down and 536 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 156.10 million shares, against 189.63 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
