<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NorthwestImage     07-08 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Image,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Wants to Know What Kind of Image it Has</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines wants to know what people
think of the beleaguered airline, so it's hired a consulting firm
to survey customers, employees and shareholders, a newspaper said
today.
   The Detroit News said it had obtained an internal Northwest memo
dated July 1 asking employees to share with management their
perception of the airline's identity, including ``the red tail, the
airline's name and logo and their reaction to changing these
identity elements.''
   Northwest spokesman Alan Muncaster said such surveys are
routine, that the airline is only evaluating its visual image.
   ``The Northwest logo and colors, or many of those elements, have
been around a long, long time,'' he said. ``We want to assure
ourselves that we're reflecting a contemporary airline, and are we
doing it the right way.''
   Employee questionnaires are due Monday at the San
Francisco-based Landor Associates Inc. Muncaster said results are
expected later this summer.
   ``If there's an overwhelming need to make changes, then, in all
likelihood, we would consider making those changes, but I don't
know when,'' he said.
   Alan Taylor, a senior vice president of Landor, said that in
addition to the employee questionnaires, his company would check
with customers and shareholders of NWA Inc., Northwest's parent
company.
   Taylor said Landor has done similar work for Mercedes-Benz,
General Electric Co., Coca-Cola Co. and about 30 other airlines.
   During the past couple of years, Northwest has weathered labor
problems, disappointing on-time statistics and increased consumer
complaints. Last August, Northwest Flight 255 crashed on takeoff
from Detroit, killing 156 people. The company was criticized on
several fronts for refusing to release a passenger list from that
crash.
</TEXT>
