<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PCConnection Adv11   07-08 0975</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PC Connection, Adv 11,1005</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday July 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fast-Growing Company In Unlikely Setting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARLOW, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coming down the rural road off Pitcher
Mountain onto state Route 10 into Marlow, population 551, PC
Connection is easy to find, but hard to believe.
   What is one of the nation's fastest-growing companies _ purveyor
of mail-order computer software and accessories _ doing in a place
like this?
   The general store, Vic's Lunch and the statue of a soldier in
the center of town are within walking distance. Employees can fish
_ in season, of course _ on their lunch hour in the Ashuelot River
running alongside the modest, two-story frame building. The worst
traffic comes from mosquitoes and black flies.
   Far away are the glitzy, high-tech worlds of Silicon Valley in
California and Route 128 outside Boston.
   But to hear Pat Gallup talk, rural New Hampshire is the perfect
setting for a company with a raccoon for a logo, a historian on the
staff and 18,000 corporate accounts. And why should anyone be
surprised that at age 34, with a background in archeology, she is
president of a company that grossed $60 million in 1986, and an
estimated $100 million in 1987.
   Gallup and David Hall, 39, co-founder and chief executive
officer, were in the right place at the right time with the right
idea when they started PC Connection in 1982 and grossed $233,000.
   ``We were the first to specialize in PC products and service,''
Gallup said.
   Receipts reached $8 million in 1983 and have kept growing.
   Last December, Inc Magazine listed PC Connection as the second
fastest-growing firm in the country in 1986. Also last December, a
PC Magazine survey of companies and individuals making mail-order
purchases gave PC Connection better ratings for service, prices and
reputation than any other mail-order company.
   For example, salespeople handling telephones are all college
graduates working on salary _ no commission, no pressure selling _
and all are trained to understand the products, Gallup says.
   Order a product from PC Connection before 8 p.m. and it will
arrive the next day. The shipping charge is $3 regardless of
destination.
   And with every hard disk drive, the customer gets a 90-minute
videotape with 15 minutes of instruction, 75 minutes blank. ``We
tell them to erase the tape when they're finished and use it for a
movie,'' Gallup said.
   Peter Haas, director of customer affairs, has been with the
company for five years. He says many of the company's ideas are
based on bad experiences with other companies.
   ``A lot of our competitors think price alone and sell short on
service,'' Haas said.
   The emphasis on detail is expensive, he says, but it pays off in
reorders from satisfied customers.
   The company's distinctive tastes extend to its physical plant.
In addition to expanding its 50,000-square-foot headquarters at a
cost of $500,000, the company has undertaken a $1 million
renovation of the historic, 155-year-old Christmas Tree Inn across
Route 10 and has invested $1.5 million in a video studio in Newport.
   When it opens next year, the inn will be a retail showroom and a
training facility for businesses to acquaint themselves with PC
Connection products. The studio will produce videos that can be
transmitted by satellite directly to corporations for training.
   Neither studio nor inn are expected to produce revenue; instead,
they are designed to enhance product support for PC Connection
customers.
   With her interest in archeology, Gallup hired a historian to
make certain that renovations to the 13,000-square-foot Victorian
inn conform with the way the inn looked at the turn of the century.
   All these unusual undertakings started with a chance meeting of
two backpackers at Bishbash Falls on the Appalachian Trail in 1975.
Gallup, of Mansfield, Conn., was at the University of Connecticut.
Hall, a chemical engineering major from the University of New
Hampshire whose family moved from New York to Gilsum, N.H., in the
1960s, was working in the family business making broadcasting and
recording equipment.
   Gallup worked in archeology for a few years after college before
Hall persuaded her to come to Gilsum to work in personnel, public
relations and advertising in the audio shop, which was moved to
Marlow in 1980.
   They got interested in personal computers, but had difficulty
getting up-to-date information in the fast-growing industry.
   ``We saw the need to put all the information and the product in
one place,'' Gallup said.
   Operating out of the audio shop, they started up in 1982 needing
only some phone lines and United Parcel Service. The biggest
expense was advertising _ one-ninth of a page in Byte magazine in
February 1982.
   ``The phone didn't ring for three days, and we sat looking at
each other,'' Gallup recalled. Then it started, and never stopped.
   ``We did everything _ took calls, placed orders, packed boxes.
When we were in business a year we knew it would require 100
percent of our attention.''
   They left the audio business to Hall's family, hired eight more
people _ they now employ 185 _ and rented space at the inn. Before
long, the phone company had to upgrade the lines to Keene _ the
largest nearby community _ to carry the extra traffic.
   The company's advertising now stresses its off-the-beaten-track,
Marlow connection.
   ``We play up Marlow in the ads,'' Gallup said. ``We're not just
another company from California, and maybe people feel a little
more comfortable than if we were operating out of a warehouse in
Hoboken.''
   While Marlow provides PC Connection with a New England heritage,
the company has provided the town with jobs, taxes and a $6,000
computer system for town records and the school. And when the
wooden flagpole blew over, the company gave the town a new
fiberglass one.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday July 11</NOTE>
