<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybeans Open Mixed In Cautious Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed in slow,
cautious trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Many analysts were confused by Thursday's sharp declines in the
face of mostly bullish signals, and traders appeared unwilling to
take a gamble on the weekend weather.
   Scattered showers forecast for Minnesota, Wisconsin and northern
Iowa today were expected to reach Illinois, Indiana and Ohio by
Sunday, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in Chicago.
   But the rains were expected to be light, the long-range outlook
remained hot and dry and Lespinasse wasn't making any predictions
about the market's performance.
   ``The market is perplexing,'' he said. ``It's inexplicable why
we went down so hard when there isn't that much rain around and the
temperatures are very hot. Maybe the market knows something we
don't.''
   Some oat futures opened down the 15-cents-a-bushel limit for
daily trading. Corn was lower, soybeans were mixed and wheat was
higher.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 4{ cents higher with July
at $3.81 a bushel; corn was 5\ cents lower to { cent higher with
July at $3.20{ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 15 cents lower with
July at $2.98 a bushel; soybeans were 13{ cents lower to 9{ cents
higher with July at $9.44 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .35 cent lower to .08 cent higher with August
at 64.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .13
cent higher with August at 74.65 cents a pound; hogs were .80 cent
lower to .15 cent higher with July at 45.55 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to 1 cent lower with July at
33.80 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
