<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0005 07-08 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0005,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Slip Following Surge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with midday trading. Picks up
5th graf pvs, Prices rose ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures retreated today in the wake of
Thursday's sharp advance that was sparked by confusion over a rig
explosion in the North Sea and speculation over the chances for an
emergency OPEC meeting.
   By midday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for
August delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude oil fell 27 cents
to $15.56 per 42-gallon barrel after closing 47 cents higher on
Thursday. The contract had traded as high as $16.35 per barrel
during that session.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange today, unleaded
gasoline was off 0.17 cent a gallon at 52.95 cents after settling
2.56 cents higher on Thursday.
   Home heating oil, which advanced 1.68 cents a gallon to 44.29
cents in the previous session, slipped 0.59 cent to 43.70 cents.
   Peter Beutel, an oil analyst with Elders Futures Inc., said
today's price decline was the result of some profit-taking and a
general correction from Thursday's overbought condition.
   ``It may be a case of calmer heads prevailing today,'' he said.
``I think a lot of people felt it was overdone.''
   On Thursday, the news of an oil rig explosion off the coast of
Scotland ``was the beginning reason for hysteria'' in the oil
futures markets, said John O'Connell, senior energy analyst at
Refco Inc.
   Prices rose sharply as traders reacted to reports that the
explosion would affect about 12 percent of total North Sea
production, or as much as 300,000 barrels of oil per day.
   ``That sounds very, very impressive, but it's really
insignificant _ it's a very small amount of world production,'' and
crude contracts began to ease once traders put the incident into
perspective, O'Connell said.
   Gasoline prices rose sharply following a report by the American
Petroleum Institute late Wednesday that U.S. inventories of
unleaded gasoline declined by 5 million barrels in the previous
week.
   Bob Baker, senior energy analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., attributed the decline to higher consumption coupled with
refinery problems that have reduced production.
   Analysts also said the market had some left-over nervousness
from Wednesday's report that three members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting countries might request an emergency meeting of
the cartel.
   The Kuwaiti news agency quoted unidentified sources as saying
officials from Venezuela, Algeria and Ecuador wanted OPEC to
consider ways of cutting production and propping up prices.
   The report ``continued to be denied, and by late afternoon
(Thursday) these hopes had faded and people were becoming more
realistic,'' O'Connell said.
   Baker said the request for an OPEC meeting ``doesn't have broad
sponsorship at all.
   ``They'll only face the same issues they were unable to resolve
at the last meeting,'' he said, referring to last month's meeting
of the 13-nation cartel in Vienna, Austria, where oil ministers
left the existing system of production quotas and prices intact.
   Most OPEC members are thought to be producing above their
individual quotas or discounting their prices. Some estimates put
OPEC production at 3.5 million barrels above the group's
self-imposed overall ceiling of 15.06 million barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
