<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-AirTraffic     07-08 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Air Traffic,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Parliament Calls for Action to Ease Airport Delays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Parliament has urged
quick action by European Economic Community executives to resolve
what it called a worsening problem of flight delays and airliner
near-misses.
   Among the parliament's recommendations was that Eurocontrol, the
10-nation body which monitors flights in Western Europe, be made
part of the EEC, which currently has no formal authority in this
area.
   Airline traffic in Western Europe has grown much faster than
expected in recent years, and a resolution adopted by the
parliament late Thursday said traffic growth is likely to
accelerate as the EEC deregulates the commercial airline industry
in the next several years.
   The resolution said over-congested airspace and limited airport
capacity had led to delays ``not only causing major inconvenience
to passengers but also reducing safety.''
   The parliamentarians sharply criticized both the EEC executive
Commission and national civil aviation authorities for a ``lack of
will'' to create a single system for air traffic control for the
12-nation trading bloc.
   Many of the flight delays result from the fact that 11 different
air traffic-control centers in the EEC are equipped with
incompatible computers, the resolution said.
   George Anastassopoulos, chairman of the parliament's transport
committee, told a news conference that ``the skies cannot be
divided'' in this way. He noted that the EEC planned to dismantle
all barriers to the free movement of people, goods, services and
capital by the end of 1992.
   He blamed the problem on ``misplaced sensitivities about
sovereignty,'' citing Britain and unspecified Scandinavian
countries as notable culprits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
