<1ST_LINE>r f AM-May-LoehmannSale     07-08 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-May-Loehmann Sale,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>May Selling Loehmann's Division to Investor Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co. said Friday it had
signed an agreement in principle to sell its Loehmann's specialty
store chain to a group of investors.
   The group is led by Sefinco Ltd., an affiliate of Entrecanales y
Tavora, an international construction and engineering company based
in Madrid and by the Sprout Group, a division of Donaldson, Lufkin
& Jenrette Securities Corp.
   The purchase price was not disclosed.
   Loehmann's is a specialty store chain featuring quality
off-price women's apparel. Headquartered in New York, it operates
77 stores in 25 states. It had sales of $334 million in 1987.
   Thomas Tashjian, a retail industry analyst with Seidler Amdec
Securities Inc. in Los Angeles, said the sale of Loehmann's was not
a surprise.
   ``It didn't really fit with the rest of the company,'' he said,
adding that May would prefer to concentrate on its larger
divisions, including its department stores and discount stores.
   May, the nation's seventh-largest retailer, owns department
stores including Lord & Taylor, Hecht's, Filene's, Foley's and
Famous Barr. Its discount stores include Caldor and Venture.
   Loeshmann's management team will continue to run the business,
according to a news release from May.
   The transaction is expected to be completed by the end of August.

</TEXT>
