<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-08 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Grain, Soybean Futures Close Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybeans futures prices closed
sharply lower for the second consecutive session Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade, stumping many analysts who saw mostly
bullish signs ahead.
   Some corn contracts and most oat contracts fell their
15-cents-a-bushel limit for daily trading, and the contract for
November delivery of soybeans plunged nearly the 45-cent limit for
that market. Wheat futures were mixed.
   Some private forecasters said chances had improved for weekend
showers in Illinois and Iowa, but chances had fallen for rain in
Indiana and Ohio on the belt's parched eastern edge.
   ``You'd think one would offset the other but it didn't turn out
that way,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   The selling was led by independent traders and hedgers, and may
simply have represented profit-taking ahead of the weekend,
analysts said.
   Many private projections for 1988 corn and soybean production
were released in advance of the Agriculture Department's official
report, which is due on Tuesday. But the estimates varied widely.
   ``I don't know how to explain it,'' Lespinasse said of the sharp
drop in prices. ``I'm at a loss for words and so are most other
people.''
   At the close, wheat was 5 cents lower to 8{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.80 a bushel; corn was 1{
cents to 15 cents lower with July at $3.09 a bushel; oats were 8
cents to 15 cents lower with July at $2.93 a bushel; soybeans were
42{ cents lower to 7 cents higher with July at $9.24 a bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
