<1ST_LINE>u f AM-USG-DesertPartners Bjt   07-08 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USG-Desert Partners, Bjt,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restructuring Plan Increasing USG Debt Four-Fold Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restructuring plan that will increase USG
Corp.'s debt four-fold _ the legacy of the company's costly victory
in a takeover battle with Desert Partners L.P. _ was overwhelmingly
approved Friday by shareholders.
   Approval by 94 percent of the shareholders who cast votes
``indicates support for USG's continued existence as an independent
company run by current management,'' Chairman Robert Day said after
balloting was complete.
   A total of 51.8 million shares _ 70 percent of the outstanding
stock _ was represented in the vote.
   The restructuring plan, made necessary when the Chicago-based
building supply conglomerate's management rebuffed a takeover bid
by Desert Partners of Midland, Texas, will boost the company's debt
load to $3.1 billion from $800 million.
   Under the plan, shareholders of record by next Tuesday will be
entitled to $37 in cash, $5 in securities and one new share of
common stock for each common share they currently own.
   ``USG has historically carried a modest level of debt, and while
that is our preference, present circumstances require that we
provide an immediate return to shareholders,'' said Day. ``We
intend to reduce our debt load as rapidly as possible and are in a
strong position to do so.''
   Virtually all of the 20-minute comment period Friday on motions
affecting shareholders was devoted to the recapitalization.
   ``Many said they'd made a lot of money in the past and were
happy with the way things were,'' said Thomas Sleeter, manager of
investor relations. ``They didn't wany anybody to tamper.''
   The company's stock price had doubled over the past five years,
and was trading above $50 per share before October's market crash.
When Desert Partners launched its $42-per-share offer in March, USG
was trading below $30.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, USG was up 62{ cents
a share at $49 by late afternoon.
   Day and USG's current management won the bitter, protracted
takeover battle, but he acknowledged in an interview Thursday that
the price was a recapitalization that will inhibit USG's growth and
restrict its resources for several years.
   ``There are no winners in this. We're going into very heavy
leverage, and that has its negatives,'' Day said Thursday. ``We
don't feel we lost, but the whole process isn't one that gives us a
great deal of satisfaction, either.''
   As a result of the restructuring, an unspecified number of jobs
will be lost. Already, the work force has been cut 9 percent this
year, Day said.
   Two companies will be sold, reversing a trend that saw USG
acquire five companies in 1987.
   ``It will restrict our ability to pay dividends, to commit
capital to capital investments, and reduce our research and
development program. And these latter two, in particular, are the
things which provide growth for the future,'' Day said.
   He said the recapitalization was the only why to satisfy USG's
loyal, long-term investors and the newcomers who moved in on the
heels of Desert Partners.
   But he admitted he regrets the restructuring was necessary.
   ``I'm not bitter, but I am sorry,'' Day said. ``It's been very
costly, disruptive and demoralizing. So it's pretty hard to find
anything to feel good about.''
</TEXT>
