<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankBid     07-08 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Grants Bank of NY Extension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Friday gave the
Bank of New York Co. another 60-day extension to persue its hostile
bid for rival Irving Bank Corp., but the regulators also expressed
uneasiness the takeover attempt has entered its 10th month.
   The Fed indicated it was concerned about the costs associated
with the long-standing battle and urged both parties to bring it to
a prompt conclusion.
   ``It is the expressed desire of the board that the parties avoid
further delay and take all steps necessary to bring the pending
proceedings to a prompt conclusion,'' the Fed said in approving
Bank of New York's request for an extension.
   The Fed's extension until Sept. 7 was the second for the Bank of
New York since regulators gave the company conditional approval to
proceed with its takeover plans in February. The first extension
was scheduled to run out Saturday.
   Bank of New York first announced its merger proposal in
September, but all subsequent offers have been steadfastly turned
down by Irving.
   Irving management instead favors a friendly merger with the
state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second largest
bank.
   Bank of New York, which owns a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of
Irving's 18.5 million common shares outstanding. The offer is
valued at around $68 a share, or $1.2 billion.
   The Milan-based Banca Commerciale is offering $80 a share for 51
percent of Irving's outstanding shares and a special $10-a-share
dividend for the remaining 49 percent.
   It recently sweetened the offer to include warrants entitling
shareholders to buy newly issued Irving stock at $65 a share over
the next seven years. Stockholders would receive one warrant for
every four shares they currently owned.
   Robert A. Falise said Irving was disappointed with the Fed's
decision.
   ``The Federal Reserve Board's action ... is contrary to the best
interest of both banking institutions,'' he said.
   The Fed's decision came two days after a New York state judge
struck down a provison of Irving's anti-takeover ``poison pill''
that was designed to thwart the Bank of New York.
</TEXT>
