<FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SingerDivestment     07-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singer Divestment,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer Sells Two Divisions For $570 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Singer Co. announced plans Friday to
sell its vocational and military training divisions to separate
companies for a total of $570 million as part of a previously
disclosed divestment program.
   Integrated Resources Acquisition Inc. will acquire the Education
Division, known as Career Systems Development, for $20 million. The
division, a major operator of Job Corps vocational training centers
for the Department of Labor, is headquartered in Rochester, N.Y.
   CAE Industries Ltd. of Toronto will acquire Singer's Link
Domestic Simulation and Training Systems Division for $550 million.
   The division is the leading supplier of military simulation
systems and training services to the Army, Navy, Air Force and the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   Its headquarters are in Binghamton, N.Y., but it also has
facilities in Houston; Dallas; Sunnyvale, Calif.; Silver Springs,
Md.; and Alexandria, Va.
   CAE is a publicly traded holding and management company with
seven operating divisions across Canada and one in West Germany. It
is engaged in electronics, aerospace and industrial products
manufacturing and services.
   The Singer divisions are the second and third to be sold since
the company was acquired earlier this year by a partnership headed
by investor Paul A. Bilzerian. In making the acquisition, Bilzerian
said at least part of the company's operations would be divested.
   Ryobi Limited of Tokyo, Japan, announced Tuesday it would buy
Singer's motor products division for $325 million.
   Company officials said they expect the sale of the Education
Division to be completed in August. The closing date for the Link
sale depends on regulatory approvals.
   David H. Race, president and chief executive officer of CAE,
said Link and CAE ``are the ideal fit.'' He said CAE intends to
operate Link as an autonomous business unit in its present form.
   ``The combination of technical, manufacturing and financial
resources resulting from this agreement will enhance the ability of
both CAE and Link to serve their customers,'' he said in a joint
statement with Bilzerian.
   Both companies develop and design simulation systems for
fixed-wing aircraft and helicopters and share expertise in
shipboard machinery control systems, nuclear submarine simulators
and control systems for utilities.
   A total of 7,500 people work for Link, which has annual revenues
of approximately $550 million. CAE employes 4,200 people and had
revenues of $283 million for the fiscal year ended March 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
