<HEAD>Former Bank of Boston Vice President Accused Of Fraud</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 3 new grafs after penultimate graf with more reaction
from bank spokesman; picks up final graf pvs bg'ng, Buteau's trial
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Bank of Boston Corp. vice president
appeared in court Friday on charges of conspiring to defraud the
bank of 15 million pounds, or around $25.5 million.
   Detectives from a special task force known as the Serious Fraud
Squad arrested Max Buteau, 39, on Wednesday, the day before he was
to go to his native Haiti.
   His request to be released on bail was turned down during his
court appearance on the grounds that he might attempt escape.
   Buteau, who lives in west London, resigned last month from the
bank's branch at Victoria in central London.
   During the seven-minute court session Friday, prosecutor Robert
Wardle said Buteau had been issuing false guarantees of payment on
behalf of the bank's London branch so that alleged co-conspirator
Tina Jeffe, a French doctor turned financial consultant, could
attract domestic and foreign corporations into her investment
business.
   Ms. Jeffe, 40, has fled Britain, Wardle said, leaving behind a
Bank of Boston account with a 300,000 pound, or $510,000, deficit.
   Wardle told the court that Buteau ``had no authority to issue
those letters, and concealed this from the bank.''
   Defense lawyer Stephanie Nedas said her client ``vigorously
denied the charge.''
   Bank of Boston spokesman Wayne Taylor said the U.S. bank was
cooperating with the investigation.
   Taylor denied reports that the bank had already begun making
payments to parties allegedly affected in the case.
   The spokesman said the bank does not expect significant earnings
losses due to any possible payments associated with the case.
   ``Any loss, should it occur, is expected to be substantially
less than the figure mentioned in the press reports out of
London,'' said Taylor. ``We also believe such payments would be
covered by present reserves and-or insurance.''
   Buteau's trial is scheduled to begin Wednesday.
</TEXT>
