<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Ecuador-Debt     07-08 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Debt,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspends Negotiations on Resuming Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday scrapped
negotiations aimed at resuming payments on its $9.2 billion foreign
debt, attributing the decision to lack of money.
   ``It is prudent to suspend renegotiations without setting a
renewal date,'' Finance Minister Eduardo Cabezas told a news
conference.
   He said falling prices for oil, from accounts for about 60
percent of Ecuador's income, and a shortage of foreign credit were
important considerations in its decision.
   The government of President Leon Febres Cordero suspended
payments on Ecuador's debt in March 1987, after a series of
earthquakes wreaked widespread destruction and severed a major oil
pipeline, paralyzing the oil export industry for six months.
   Cabezas said the the country's economic situation has worsened
this year and that recent presidential elections had caused a drop
in foreign exchange remittances, but he did not elaborate.
   Social Democrat Rodrigo Borja replaces conservative Febres
Cordero in August. Borja defeated populist Abdala Bucaram in May
following a heated campaign that incited frequent rumors of a
military coup.
   Cabezas said the government had based its budget on oil income
at $17.25 a barrel but has only been receiving $13.
   A plan to receive $350 million in loans from foreign banks had
also fallen through, further crippling the country's ability to
pay, he said.
</TEXT>
