<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Beef     07-08 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Beef,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: South Korea To Lift Ban On Beef Imports Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has decided to lift its
ban on beef imports and plans to order 15,000 tons of foreign beef
next week, the Yonhap News Agency reported Friday.
   Government officials declined to comment on the report, but said
an annoucement could be expected soon.
   Yonhap said no objections were raised on the floor of the
National Assembly to the proposed lifting of the ban when Deputy
Prime Minister Rha Woong-bae told the legislature Thursday that
Korea would suffer retaliation if it continued resisting U.S.
pressure to lift the ban.
   Rha noted the United States had complained to the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade that the Korean beef import ban
violates fair trade practice. Rha said GATT was certain to rule
that Korea should immediately lift the ban, and if Korea did not do
so it would face legal retaliation from the United States and other
GATT memebrs.
   The government of President Roh Tae-woo originally planned to
lift the ban earlier this year but delayed action in the face of
strong domestic resistance.
   South Korea plans to buy just 15,000 tons of beef this year.
   Yonhap quoted officials as saying the tonnage to be ordered next
week included 5,000 tons of high quality beef to be imported from
the United States for use at hotels.
   The remaining 10,000 tons of beef of ordinary quality will be
for sales to the public and will be purchased through international
bidding to be conducted by a government-designated livestock
product distribution agency, Yonhap said.
   The officials were quoted as saying American and Australian
suppliers were expected to take part in the bidding next week.
</TEXT>
